question:
Calculate the volume in $\mathrm{cm}^{3}$ of 16.0 moldm ${ }^{-3}$ ethanoic acid needed to prepare $500 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of $2.50 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$
solution of the acid.
answer:
Use the expression; $M_{1} V_{1}=M_{2} V_{2} ;$ where
$\mathrm{M}_{1}=16.0 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3} ; \mathrm{V}_{1}=? ; \mathrm{M}_{2}=2.50 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3} ; \mathrm{V}_{2}=500 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$.
The volume of the acid needed, $\mathrm{V}_{1}=\frac{2.50 \times 500}{16.0}=78.1 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$
subject: Chemistry

question:
Calculate the mass in grams of ethanedioic acid dihydrate needed to prepare $200 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of $0.700 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$
solution. $\mathrm{O}=16.0 ; \mathrm{C}=12.0 ; \mathrm{H}=1.00$.
answer:
Ethanedioic acid $\quad=\quad \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{C}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{4} \cdot 2 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}=2.00+24.0+64.0+36.0 \quad 126$
Mass of the acid needed to prepare $1.00 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ of a $0.700 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$ solution $=126^{*} 0.700=88.2 \mathrm{~g}$
$\therefore$ Mass needed to prepare $200 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of 0.700 moldm $^{-3}=0.200 * 88.2=17.6 \mathrm{~g}$
subject: Chemistry

question: Calculate the final concentration of $\mathrm{HCl}$ in moldm ${ }^{-3}$ when $150 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of $6.00 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3} \mathrm{HCl}$ are diluted with 250 $\mathrm{cm}^{3}$ of de-ionised water and $100 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of this solution, further diluted to $300 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$.
answer:
$1^{\text {st }}$ Dilution: $150 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ to $400 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} ; \quad$ Dilution factor $\quad=\quad$ in 8
$2^{\text {nd }}$ Dilution: $100 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ to $300 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$; Dilution factor $\quad=1$ in 3
Total dilution factor $=\frac{3}{8} \times \frac{1}{3}=\frac{1}{8}$
Final concentration $=\frac{6.00}{8.00}=0.750$ moldm $^{-3}$
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text:
Each school will be presented with two half-cells with their corresponding electrode potentials.
Give the balanced equation for the cell reaction of a voltaic cell that can be set up with the halfcells. Give the maximum initial emf of the cell.
question: $\mathrm{Zn}(\mathrm{CN})_{4^{2-}}, \mathrm{CN} / \mathrm{Zn}, \quad-1.26 \mathrm{~V} ; \mathrm{Au}^{3+} / \mathrm{Au} \quad \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{Au}, \quad 1.42 \mathrm{~V}$
answer:
Oxidation: $\mathrm{Zn}-2 \mathrm{e}+4 \mathrm{CN}^{-} \rightarrow \mathrm{Zn}(\mathrm{CN})_{4^{2-}} \quad 1.26 \mathrm{~V}$.... (1)
Reduction: $\mathrm{Au}^{3+}+3 \mathrm{e} \rightarrow \mathrm{Au} \quad 1.42 \mathrm{~V}$
Multiply (1) by 3 and (2) by 2 and add.
Cell reaction: $\quad 3 \mathrm{Zn}+12 \mathrm{CN}^{-}+2 \mathrm{Au}^{3+} \rightarrow 3 \mathrm{Zn}(\mathrm{CN})_{4^{2-}}+2 \mathrm{Au}$
$\mathrm{Emf}=1.26+1.42=2.68 \mathrm{~V}$
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text:
Each school will be presented with two half-cells with their corresponding electrode potentials.
Give the balanced equation for the cell reaction of a voltaic cell that can be set up with the halfcells. Give the maximum initial emf of the cell.
question: $\mathrm{Al}^{3+} / \mathrm{Al}-1.71 \mathrm{~V} ; \quad \mathrm{SO}_{4}{ }^{2-}, \mathrm{SO}_{3}{ }^{2-}, \mathrm{OH} / \mathrm{Pt} \quad-0.920 \mathrm{~V}$.
answer:
Oxidation: $\mathrm{Al} \quad-\quad 3 \mathrm{e} \quad \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{Al}^{3+}$; Reduction: $\mathrm{SO}_{4}{ }^{2-}+2 \mathrm{e}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O} \rightarrow \mathrm{SO}_{3}{ }^{2-}+2 \mathrm{OH} ;-0.920 \mathrm{~V} \ldots$ (2)
Multiply (1) by 2 and (2) by 3 and add
Hence, Cell Reaction: $2 \mathrm{Al}+3 \mathrm{SO}_{4}{ }^{2-}+3 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O} \rightarrow 2 \mathrm{Al}^{3+}+3 \mathrm{SO}_{3}{ }^{2-}+6 \mathrm{OH}$
Emf $\quad=\quad 1.71-0.920=+0.790 \mathrm{~V}$
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text:
Each school will be presented with two half-cells with their corresponding electrode potentials.
Give the balanced equation for the cell reaction of a voltaic cell that can be set up with the halfcells. Give the maximum initial emf of the cell.
question: $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{2}, \mathrm{OH}^{-} / \mathrm{Pt} \quad 0.880 \mathrm{~V} ; \quad \mathrm{HNO}_{2}, \mathrm{~N}_{2} \mathrm{O}, \mathrm{H}^{+} / \mathrm{Pt} \quad 1.27 \mathrm{~V}$.
answer:
Oxidation: $2 \mathrm{OH}^{-}-\quad 2 \mathrm{e} \quad \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{2} \quad-0.880 \mathrm{~V} \ldots$ (1)
Reduction: $2 \mathrm{HNO}_{2}+4 \mathrm{e}+4 \mathrm{H}^{+} \rightarrow \mathrm{N}_{2} \mathrm{O}+3 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}+1.27 \mathrm{~V} \ldots$ (2)
Multiply (1) by 2 and add to (2)
Hence, Cell Reaction:
$\left(2 \mathrm{HNO}_{2}+4 \mathrm{OH}^{-}+4 \mathrm{H}^{+} \rightarrow 2 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{2}+\mathrm{N}_{2} \mathrm{O}+3 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)$
$2 \mathrm{HNO}_{2}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O} \rightarrow 2 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{2}+\mathrm{N}_{2} \mathrm{O} \quad$ (Correct equation)
Emf $\quad=(1.27-0.880) \mathrm{V}=0.390 \mathrm{~V}$
subject: Chemistry

question: A version of Graham's Law of Diffusion states that the rate of diffusion of a gas at constant temperature and pressure is indirectly proportional to the square root of the density of the gas. Explain why the rate of diffusion can also to be indirectly proportional to the square root of the molar mass of the gas.
answer:
Equal volumes of different gases contain the same number of particles. Therefore, moles per unit volume at a given temperature and pressure is constant. Hence the densities of gases are directly proportional to their molar masses.
[ALTERNATIVELY, density $=\frac{\text { mass }}{V}$, But mass $=$ molar mass $*$ number of moles Density $=\left(\frac{\text { number of moles }}{V}\right) *$ Molar mass, But for different gases $\quad\left(\frac{\text { number of moles }}{V} \right.$ is constant, $\quad$ Hence Density $\propto$ Molar mass ]
subject: Chemistry

subject: Chemistry

question: At low temperatures or high pressures real gases deviate from the ideal gas behavior, why?
answer: At high pressures gases occupy low volumes; the volumes occupied by the gaseous particles are no longer negligible. At low temperatures and high pressures, the gaseous molecules are close to one another and intermolecular forces of attraction and repulsion affect the actual pressures.

preamble_text:
The Ostwald Process is a commercial method for the manufacture of trioxonitrate(V) acid by catalytic oxidation of ammonia. The balanced equations for the steps involved are as follows:
(1) $4 \mathrm{NH}_{3(\mathrm{~g})}+5 \mathrm{O}_{2(\mathrm{~g})} \rightarrow \quad 4 \mathrm{NO}_{(\mathrm{g})}+6 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{(\mathrm{g})}$
(2) $2 \mathrm{NO}_{(\mathrm{g})}+\quad \mathrm{O}_{2(\mathrm{~g})} \rightarrow \quad 2 \mathrm{NO}_{2(\mathrm{~g})}$
(3) $3 \mathrm{NO}_{2(\mathrm{~g})}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{(\mathrm{l})} \rightarrow \quad 2 \mathrm{HNO}_{3(\mathrm{aq})}+\quad \mathrm{NO}_{(\mathrm{g})}$
$\mathrm{O}=16.0 ; \mathrm{N}=14.0 ; \mathrm{H}=1.00$
question: Calculate the total mass of oxygen needed to convert $17.0 \mathrm{~kg}$ of $\mathrm{NH}_{3}$ gas to the stoichiometric amount of $\mathrm{HNO}_{3}$.
answer:
In Reaction (1) $\frac{5}{4}$ mole of $\mathrm{O}_{2}$ is needed to oxidisel mole of $\mathrm{NH}_{3}$ to a mole of $\mathrm{NO}$ In Reaction (2) $\quad \frac{1}{2}$ mole of $\mathrm{O}_{2}$ is needed to oxidize 1 mole of $\mathrm{NO}$ to $\mathrm{NO}_{2}$
Hence total moles of $\mathrm{O}_{2}$ needed for 1 mole $\mathrm{NH}_{3}=\left(\frac{5}{4}+\frac{1}{2}\right)=\frac{7}{4}=1.75$
$\therefore$ moles of $\mathrm{O}_{2}$ needed for the conversion of $1.00 * 10^{3}$ mole of $\mathrm{NH}_{3}=\quad 1.75^{*} 10^{3}$ mole
Mass in $\mathrm{kg}$ of $\mathrm{O}_{2}=1.75^{*} 32.0 \mathrm{~kg}=56.0 \mathrm{~kg}$
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text:
The Ostwald Process is a commercial method for the manufacture of trioxonitrate(V) acid by catalytic oxidation of ammonia. The balanced equations for the steps involved are as follows:
(1) $4 \mathrm{NH}_{3(\mathrm{~g})}+5 \mathrm{O}_{2(\mathrm{~g})} \rightarrow \quad 4 \mathrm{NO}_{(\mathrm{g})}+6 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{(\mathrm{g})}$
(2) $2 \mathrm{NO}_{(\mathrm{g})}+\quad \mathrm{O}_{2(\mathrm{~g})} \rightarrow \quad 2 \mathrm{NO}_{2(\mathrm{~g})}$
(3) $3 \mathrm{NO}_{2(\mathrm{~g})}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{(\mathrm{l})} \rightarrow \quad 2 \mathrm{HNO}_{3(\mathrm{aq})}+\quad \mathrm{NO}_{(\mathrm{g})}$
$\mathrm{O}=16.0 ; \mathrm{N}=14.0 ; \mathrm{H}=1.00$
question: Calculate the net amount of water consumed or produced during the conversion of $17.0 \mathrm{~kg}_{\mathrm{g}}$ of $\mathrm{NH}_{3}$ to the stoichiometric amount of $\mathrm{HNO}_{3}$. You should state if the water is consumed or produced.
answer:
In Reaction (1) 1 mole of $\mathrm{NH}_{3}$ gas will produce $\frac{6}{4}$ or 1.50 mole of $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$
In Reaction (3) 1 mole of $\mathrm{NO}_{2}$ will consume $\frac{1}{3}$ or 0.333 mole of $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$
Hence the net amount of water produced $=\quad 1.50-0.333\left[\right.$ or $\left.\frac{6}{4}-\frac{1}{3}\right] \quad=1.17\left[\right.$ or $\left.\frac{7}{6}\right] \mathrm{mole}$
Hence mass of $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$ in $\mathrm{kg}$ produced $=(1.17$ [or $\left.7 / 6]\right)^{*} 18=21.1 \mathrm{~kg}$ or $[21.0 \mathrm{~kg}]$
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text: Find the constant term in the expansion of the given binomial. You may leave answer in the form $n C_{r} a^{r} b^{s}$
question: $\left(3 x^{2}+2 / x\right)^{6}$
answer: $6 C_{2} 3^{2} 2^{4} \quad\left[6 C_{r}\left(3 x^{2}\right)^{r}(2 / x)^{6-r}=6 C_{r} 3^{r} 2^{6-r} x^{3 r-6}\right.$, for constant term $3 r-6=0, r=2$, hence constant term is $\left.6 C_{2} 3^{2} 2^{4}\right]$
subject: Mathematics

preamble_text: Find the constant term in the expansion of the given binomial. You may leave answer in the form $n C_{r} a^{r} b^{s}$
question: $\left(2 x+1 / 3 x^{2}\right)^{9}$
answer: $9 C_{6}\left(2^{6} / 3^{3}\right)$ or $9 C_{3} 2^{6} 3^{-3} \quad\left[9 C_{r}(2 x)^{r}\left(1 / 3 x^{2}\right)^{9-r}=9 C_{r} 2^{r} 3^{r-9} x^{3 r-18}, 3 r-18=0\right.$, $r=6$, hence for constant term $\left.9 C_{6}\left(2^{6} / 3^{3}\right)\right]$
subject: Mathematics

preamble_text: Find the constant term in the expansion of the given binomial. You may leave answer in the form $n C_{r} a^{r} b^{s}$
question: $\left(5 x^{2}+1 / 2 x^{2}\right)^{8}$
answer: $8 C_{4}\left(5^{4} / 2^{4}\right)$ or $8 C_{4} 5^{4} 2^{-4} \quad\left[8 C_{r}\left(5 x^{2}\right)^{\mathrm{r}}\left(1 / 2 x^{2}\right)^{8-\mathrm{r}}=8 \mathrm{C}_{\mathrm{r}} 5^{\mathrm{r}} 2^{\mathrm{r}-8} \mathrm{x}^{4 \mathrm{r}-16}, 4 \mathrm{r}-16=0\right.$, $\mathrm{r}=4$, hence constant term $\left.=8 \mathrm{C}_{4}\left(5^{4} / 2^{4}\right)\right]$
subject: Mathematics

preamble_text: A student monitors the level of water in a Veronica bucket by measuring the electrical resistance between the top and bottom surfaces of water in the bucket. The bucket is in the shape of a truncated right circular cone with a bottom radius of $0.20 \mathrm{~m}$, a top radius of $0.25 \mathrm{~m}$ and a full vertical depth of $0.60 \mathrm{~m}$. The resistivity of water in the bucket is $2500 \Omega \mathrm{m}$.
question: Determine the resistance the student measures when the bucket is full of water.
answer:
$9.5 \mathrm{k} \Omega$
$$
R=\frac{H \rho}{\pi r_{t} r_{b}}=0.60 m \times 2500 \Omega m /(\pi \times 0.25 m \times 0.20 m)=9.5 \mathrm{k} \Omega
$$
subject: Physics

preamble_text: A student monitors the level of water in a Veronica bucket by measuring the electrical resistance between the top and bottom surfaces of water in the bucket. The bucket is in the shape of a truncated right circular cone with a bottom radius of $0.20 \mathrm{~m}$, a top radius of $0.25 \mathrm{~m}$ and a full vertical depth of $0.60 \mathrm{~m}$. The resistivity of water in the bucket is $2500 \Omega \mathrm{m}$.
question: Determine the resistance the student measures when the depth of water in the bucket is $0.50 \mathrm{~m}$.
answer:
$8.2 \mathrm{k} \Omega$
$$
R=\frac{h \rho}{\pi r_{b}\left[r_{b}+h\left(r_{t}-r_{b}\right) / H\right]}=\frac{0.50 \mathrm{~m} \times 2500 \Omega \mathrm{m}}{\pi \times 0.2 m \times[0.2 m+0.5 m \times(0.25 m-0.20 m) /(0.60 m)]}=8.2 \mathrm{k} \Omega
$$
subject: Physics

preamble_text: Explain the following terms with respect to infectious diseases

An epidemic is a disease that affects a large number of people within a community, population, or region.

preamble_text: In a titration of a solution containing $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{NaHCO}_{3}$ with 0.100 moldm $\mathrm{dm}^{-3}$ HCl solution, $25.0 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of it required a titre of $8.00 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ when phenolphthalein was used as indicator. Repeating this titration with a fresh $25.0 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of the mixture but using methyl orange as indicator required $26.0 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of the acid.
question: Calculate the concentration of the $\mathrm{NaHCO}_{3}$ in the mixture.
answer:
Volume of the titre due to the $\mathrm{NaHCO}_{3}$ alone $=26.0-(2 * 8.00)=10.0 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ $\frac{25.0 * M}{10.0 * 0.100}=\frac{1}{1}$
Concentration of $\mathrm{NaHCO}_{3}, \mathrm{M}=\frac{10.0 * 0.100}{25.0}=0.0400 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text: In a titration of a solution containing $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{NaHCO}_{3}$ with 0.100 moldm $\mathrm{dm}^{-3}$ HCl solution, $25.0 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of it required a titre of $8.00 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ when phenolphthalein was used as indicator. Repeating this titration with a fresh $25.0 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of the mixture but using methyl orange as indicator required $26.0 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of the acid.
question: Calculate the concentration of $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3}$ in the solution.
answer:
Using phenolphthalein, only $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3}$ reacted.
$\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3}+\mathrm{HCl} \rightarrow \mathrm{NaHCO}_{3}+\mathrm{NaCl}$
$\frac{25.0 * M}{8.00 * 0.100}=\frac{1}{1}$
$\mathrm{M}=\frac{8.00 * 0.100}{25.0}=0.0320 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$
[The same answer will be obtained using a titre of $(26-10) \mathrm{cm}^{3}$ and an acid-base ratio of 2:1]
subject: Chemistry

question: State the Arrhenius definition of an acid and give one limitation of this definition.
answer: According to Arrhenius an acid is any substance that ionises in water to give $\mathrm{H}^{+}$ions. Limitation: Definition is restricted to ionisation in the aqueous medium.
subject: Chemistry

question: Define a base according to the Bronsted-Lowry concept and state its limitation if any, with an example.
answer:
Bronsted-Lowry concept defines a base as a proton (or hydrogen ion) acceptor.
Limitation: There are some acid-base reactions that do not involve proton transfer such
as:
$\mathrm{CaO}+\mathrm{SiO}_{2} \rightarrow \mathrm{CaSiO}_{3}$
In this reaction $\mathrm{CaO}$, the base is not acting as a proton acceptor.
(Accept any example in which a known base reacts with a known acid which is not a proton donor. An amphoteric oxide such as $\mathrm{Al}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3}$ may be used as a base or acid)
subject: Chemistry

question: Define the Lewis concept of acids and bases and explain why it is a more universal concept.
answer: Lewis acid is an electron pair acceptor and a Lewis base is an electron pair donor. It is a more universal concept because it does away with all the limitations of the Arrhenius concept requiring an aqueous medium and a proton transfer in Bronsted-Lowry concept.
subject: Chemistry

question: A $96.0 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ steel vessel containing a quantity of argon at a temperature of $27.0^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ and pressure of $102 \mathrm{kPa}$, was immersed in a cooling bath. In order to maintain the same pressure of the gas a suitable liquid had to be added to the vessel until the liquid occupied $32.0 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$. What was the temperature of the cooling bath?
answer:
Apply Charles' law. There is a change in volume at constant pressure of the gas.
Initial volume $V_{1}$ of gas $=96.0 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$
Final volume $V_{2}$ of the gas $=96.0-32.0=64.0 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$
$\mathrm{T}_{1}=300 \mathrm{~K} ; \mathrm{T}_{2}=$ Temperature of the bath $\mathrm{T}_{2}=\left(\frac{V_{2}}{V_{1}}\right) \mathrm{T}_{1}=\left(\frac{64.0}{96.0}\right)^{*} 300=200 \mathrm{~K}$
Bath temperature, $\mathrm{T}_{2}=200 \mathrm{~K}$ or $-73.0^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$.
subject: Chemistry

question: If $24.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of oxygen gas $\mathrm{O}_{2}$ at a pressure of $99.72 \mathrm{kPa}$ occupies a volume $15.0 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$, what is its temperature? $\mathrm{O}=16.0$
answer:
Use the Ideal Gas equation: moles of $\mathrm{O}_{2}=\frac{24.0}{32.0}=0.75$
$$
\mathrm{T}=\left(\frac{P V}{n R}\right)=\frac{15.0 * 99.72}{0.75 * 8.31}
$$
Temperature of the $\mathrm{O}_{2} \quad=\quad 240 \mathrm{~K}$ or $-33.0^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$
subject: Chemistry

question:
Small amounts of hydrogen can be prepared by the following reaction in the laboratory.
$2 \mathrm{Al}+2 \mathrm{NaOH}+6 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O} \rightarrow 2 \mathrm{NaAl}(\mathrm{OH})_{4}+3 \mathrm{H}_{2}$.
What mass of aluminium is required to prepare $5.00 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ of $\mathrm{H}_{2}$ gas at $498.6 \mathrm{kPa}$ and $27.0^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ ?
Al $=27.0, \mathrm{H}=1.00$.
answer:
Use the Ideal Gas Equation to calculate $\mathbf{n}$ moles of hydrogen gas formed.
$\mathrm{n}=\frac{P V}{R T} \quad=\frac{498.6 * 5.00}{8.31 * 300}=1.00$
But $1.00 \mathrm{~mol} \mathrm{H}_{2}$ will be produced by $\frac{2}{3} \mathrm{~mol} \mathrm{Al} \quad \equiv \frac{2 * 27}{3} \mathrm{~g}$ of $\mathrm{Al} \quad=\quad 18.0 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{Al}$
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text: Each school will be presented with two elements and their respective atomic numbers. You are to state, giving your reasons which element has the higher first ionization energy.
question: Sulphur 16 Chlorine 17
answer:
Chlorine has the higher first ionization energy.
Reason: Chlorine has a smaller atomic radius.
Chlorine has higher effective nuclear charge.
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text: Each school will be presented with two elements and their respective atomic numbers. You are to state, giving your reasons which element has the higher first ionization energy.
question: Nitrogen $7 \quad$ oxygen 8
answer:
Nitrogen has the higher first ionization energy.
Reason: The electron configuration of the neutral atom of nitrogen is stable due to the halffilled p-subshell. Oxygen would give up an electron readily to attain that stable electronic configuration, hence nitrogen has the higher first ionization energy.
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text: Each school will be presented with two elements and their respective atomic numbers. You are to state, giving your reasons which element has the higher first ionization energy.
question: Chlorine 17 Argon 18
answer:
Argon has the higher first ionization energy.
Reason: Argon, despite having the larger atomic radius, has very stable electronic configuration because of the fully filled valence shell.
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text: A steel cylinder at $27.0^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ contains $27.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of ethane, $17.6 \mathrm{~g}$ of propane and $17.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of hydrogen sulphide. $\mathrm{S}=32.0 ; \mathrm{C}=12.0 ; \mathrm{H}=1.00$
question: Calculate the total number of moles of gases in the cylinder.
answer:
Ethane $=\quad \mathrm{C}_{2} \mathrm{H}_{6}=30.0$ Moles of ethane $=\frac{27.0}{30.0}=0.900$
Propane $\quad=\mathrm{C}_{3} \mathrm{H}_{8} \quad=\quad 44.0$
Moles of propane $=\frac{17.6}{44.0}=0.400$
Moles of $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{~S}=\frac{17.0}{34.0}=0.500$
Total moles of gases in the cylinder $=\quad 0.900+0.400+0.500=\quad 1.80$
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text: A steel cylinder at $27.0^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ contains $27.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of ethane, $17.6 \mathrm{~g}$ of propane and $17.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of hydrogen sulphide. $\mathrm{S}=32.0 ; \mathrm{C}=12.0 ; \mathrm{H}=1.00$
question: Calculate the partial pressure of propane if the pressure in the cylinder at $27.0^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ is $240 \mathrm{kPa}$, The total number of moles of gases is 1.80 .
answer:
Mole fraction of propane $=\frac{0.400}{1.80}$
Partial pressure of propane $=\frac{0.400}{1.80} * 240=53.3 \mathrm{kPa}$
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text: A steel cylinder at $27.0^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ contains $27.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of ethane, $17.6 \mathrm{~g}$ of propane and $17.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of hydrogen sulphide. $\mathrm{S}=32.0 ; \mathrm{C}=12.0 ; \mathrm{H}=1.00$
question: Calculate the amount in moles of propane that must be added to the mixture of gases in the cylinder at the constant temperature of $27.0^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ to raise the pressure from $240 \mathrm{kPa}$ to $300 \mathrm{kPa}$. The total moles of gases in the cylinder is 1.80 .
answer:
From the ideal gas equation; $\mathrm{P}=\frac{n R T}{V}$
For constant $\mathrm{T}$ and $\mathrm{V}, \quad \mathrm{P} \propto \mathrm{n}$
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{P_{1}}{n_{1}}=\frac{P_{2}}{n_{2}} ; \quad \mathrm{n}_{2}=\left(\frac{P_{2}}{P_{1}}\right) * \mathrm{n}_{1}=\frac{300}{240} * 1.80=2.25 \\
& \text { Moles of propane to be added }=2.25-1.80=0.45
\end{aligned}
$$
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain why the compound $\mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{COOH}$ is an acid but $\mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CH}_{2} \mathrm{OH}$ is not.
answer:
Acidity depends on (i) ability to donate $\mathrm{H}^{+}$ions and $\quad$ (ii) the stability of the anion formed.
The $\mathrm{OH}$ bonds in each of the compounds is polarized. But when $\mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CH}_{2} \mathrm{OH}$ loses a proton the conjugate base $\mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CH}_{2} \mathrm{O}^{-}$is not stable and so readily recombines with $\mathrm{H}^{+}$to form $\mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CH}_{2} \mathrm{OH}$. When $\mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{COOH}$ loses a proton, the conjugate base is stabilized by resonance.
subject: Chemistry

question: Since electronegativity decreases down a Group in the Periodic Table one would expect HF molecule to be a stronger acid than $\mathrm{HCl}$, but it is the other way round, Why?
answer: $\mathrm{HCl}$ in water dissociates completely to give $\mathrm{H}_{3} \mathrm{O}^{+}$ions and $\mathrm{Cl}^{-}$ions. $\mathrm{HF}$ is a weak acid because the $\mathrm{H}-\mathrm{F}$ bond is very strong. Both $\mathrm{F}$ and $\mathrm{H}$ are small atoms and their orbitals can overlap effectively.
subject: Chemistry

question: Even though the iodine atom is less electronegative than the bromine atom, $\mathrm{HI}$ molecule is a stronger acid than $\mathrm{HBr}$ molecule. Why?
answer: Acidity involves the heterogenous cleavage of the bond between $\mathrm{H}$ and the halogen OR Acidity depends on the strength of the bond between $\mathrm{H}$ and the halogen. HI bond is weaker. There is less effective overlap of the orbitals of $\mathrm{H}$ and I because of the larger size of the I atom.
subject: Chemistry

question: Calculate the mass of trinitroglycerin to be obtained from $184 \mathrm{~kg}$ of $1,2,3$-propantriol if the yield is only $90.0 \%$. Assume there is excess $\mathrm{HNO}_{3}$.
answer:
$\quad \mathrm{C}_{3} \mathrm{H}_{5}(\mathrm{OH})_{3}+3 \mathrm{HNO}_{3} \rightarrow \mathrm{C}_{3} \mathrm{H}_{5}\left(\mathrm{NO}_{3}\right)_{3}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$
$\begin{array}{lll}92.0 & 189 & 227\end{array}$
For $100 \%$ yield mass of trinitroglycerin from $184 \mathrm{~kg} \quad=\quad \frac{184}{92.0} * 227 \quad=\quad 454 \mathrm{~kg}$
For $90.0 \%$ yield, mass trinitroglycerin $=0.900 * 454=408.6=409 \mathrm{~kg}$
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain how two liquids of different boiling points get separated in a simple distillation procedure.
answer: When the mixture is heated the liquid with the lower boiling point begins to vapourise. This continues until the boiling point is reached. The vapour is $100 \%$ of that of the liquid with a lower boiling point. The vapour enters the condenser and gets collected as liquid. The second liquid distils at a higher temperature.
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain how two liquids with close boiling points get separated by fractional distillation.
answer: When the mixture is initially heated the vapour of the liquid of the lower boiling point constitutes a bigger fraction of the vapour that rises. As the vapour rises in the fractionating column it becomes richer and richer of the vapour of the low boiling liquid. The vapour finally becomes pure vapour of the lower boiling liquid; it enters the condenser and condenses as pure liquid. The second liquid distils later.
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain how the fractionating column gets the vapours separated.
answer: The fractionating column offers a larger surface for condensation and re-evaporation processes. When the mixture of vapours enters the column, it condenses and as the liquid descends it meets hot vapour and re-evaporation takes place. The new vapour, richer in the vapour of the lower boiling liquid, rises and re-condenses. The process repeats itself further up the column until pure vapour of the lower boiling liquid enters the condenser. Generally, the temperature in the column decreases as the vapour ascends the column
subject: Chemistry

question: Avogadro's hypothesis suggests that equal volumes of different gases at the same temperature and pressure contain the same number of particles. Provide a quantitative explanation to show that this is consistent with the Ideal Gas Law. $\quad \mathrm{R}=8.31 \mathrm{Jmol}^{-1} \mathrm{~K}^{-1}$. $\quad$ Assume pressure of $100 \mathrm{kPa}$ and temperature of $27.0{ }^{0} \mathrm{C}$.
answer:
Ideal Gas Law states; $\quad$ PV $=$ nRT
$$
\frac{n}{V}=\frac{P}{R T}=\frac{100}{8.31 * 300}=0.0401 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}
$$
This is true of all gases, irrespective of the identity of the gas.
subject: Chemistry

question:
Calculate the densities of methane and air in $\mathrm{gdm}^{-3}$ and show that balloons filled with methane at $27.0{ }^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ and $100 \mathrm{kPa}$ will float. Assume the molar mass of air at that temperature and pressure is 29.0 gmol $^{-1}$.
$\mathrm{CH}_{4}=16.0$
answer:
Since moles of gas per $\mathrm{dm}^{3}=0.0401$
Density of methane $=\quad 16.0 * 0.0401=0.642 \mathrm{gdm}^{-3}$
Density of air $=29.0 * 0.0401=1.16 \mathrm{gdm}^{-3}$
Hence methane is less dense than air and will float.
subject: Chemistry

question: Calculate the densities of NO gas and propane and predict the behaviour of balloons filled separately with these gases. $\mathrm{NO}=30.0 ; \mathrm{C}_{3} \mathrm{H}_{8}=$ 38.0. Assume density of air $=1.16 \mathrm{gdm}^{-3}$
answer:
Density of NO in $\mathrm{gdm}^{-3}=0.0401 * 30.0=1.20 \mathrm{gdm}^{-3}$
Density of $\mathrm{C}_{3} \mathrm{H}_{8}$ in $\mathrm{gdm}^{-3}=0.0401 * 38.0=1.52 \mathrm{gdm}^{-3}$
NO has almost the same density as air and will not float.
Propane is much denser than air and will not float.
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain how indicators work during titrations.
answer:
Indicators are weak organic acids (or bases). The acid-base conjugate pairs have different colours.
An indicator is chosen for a titration such that at the $\mathrm{pH}$ of the equivalence point there is a change from the acid to the conjugate base (or from the base to the conjugate acid) and hence a change in colour.
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain why for volumetric exercises involving dilute $\mathrm{HCl}$ and $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3}$ solution it is possible to use either phenolphthalein or methyl orange.
answer:
$\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3}$ reacts with $\mathrm{HCl}$ in two steps.
$\begin{array}{llllll}\text { Step I: } \mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3}+\mathrm{HCl} & \rightarrow & \mathrm{NaHCO}_{3}+ & \mathrm{NaCl} & \\ \text { Step II: } \mathrm{NaHCO}_{3} & + & \mathrm{HCl} & \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{NaCl}+\mathrm{CO}_{2}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\end{array}$
For step I, the solution is alkaline at the end-point with the formation of $\mathrm{NaHCO}_{3}$ and therefore phenolphthalein which changes colour in the alkaline region is suitable for that change.
For step II, the solution is acidic when $\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ and $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$ are formed and methyl orange changes colour in that region.
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain the volumetric exercises you would perform to determine the concentrations of $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{NaHCO}_{3}$ in a solution. (You need not explain how the concentrations would be calculated)
answer: Titrate the solution with the $\mathrm{HCl}$ solution using phenolphthalein as indicator and record the average titre $\mathrm{V}_{1}$. Either add methyl orange to the colourless solution and continue with the titration and record the average titre $\mathrm{V}_{2}$ OR use a fresh solution and titrate with methyl orange as indicator and record the titre as $\mathrm{V}_{2}^{\prime}$.
subject: Chemistry

question: State one significance of glycolysis to living organisms
answer:
It is an almost universal central pathway of glucose catabolism occurring in the cytoplasm of all the tissues of biological systems leading to generation of energy in the form of ATP for vital activities
It is the pathway through which the largest flux of carbon occurs in most cells
Some plant tissues which are modified for the storage of starch such as potato tubers and some plants adapted to growth in inundated water such as water cress derive most of their energy from glycolysis
In plants, glycolysis is the key metabolic component of the respiratory process, which generates energy in the form of ATP in
Many types of anaerobic microorganisms are entirely dependent on glycolysis
Mammalian tissues such as renal medulla and brain solely depend on glycolysis for major sources of metabolic energy

question: There are 5 main postulates of the Atomic Theory proposed by John Dalton. Give any one of them.
answer:
Elements are made up of small particles called atoms.
Atoms can neither be created nor destroyed.
Atoms of the same elements are identical; they have the same mass and size.
Atoms of different elements have different mass and size.
Atoms combine to form compounds and they do so in simple whole numbers.
subject: Chemistry

question:
Explain why the reaction:
$2 \mathrm{KMnO}_{4}+16 \mathrm{HCl} \rightarrow \mathrm{MnCl}_{2}+2 \mathrm{KCl}+5 \mathrm{Cl}_{2}+8 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$ is a redox reaction.
answer:
The oxidation state of manganese in $\mathrm{KMnO}_{4}$ changes from + 7 to +2 in $\mathrm{MnCl}_{2}$ and the oxidation state of
$\mathrm{Cl}$ in $\mathrm{HCl}$ changes from -1 to zero in $\mathrm{Cl}_{2}$.
subject: Chemistry

question:
Explain why the reaction: $\mathrm{Cl}_{2(\mathrm{~g})}+2 \mathrm{NaOH}_{\text {(aq) }} \rightarrow \mathrm{NaCl}_{\text {(aq) }}+\mathrm{NaOCl}_{\text {(aq) }}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{\text {(I) }}$
is described as a disproportionation reaction.
answer:
In a disproportionation reaction the same species is reduced and oxidized at the same time.
$\mathrm{Cl}_{2}$ is reduced to $\mathrm{Cl}^{-}$in $\mathrm{NaCl}$ and oxidized to $\mathrm{Cl}^{+}$in $\mathrm{NaClO}$.
subject: Chemistry

question:
Explain why the reaction:
$\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{(\mathrm{l})}+\mathrm{CN}_{(\text {(aq) }} \rightarrow \mathrm{HCN}_{(\mathrm{aq})}+\mathrm{OH}_{(-}^{-}$(aq), may be described as an acid-base reaction or hydrolysis.
answer:
It is an acid-base reaction because $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$ donates a proton to the $\mathrm{CN}^{-}$.
It is hydrolysis because the $\mathrm{CN}^{-}$ion, a conjugate base of a weak acid reacts with water molecule by splitting it into $\mathrm{H}^{+}$and $\mathrm{HO}^{-}$.
subject: Chemistry

question: Calculate the gain in mass in $\mathrm{kg}$ of the cathode in the electrolysis of $\mathrm{CuSO}_{4}$ solution, using copper electrodes after passing 120 Faraday of charge. $\quad \mathrm{Cu}=63.5$
answer:
At cathode: $\quad \mathrm{Cu}^{2+}+$ 2Faraday $\rightarrow \mathrm{Cu}$
Mass of copper produced by $2.00 \mathrm{~F}=63.5 \mathrm{~g}$
Mass of copper to be produced by 120 Faraday $=\quad \frac{120}{2.00} * 63.5=3,810 \mathrm{~g}=3.81 \mathrm{~kg}$
subject: Chemistry

question: Calculate the volume of hydrogen evolved at STP in the electrolysis of dilute $\mathrm{NaCl}$ solution using inert electrodes after passing a charge of 64.0 Faraday. Molar volume of ideal gas at STP $\quad=22.4 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$.
answer:
At cathode: $2 \mathrm{H}^{+}+2Faraday \rightarrow \mathrm{H}_{2}$
Volume of $\mathrm{H}_{2}$ discharged by $2 \mathrm{~F}$ of charge $=22.4 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$
Volume at STP to be discharged by 64.0 Faraday $=\frac{64.0}{2.00} * 22.4=32.0 * 22.4$
$$
=716.8 \mathrm{dm}^{3} \quad=\quad=717 \mathrm{dm}^{3}
$$
subject: Chemistry

question: Calculate the mass of oxygen in gram to be discharged in the electrolysis of dilute $\mathrm{NaCl}$ solution using inert electrodes after passing 64.0 Faraday of charge. $\mathrm{O}=16.0$
answer:
At anode: $4 \mathrm{OH}^{-}-4 \mathrm{~F} \rightarrow 2 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}+\mathrm{O}_{2}$
Mass of $\mathrm{O}_{2}$ produced after passing 4.00 Faraday of charge $=\quad 32.0 \mathrm{~g}$
Mass of $\mathrm{O}_{2}$ to be produced by 64.0 Faraday $=\quad \frac{64.0}{4.00} * 32.0 \mathrm{~g}=512 \mathrm{~g}$

question: Give one advantage of Poultry Farming:

Food: It provides eggs and meat which are highly nutritious foods. They are a rich source of animal protein, minerals, right kind of fat and vitamins (A, B and D) for good health. Unfertilized eggs are called "vegetarian eggs".

Manure: The faecal matter of birds form a rich manure which increases the fertility of soil. It increases crop yields.
Feathers: Feathers of the birds are useful.
Recreation: The birds of poultry are also a means of recreation. Coloured chickens give pleasure look. Cock-fighting is popular in some people

Calculate the volume of $\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ gas that will be evolved at $27.0{ }^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ and pressure of $100 \mathrm{kPa}$ when $200 \mathrm{~g}$ of calcium trioxocarbonate (IV) is heated until it decomposes completely.
$\mathrm{Ca}=40.0 ; \mathrm{O}=16.0 ; \mathrm{C}=12.0 ; \quad$ Ideal Gas constant, $\mathrm{R}=\quad 8.31 \mathrm{JK}^{-1} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$.
answer:
$\mathrm{CaCO}_{3} \rightarrow \mathrm{CaO}+\mathrm{CO}_{2}$
$100 \quad 1.00 \mathrm{~mol}$
Moles of $\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ to be produced $=\frac{200}{100}=2.00$ moles
$$
\therefore \mathrm{V}=\frac{2 * 8.31 * 300}{100}=49.9 \mathrm{dm}^{3}
$$
subject: Chemistry

question:
Calculate the pressure of hydrogen evolved at $27.0{ }^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ and kept in a $50.0 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ cylinder when $84.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of magnesium is made to react with excess $\mathrm{HCl}$ solution.
$\mathrm{Mg}=24.0 ;$ Ideal Gas constant, $\mathrm{R}=\quad 8.31 \mathrm{JK}^{-1} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$
answer:
$\operatorname{Mg}_{(\mathrm{s})}+\quad \mathrm{H}_{(\mathrm{aq})}^{+} \quad \rightarrow \mathrm{Mg}^{2+}+\mathrm{H}_{2(\mathrm{~g})}$
$24.0 \mathrm{~g} \quad 1.00$ mole
Moles of $\mathrm{H}_{2}$ to be produced from $84.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of $\mathrm{Mg}=\frac{84.0}{24.0}=3.50$
Pressure $=\frac{3.50 * 8.31 * 300}{50.0}=174.5=175 \mathrm{kPa}$
subject: Chemistry

Moles of $\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ to be produced $=1 / 2 \equiv 0.500$

Silicon carbide, when pure is a colourless solid. It is also known as carborundum and it is so hard it is used to sharpen tools etc. It is made by heating a mixture of silica and coke in an electric furnace. The equation for the reaction is as follows:
$\mathrm{SiO}_{2}+3 \mathrm{C} \rightarrow \mathrm{SiC}+2 \mathrm{CO}$
$\mathrm{Si}=28.0 ; \mathrm{O}=16.0 ; \mathrm{C}=12.0$
question: Calculate the mass of silicon carbide that can be obtained from a mixture of $40.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of silica and $20.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of coke.
answer:
$\mathrm{SiO}_{2}+3 \mathrm{C} \rightarrow \mathrm{SiC}+2 \mathrm{CO}$
$60.0 \quad 46.0 \quad 40.0 \quad 56.0$
Moles of $\mathrm{SiO}_{2}$ present $=\frac{40.0}{60.0}=0.667$
Moles of C present $\quad=\frac{20.0}{12.0}=1.67$
Hence $\mathrm{C}$ is present in limiting quantity
Mass of SiC to be obtained $=\frac{20.0}{36.0} * 40.0=22.2 \mathrm{~g}$
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text:
Silicon carbide, when pure is a colourless solid. It is also known as carborundum and it is so hard it is used to sharpen tools etc. It is made by heating a mixture of silica and coke in an electric furnace. The equation for the reaction is as follows:
$\mathrm{SiO}_{2}+3 \mathrm{C} \rightarrow \mathrm{SiC}+2 \mathrm{CO}$
$\mathrm{Si}=28.0 ; \mathrm{O}=16.0 ; \mathrm{C}=12.0$
question: Calculate the mass of carbon required to react with excess silica to produce $90.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of silicon carbide.
answer:
$\mathrm{SiO}_{2}+3 \mathrm{C} \rightarrow \mathrm{SiC}+2 \mathrm{CO}$
$60.0 \quad 36.0 \quad 40.0 \quad 56$
Mass of carbon required to make $40.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of the carbide $\quad=\quad 36.0 \mathrm{~g}$
Mass of carbon required to make $90.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of the carbide $=\frac{90.0}{40.0} * 36 .=81.0 \mathrm{~g}$
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text:
Silicon carbide, when pure is a colourless solid. It is also known as carborundum and it is so hard it is used to sharpen tools etc. It is made by heating a mixture of silica and coke in an electric furnace. The equation for the reaction is as follows:
$\mathrm{SiO}_{2}+3 \mathrm{C} \rightarrow \mathrm{SiC}+2 \mathrm{CO}$
$\mathrm{Si}=28.0 ; \mathrm{O}=16.0 ; \mathrm{C}=12.0$
question: Calculate the mass of silicon carbide in $\mathrm{kg}$ that can be obtained from a mixture of $75.0 \mathrm{~kg}$ of silicon oxide and $50.0 \mathrm{~kg}$ of carbon.
answer:
Moles of $\mathrm{SiO}_{2}$ provided $=\frac{75.0 * 10^{3}}{60.0}=1.25^{*} 10^{3}$
Moles of coke provided $=\frac{50.0 * 10^{3}}{12.0}=4.17 * 10^{3}$
Moles of $\mathrm{SiO}_{2}$ needed for $4.17 * 10^{3}$ moles of $\mathrm{C}=1.39 * 10^{3}$ moles
So $\mathrm{SiO}_{2}$ is present in limiting quantity Hence mass of $\mathrm{SiC}$ expected $=\quad \frac{75.0}{60.0} * 40.0 \mathrm{~kg}=\quad 50.0 \mathrm{~kg}$
subject: Chemistry

question: The initial position of a particle is $3 \hat{\mathrm{im}}$ and its velocity is given in terms of time $t$ by $v(t)=\left[(2 \hat{i}+5 \hat{j}) \mathrm{ms}^{-4}\right] t^{3}$. What is the position of the particle at time $t ?$
answer:
$3 \hat{i} m+\left(\frac{1}{2} \hat{i}+\frac{5}{4} \hat{j}\right) t^{4} m s^{-4}=\left(3 m+\frac{1}{2} t^{4} m s^{-4}\right) \hat{i}+\left(\frac{5}{4} t^{4} m s^{-4}\right) \hat{j}$
$$
r(t)=r_{0}+\int_{0}^{t} v d t=3 \hat{i} m+\left(\frac{1}{2} \hat{i}+\frac{5}{4} \hat{j}\right) t^{4} m s^{-4}=\left(3 m+\frac{1}{2} t^{4} m s^{-4}\right) \hat{i}+\left(\frac{5}{4} t^{4} m s^{-4}\right) \hat{j}
$$
subject: Physics

question: The velocity of a particle whose initial position is $(2 \hat{i}+3 \hat{j}) \mathrm{m}$ is given in terms of time $t$ by $v(t)=\left(a t \hat{i}+b t^{2} \hat{j}\right)$ where $a$ and $b$ are constants. Find the position of the particle at time $t$.
answer:
$\left(2 m+\frac{1}{2} a t^{2}\right) \hat{i}+\left(3 m+\frac{1}{3} b t^{3}\right) \hat{j}$
$$
r(t)=r_{0}+\int_{0}^{t} v d t=(2 \hat{i}+3 \hat{j}) m+\left(\frac{1}{2} a t^{2} \hat{i}+\frac{1}{3} b t^{3} \hat{j}\right)=\left(2 m+\frac{1}{2} a t^{2}\right) \hat{i}+\left(3 m+\frac{1}{3} b t^{3}\right) \hat{j}
$$
subject: Physics

question: The velocity of a particle whose initial position is $5 \hat{j} m$ is given in terms of time $t$ by $v(t)=\left(c t^{4} \hat{i}+d t^{-2} \hat{j}\right)$ where $c$ and $d$ are constants. Find the position of the particle at time $t$.
answer:
$\frac{1}{5} c t^{5} \hat{i}+\left(5 m-d t^{-1}\right) \hat{j}$
$$
r(t)=r_{0}+\int_{0}^{t} v d t=5 \hat{j} m+\left(\frac{1}{5} c t^{5} \hat{i}-d t^{-1} \hat{j}\right)=\frac{1}{5} c t^{5} \hat{i}+\left(5 m-d t^{-1}\right) \hat{j}
$$
subject: Physics

$\mathrm{HCO}_{3}^{-}$is the conjugate base of $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3}$

Hence $\mathrm{pH}=14.0-8.40=8.60$

preamble_text: State the effect(s) of each of the following on biodiversity the variability among living organisms from all source.
question: Habitat loss
answer: Habitat loss will decrease biodiversity. When this occurs only the animals that are able to adapt and live within the new habitat will survive. This could potentially cause a genetic bottleneck for those that were once thriving in the initial habitat.
subject: Biology

preamble_text: State the effect(s) of each of the following on biodiversity the variability among living organisms from all source.
question: Overharvesting
answer: Overharvesting can limit biodiversity. If too much of a species (whether plants or animals) is harvested for human use, then there is the potential that certain genes from the pool are completely wiped out. This means that they will be very hard to re-introduce into the population, and the biodiversity lessens.
subject: Biology

preamble_text: State the effect(s) of each of the following on biodiversity the variability among living organisms from all source.
question: Exotic species
answer: Exotic species are a threat to biodiversity. This is because it will add a new element to the food chain. Perhaps the exotic species is a predator and will kill off some other organisms therefore shrinking biodiversity in an area. The exotic species could also be an invasive plant that takes root space away from other species, therefore threatening biodiversity.
subject: Biology

preamble_text:
Phosphorus (V) chloride decomposes to phosphorus (III) chloride and chlorine gas when heated. The balanced equation is as follows:
$$
\mathrm{PCl}_{5(\mathrm{~g})} \rightleftharpoons \mathrm{PCl}_{3(\mathrm{~g})}+\mathrm{Cl}_{2(\mathrm{~g})}
$$
The equilibrium constant $\mathrm{K}_{\mathrm{C}}$ for the reaction is 0.0360 at $300{ }^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$.
question: In an experiment when only $20.0 \%$ of the initial amount of $0.100 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$ of the $\mathrm{PCl}_{5}$ had decomposed, it was not certain if equilibrium had been attained. If the initial concentration of each of $\mathrm{PCl}_{3}$ and $\mathrm{Cl}_{2}$ was zero moldm ${ }^{-3}$, determine by calculating the Reaction Quotient if there was equilibrium. If not state, the direction the reaction should move to establish equilibrium.
answer:
$\quad \mathrm{PCl}_{5(\mathrm{~g})} \rightleftharpoons \mathrm{PCl}_{3(\mathrm{~g})}+\mathrm{Cl}_{2(\mathrm{~g})}$
Initial: $0.100 \quad 0 \quad 0$
Final: $0.0800 \quad 0.0200$
$\mathrm{Q}=\frac{(0.0200)^{2}}{(0.0800)}=\frac{4.00 * 10^{-4}}{8.00 * 10^{-2}}=5.00^{*} 10^{-3}$ or 0.00500
This is less than the $\mathrm{K}_{\mathrm{C}}\left(3.60^{*} 10^{-2}\right)$ and so the reaction is not at equilibrium.
It must shift from left to right to reach equilibrium.
subject: Chemistry

answer:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \begin{array}{llll}
\text { Final: } & 0.0500 & 0.0500 & 0.0500
\end{array} \\
& \mathrm{Q}=\frac{(0.0500)^{2}}{(0.0500)}=0.0500=5.00^{*} 10^{-2} \text { or } 0.0500
\end{aligned}
$$
This is greater than the $\mathrm{K}_{\mathrm{C}}$ of $3.60^{*} 10^{-2}$, hence the reaction would not be at equilibrium.

answer:

Q II = $(0.0500)^{2}/(0.0700) = ( 25.0 7 )*10^{-2} = 3.57*10^{-2} \\ or \\ 0.0357$

question: Boyle's Law states that the volume of a gas varies inversely with its pressure at constant temperature. How does the Kinetic Theory of gases explain this law?
answer: At constant temperature, the average kinetic energy of a molecule is constant. Therefore, the average speed of the molecule is constant and the force of collision with walls, generating the pressure is constant. When the volume is increased the concentration decreases and the frequency of collision per unit wall area decreases leading to decrease in pressure.
subject: Chemistry

question: Avogadro's Law states that equal volumes of any two gases at the same temperature and pressure contain the same number of molecules. How does the Kinetic Theory of gases explain this law?
answer: Since the pressure of a gas at a given temperature results from the frequency of collisions with the walls of its container, for two different gases of the same volume and at the same temperature to have the same pressure, the frequency of collisions should be the same and hence should contain the same number of molecules.
subject: Chemistry

question: Charles' Law states that the volume occupied by any given amount of gas at constant pressure is directly proportional to the absolute temperature.
answer: When temperature is raised, the average molecular speed of the molecule is increased, frequency of collision with the walls of its container is increased and the pressure is increased, all other factors remaining constant. If the pressure is to remain constant the volume has to increase to reduce the frequency per unit wall area.
subject: Chemistry

question: Atomic size of elements is a Periodic Property. Use a Period of the Periodic Table to illustrate this.
answer: In a Period, atomic size decreases from left to right. In a Period, from an element to the next, the electron enters the same valence shell while the nuclear charge increases by one. The valence electrons are therefore attracted with a greater force ( or effective nuclear charge increases) leading to a decrease in atomic radius.
subject: Chemistry

question: Use a Group of the Periodic Table to illustrate the fact that the first ionization energy is a Periodic Property.
answer: As one descends a Group in the Periodic Table, the first ionization decreases. From one element to the one below it, a shell (or an energy level) is added. This is farther away from the nucleus. The electrons in the outer shell therefore experience less attractive force of the nucleus.
subject: Chemistry

question: Enthalpy of Atomization energy is another Periodic Property of elements. Use Group (III) or 13 of the Periodic Table to illustrate this.
answer: The atomization energy of the elements in Group (III) or 13 decreases down the Group. It reflects the strength of interatomic bonds. In boron, we have strong covalent bonds whereas, from aluminium down to thallium, it is metallic bonds. Down the Group, the atoms get bigger and the binding energies decrease.
subject: Chemistry

question: Mention one of the main factors that influence primary productivity in ecosystems.
answer:
1. Light: The light field varies with depth in the ocean, with time of day, and with time of year.
2. Temperature: Temperature controls the enzyme-mediated dark-reaction rates of photosynthesis.
3. Species composition also influence rates of primary production. For example, the size distribution of the cells and the pigment composition of the cells can both change with species composition, thus influencing nutrient uptake and light absorption for photosynthesis.
4. Availability of nutrients and photosynthetic capacity of plant also influence the primary productivity.
5. Species succession is also a determining factor.
subject: Biology

question: Give one reason why there are gaps in the fossil records in biology.
answer:
Not all fossils have been found yet.
Fossilisation is rare, so not all dead organisms fossilize (conditions may have been wrong for them to fossilize).
Many fossils have been destroyed by movements of the Earth's plates or by human activities like digging and dam building.
Soft-bodied organisms do not usually fossilize, so very few of them are present in the fossil record
5Any other relevant fact may be accepted, e.g. people may not recognize an item as a fossil, so it goes unnoticed.
subject: Biology

question: Seeds of some plants do not germinate immediately after shedding from the plants but go through a period of rest known as dormancy. Give one importance of seed dormancy
answer:
Perennation: Seed dormancy allows seeds to pass through drought, cold and other un-favourable conditions.
Dispersal: Allows long distance dispersal of seeds.
Storage: Prolongs storage
Germination under Favourable Conditions: Seeds germinate only when sufficient water is available to leach out inhibitors and soften the seed coats.
Reduces competition among plants
Prevents insitu germination / viviparity
Allows the embryo ample time to develop
subject: Biology

question: The velocity of a $2.0 \mathrm{~kg}$ object moving along a straight line is given by $v(t)=a t+b t^{2}$ where $a=1.0 \mathrm{~ms}^{-2}$ and $b=3.0 \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~s}^{-3}$. Find the force on the object at $t=5.0 \mathrm{~s}$.
answer:
$62 N$
$$
F=m d v / d t=m(a+2 b t)=2.0 \mathrm{~kg} \times\left(1.0 \mathrm{~ms}^{-2}+2 \times 3.0 \mathrm{~ms}^{-3} \times 5.0 \mathrm{~s}\right)=62 \mathrm{~N}
$$
subject: Physics

question: The velocity of a $4.0 \mathrm{~kg}$ object moving along a straight line is given by $v(t)=c t^{-1}+d t^{3}$ where $c=2.0 \mathrm{~m}$ and $d=0.50 \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~s}^{-4}$. Find the force on the object at $t=2.0 \mathrm{~s}$.
answer:
$22 N$
$$
F=m d v / d t=m\left(-c t^{-2}+3 d t^{2}\right)=4.0 \mathrm{~kg} \times\left(-2.0 m \times(2.0 s)^{-2}+3 \times 0.50 \mathrm{~ms}^{-4} \times(2.0 \mathrm{~s})^{2}\right)=22 \mathrm{~N}
$$
subject: Physics

question: The velocity of a $5.0 \mathrm{~kg}$ object moving along a straight line is given by $v(t)=u+f t^{2}$ where $u=16 \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}$ and $f=8.0 \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~s}^{-3}$. Find the force on the object at $t=2.0 \mathrm{~s}$.
answer:
$160 N$
$$
F=m d v / d t=m(2 f t)=5.0 \mathrm{~kg} \times\left(2 \times 8.0 \mathrm{~ms}^{-3} \times 2.0 \mathrm{~s}\right)=160 \mathrm{~N}
$$

question: Explain why cations have smaller radii than their corresponding neutral atoms.
answer: When a neutral atom loses an electron or a number of electrons there are fewer electrons to be attracted by the same number of protons (or the fewer electrons left experience the same attractive nuclear charge). This results in the reduction of the radius.
subject: Chemistry

question: State the trend in the atomic radii of elements in a Period of the Periodic Table up to the respective halogen and give the main reason for the observed trend.
answer:
The atomic radius decreases smoothly from left to right up to the halogen.
Reason: In the Period the outer electrons fill or go into the same shell and therefore the screening effect is caused by the same core electrons. Therefore as atomic number increases, the effective nuclear charge also increases and this causes the atomic radius to decrease.
subject: Chemistry

question: The atoms of the inert gas in each Period have the largest atomic radii. Why?
answer:
The atoms of an inert gas have all the energy levels completely filled with electrons.
The increased in atomic size from the halogen to the inert gas is due to increase in repulsion among the electrons in the complete outer shell.
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text: A sealed metal cylinder is filled with $9.00 \mathrm{~g}$ of ethane, $22.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of carbon (IV) oxide and $4.00 \mathrm{~g}$ of neon. Ne $=20.0 ; \mathrm{O}=16.0 \mathrm{C}=12.0 ; \mathrm{H}=1.00$
question: Calculate the mole fraction of ethane in the cylinder.
answer:
Moles of ethane $\left(\mathrm{C}_{2} \mathrm{H}_{6}\right)=\frac{9.00}{30.0}=0.300$
Moles of $\mathrm{CO}_{2}=\frac{22.0}{44.0}=0.500$
Moles of Ne $=\frac{4.00}{20.0}=0.200$
Hence mole fraction of $\mathrm{C}_{2} \mathrm{H}_{6}=\frac{0.300}{1.00}=0.300$

question: Mention one of the 7 major functions of plant vacuoles
answer:
1.Turgor pressure control: The water-filled central vacuole exerts pressure on the cell wall to help plant structures remain rigid and erect.
2.Growth: The central vacuole aids in cell elongation by absorbing water and exerting turgor pressure on the cell wall.
3.Storage: Vacuoles store important minerals, water, nutrients, ions, waste products, small molecules, enzymes, and plant pigments.
4.Molecule degradation: The internal acidic environment of a vacuole aids in the degradation of larger molecules sent to the vacuole for destruction.
5.Detoxification: Vacuoles remove potentially toxic substances from the cytosol, such as excess heavy metals and herbicides.
6.Protection: Some vacuoles store and release chemicals that are poisonous or taste bad to deter predators from consuming the plant.
7.Seed germination: Vacuoles are a source of nutrients for seeds during germination.
subject: Biology

preamble_text:
The hydrogen trioxocarbonate(IV) ion in aqueous medium may react with a proton in two different ways as given in equations (1) and (2).
Equation (1): $\mathrm{HCO}_{3}^{-}$(aq) $+\mathrm{H}^{+}$(aq) $\rightarrow \quad \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3 \text { (aq) }}$
Equation (2): $\mathrm{HCO}_{3}^{-}$(aq) $+\mathrm{H}_{\text {(aq) }}^{+} \rightarrow \mathrm{CO}_{2(\mathrm{~g})}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{(1)}$
Use the following enthalpies of formation all in $\mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}$ to calculate enthalpies of reactions (1) and (2) and state which of the two is more thermodynamically favourable.
question: $\mathrm{HCO}_{3}^{-}$(aq) $\quad-692 ; \mathrm{H}^{+}$(aq) $\quad 0 ; \quad \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3(\mathrm{aq})} \quad-700 ; \mathrm{CO}_{2(\mathrm{~g})}-394 ; \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{(\mathrm{ll})}-286$
answer:
$\operatorname{Rxn}(1) \quad \mathrm{HCO}_{3}^{-}$(aq) $+\mathrm{H}^{+}$(aq) $\rightarrow \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3 \text { (aq) }}$
$\Delta \mathrm{H}(\operatorname{Rxn} 1)=-700-(-692)=-8.00 \mathrm{~kJ}$
$\operatorname{Rxn}(2) \mathrm{HCO}_{3}^{-}$(aq) $+\mathrm{H}^{+}$(aq) $\rightarrow \mathrm{CO}_{2(\mathrm{~g})}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{(\mathrm{l})}$
$\Delta \mathrm{H}(\operatorname{Rxn} 2)=(-394+-286)-(-692)=\quad+12.0 \mathrm{~kJ}$
Hence Reaction (1) is more thermodynamically favourable.
subject: Chemistry

You are provided with the following enthalpies of formation all in $\mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}$. $\mathrm{Fe}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3(\mathrm{~s})}-824 ; \quad \mathrm{Mn}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3} \quad-959 ; \quad \mathrm{Al}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3} \quad-1676$.
answer:
For Fe: $\quad \mathrm{Fe}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3(\mathrm{~s})}+\quad 2 \mathrm{Al}_{(\mathrm{s})} \rightarrow 2 \mathrm{Fe}_{(\mathrm{s})}+\mathrm{Al}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3(\mathrm{~s})}$

question: Calculate the percentage change in the volume of a balloon when the gas inside is heated from $27.0^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ to $87.0^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ in a hot water bath at constant pressure.
answer:
Apply Charles' law; At constant Pressure $\quad \frac{V_{1}}{T_{1}}=\frac{V_{2}}{T_{2}}$
$$
\begin{array}{lll}
\text { Hence, } \mathrm{V}_{2}=\mathrm{V}_{1}\left(\frac{T_{2}}{T_{1}}\right) ; & \mathrm{T}_{1}=27.0+273 & =300 ; \mathrm{T}_{2}=87.0+273=360 \\
\mathrm{~V}_{2}=\mathrm{V}_{1}\left(\frac{T_{2}}{T_{1}}\right)=\mathrm{V}_{1}\left(\frac{360}{300}\right)= & 1.20 \mathrm{~V}_{1} \\
\% \text { Increase }=20.0 \% &
\end{array}
$$
subject: Chemistry

question:
Consider the following redox reactions:
$Al^{3+}_{(aq)} + Fe_{(s)} \rightarrow Al_{(s)} + Fe^{3+}_{(aq)}$
$Zn_{(s)} + Cu^{2+}_{(aq)} \rightarrow Cu_{(s)} + Zn^{2+}_{(aq)}$

$\mathrm{Fe}_{(\mathrm{aq})}^{3+}-48.5$
$\mathrm{Cu}^{2+}(\mathrm{aq})$
$-65.0$

$\mathrm{B} \quad \mathrm{Zn}_{(\mathrm{s})}+\mathrm{Cu}^{2+}{ }_{(\mathrm{aq})} \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{Cu}_{(\mathrm{s})}+\mathrm{Zn}^{2+}{ }_{(\mathrm{aq})}$
$\Delta \mathrm{H}$ reaction $=-154-(-65.0)=\quad-89.0 \mathrm{~kJ}$
From the enthalpies of reaction, $\operatorname{Redox} \mathbf{A}$ is not thermodynamically favourable.

preamble_text: A $-5.0 \mathrm{nC}$ charge is located at the origin and a $+5.0 \mathrm{nC}$ charge is located on the $x$-axis at $x=2.0 \mathrm{~m}$.
question: Find the electric field on the $x$-axis at $x=0.50 \mathrm{~m}$.
answer:
$-200 \mathrm{Vm}^{-1} \hat{\mathbf{i}}$
$$
E=\frac{1}{4 \pi \epsilon_{0}}\left[\frac{q_{1}\left(r-r_{1}\right)}{\left|r-r_{1}\right|^{3}}+\frac{q_{2}\left(r-r_{2}\right)}{\left|r-r_{2}\right|^{3}}\right]=9.0 \times 10^{9} m F^{-1} \times\left[\frac{-5.0 \times 10^{-9} C}{|0.50 m-0|^{2}} \hat{i}-\frac{5.0 \times 10^{-9} C}{|0.50 m-2.0 m|^{2}} \hat{i}\right]=-200 \mathrm{Vm}^{-1} \hat{i}
$$
Or $200 \mathrm{~V} \mathrm{~m}^{-1}$ in the negative $x$ direction.
subject: Physics

preamble_text: A $-5.0 \mathrm{nC}$ charge is located at the origin and a $+5.0 \mathrm{nC}$ charge is located on the $x$-axis at $x=2.0 \mathrm{~m}$.
question: Find the electric field on the $x$-axis at $x=-1.0 \mathrm{~m}$.
answer:
$40 \mathrm{Vm}^{-1} \hat{i}$
$$
E=\frac{1}{4 \pi \epsilon_{0}}\left[\frac{q_{1}\left(r-r_{1}\right)}{\left|r-r_{1}\right|^{3}}+\frac{q_{2}\left(r-r_{2}\right)}{\left|r-r_{2}\right|^{3}}\right]=9.0 \times 10^{9} m F^{-1} \times\left[\frac{5.0 \times 10^{-9} C}{|-1.0 m-0|^{2}} \hat{i}-\frac{5.0 \times 10^{-9} C}{|-1.0 m-2.0 \mathrm{~m}|^{2}} \hat{i}\right]=40 \mathrm{Vm} \mathrm{m}^{-1} \hat{i}
$$
Or $40 \mathrm{~V} \mathrm{~m}^{-1}$ in the positive $x$ direction.
Note: $1 \mathrm{Vm}^{-1}=1 \mathrm{NC}^{-1}$
Where needed, take the Wien constant as $2.90 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{Km}$ and the Stefan-Boltzmann constant as $5.67 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{Wm}^{-2} \mathrm{~K}^{-4}$.

question: Of the Group (II) elements, calcium, strontium and barium form mainly ionic compounds while magnesium and beryllium form either partly covalent or predominantly covalent compounds. Why?

The cations formed have low polarising power because of the large ionic radii. Beryllium and magnesium have higher ionisation potentials and small cations formed which have high polarising power.

question: The Group (II) elements have higher melting points and greater hardness than Group (I) elements. Why?

$$

question: Explain why although the ammonia molecule has three hydrogen atoms bonded to a central nitrogen atom the molecule is not trigonal planar in shape.
answer: The orbitals of the nitrogen undergo $\mathrm{sp}^{3}$ hybridisation. Three of the four hybridised orbitals have an unpaired electron each, the fourth having an electron pair. The singly occupied orbitals form covalent bonds with hydrogen atoms occupying the three corners of a tetrahedron. These are not in the same plane as the nitrogen. A trigonal pyramid is formed.
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain why the $\mathrm{BCl}_{3}$ molecule is trigonal planar but not trigonal pyramidal like $\mathrm{NH}_{3}$.
answer: Three of the boron orbitals undergo $\mathrm{sp}^{2}$ hybridisation, each hybridised orbital singly occupied. The three orbitals are uniformly spread around boron giving a trigonal plane with the boron at the centre. The remaining empty p-orbital is perpendicular to the plane.
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain why water molecule is a bent molecule and not a linear one.
answer: The orbitals of oxygen atom undergo $\mathrm{sp}^{3}$ hybridisation, two of the orbitals containing electron pair each, the other two singly occupied. The singly occupied orbitals form bonds with two hydrogen atoms. The bond angle will therefore be close to the tetrahedral angle of $109.5^{\circ}$ instead of $180^{\circ}$.
subject: Chemistry

$$
\mathrm{T}=270 \mathrm{~K} ; \quad \mathrm{R}=8.31 \mathrm{JK}^{-1} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1} ; \mathrm{n}=\frac{48.0}{32.0} ; \quad \mathrm{V} \quad=\quad 18.0 \mathrm{dm}^{3}
$$

$$

question: The first ionisation energy of elements generally increases from left to right in a Period of the Periodic Table, that is in the order of increasing atomic number. In that case why is the first ionisation energy of oxygen lower than that of nitrogen. Oxygen has a higher atomic number.
answer: Oxygen has a $\mathrm{p}^{4}$ subshell electron configuration in the neutral atom and loses an electron readily to form a more stable half-filled $p^{3}$ subshell. The neutral atom of nitrogen on the other hand has a $\mathrm{p}^{3}$ subshell which is stable and losing an electron is energetically not that favourable.
subject: Chemistry

question: Hydrogen has a lower first ionisation energy than helium although hydrogen has a smaller atomic radius. How can this be justified?
answer: Though the first ionisation energy of an element depends on atomic radius, other factors such as effective nuclear charge is also important. The net attractive force of the two protons on the valence electrons in helium is much greater than the attractive force of one proton on one valence electron in hydrogen. Hence the first ionisation energy of helium is bigger.
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain why sodium has a higher first ionisation energy than potassium?
answer: Sodium and potassium are in the same Group of the Periodic Table. Down the Group, atomic radius increases. The attractive force on the valence electron decreases from sodium to potassium. Hence, potassium has the lower first ionisation energy.
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain why magnesium oxide is expected to be less soluble in water than sodium chloride?
answer: Solubility depends on lattice energy (which requires energy in-put) and hydration energy (which gives out energy). MgO has higher combined ionic charges $-4\left(-2^{*}+2\right)$ compared to the $\mathrm{NaCl}$ combined charge of $-2\left(-1^{*}+1\right)$. Hence larger energy will be required to separate the $\mathrm{Mg}^{2+}$ and $\mathrm{O}^{2-}$ in the solid state than $\mathrm{Na}^{+}$and $\mathrm{Cl}^{-}$.

preamble_text:
Magnesium nitride, a pale-yellow solid is formed when magnesium is heated to redness in ammonia, according to the equation:
$3 \mathrm{Mg}+2 \mathrm{NH}_{3} \rightarrow \mathrm{Mg}_{3} \mathrm{~N}_{2}+\frac{3}{} \mathrm{H}_{2}$.
$\mathrm{Mg}=24.0 ; \mathrm{N}=14.0 ; \mathrm{H}=1.00$
question: Calculate the mass of the nitride formed when $36.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of magnesium is heated in $30.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of ammonia.
answer:
$3 \mathrm{Mg}+2 \mathrm{NH}_{3} \rightarrow \mathrm{Mg}_{3} \mathrm{~N}_{2}+3 \mathrm{H}_{2}$
$\begin{array}{lll}72.0 & 34.0 & 100\end{array}$
$36.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of $\mathrm{Mg}$ would require $17.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of $\mathrm{NH}_{3}$ hence $\mathrm{Mg}$ is the limiting reagent.
Mass of nitride to be obtained from $36.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of $\mathrm{Mg}=\frac{36.0}{72.0} * 100=50.0 \mathrm{~g}$
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text:
Magnesium nitride, a pale-yellow solid is formed when magnesium is heated to redness in ammonia, according to the equation:
$3 \mathrm{Mg}+2 \mathrm{NH}_{3} \rightarrow \mathrm{Mg}_{3} \mathrm{~N}_{2}+\frac{3}{} \mathrm{H}_{2}$.
$\mathrm{Mg}=24.0 ; \mathrm{N}=14.0 ; \mathrm{H}=1.00$
question: Calculate the mass of $\mathrm{Mg}_{3} \mathrm{~N}_{2}$ to be formed from $96.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of $\mathrm{Mg}$ in excess ammonia.
answer:
$3 \mathrm{Mg}+2 \mathrm{NH}_{3} \rightarrow \mathrm{Mg}_{3} \mathrm{~N}_{2}+3 \mathrm{H}_{2}$
Mass of $\mathrm{Mg}_{3} \mathrm{~N}_{2}$ from $72.0 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{Mg} \quad=100 \mathrm{~g}$
Mass of $\mathrm{Mg}_{3} \mathrm{~N}_{2}$ from $96.0 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{Mg}=\frac{96.0}{72.0} * 100=133 \mathrm{~g}$
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text:
Magnesium nitride, a pale-yellow solid is formed when magnesium is heated to redness in ammonia, according to the equation:
$3 \mathrm{Mg}+2 \mathrm{NH}_{3} \rightarrow \mathrm{Mg}_{3} \mathrm{~N}_{2}+\frac{3}{} \mathrm{H}_{2}$.

question: Calculate the volume of $\mathrm{H}_{2}$ at STP expected from a reaction of $51.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of ammonia and $96.0 \mathrm{~g}$ magnesium. Molar volume of an ideal gas at STP $=22.4 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$.
answer:
$3 \mathrm{Mg}+2 \mathrm{NH}_{3} \rightarrow \mathrm{Mg}_{3} \mathrm{~N}_{2}+3 \mathrm{H}_{2}$
$72.0 \quad 34.0 \quad 3 \times 22.4 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ at STP
Moles of $\mathrm{NH}_{3}$ in $51.0 \mathrm{~g}=3.00 \mathrm{~mol}$; $\quad$ Moles of $\mathrm{Mg}$ in $96 \mathrm{~g}=4 \mathrm{~mol}$
Moles of $\mathrm{Mg}$ needed for $3 \mathrm{~mol}$ of $\mathrm{NH}_{3}=4.5 \mathrm{~mol}$, hence $\mathrm{Mg}$ is the limiting reagent.
Since Mg: $\mathrm{H}_{2}$ mole ratio $=1: 1$
Volume of $\mathrm{H}_{2}$ expected at STP $=22.4 * 4=89.6 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$
subject: Chemistry

question: Mention one adaptations of C4 plants that makes them superior to C3 plants.
answer:
1. They have a special type of leaf anatomy/ Kranz leaf anatomy. (The bundle sheath cells may form several layers around the vascular bundles; they are characterized by having a large number of chloroplasts, thick walls impervious to gaseous exchange and no intercellular spaces. C4 plants lack photorespiration)
2. They tolerate higher temperatures
3. They show a response to high light intensities.
4. They lack photorespiration.
5. They have greater productivity of biomass.
6. They can photosynthesis in saline and arid regions
7. They can withstand Low $\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ conditions

question:

6.00 Faraday produces, $2 * 27.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of $\mathrm{Al}$

Volume of oxygen that would be produced at STP by a charge of $9.60 \mathrm{~F}$
$=\left(\frac{9.60}{6.00}\right) * \frac{3}{2} * 22.4 \mathrm{dm}^{3} \quad=\quad 53.76=53.8 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$

question: Explain how an aqueous solution of $\mathrm{SnCl}_{4}$ becomes acidic?
answer:
The molecule $\mathrm{SnCl}_{4}$ dissolves in water to form initially $\mathrm{SnCl}_{4}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)_{2}$. The water molecules bonded to the tin then ionise/hydrolyse to give $\mathrm{H}_{3} \mathrm{O}^{+}$which makes the solution acidic.
$$
\mathrm{SnCl}_{4}\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}\right)_{2}+\quad \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O} \rightarrow \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{SnCl}_{4}(\mathrm{HO})_{2} \quad \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{H}\left[\mathrm{SnCl}_{2}(\mathrm{OH})_{2}\right]+\mathrm{H}_{3} \mathrm{O}^{+}
$$
$+\mathrm{Cl}^{-}$

question: Preamble to all schools; There are five postulates of the Kinetic Molecular Theory. State any one of them and show how the postulate is manifested in the behaviour of gases.
answer:
Any one of the following
a) Gases are composed of molecules/atoms whose size is negligible compared to the average distance between them. Implication: Gases can easily be compressed
b) Molecules/atoms move randomly in straight lines in all directions and at various speed.
Implication: Brownian motion or pressure of a gas in container uniform on all the surfaces.
c) The forces of attraction or repulsion between two molecules/atoms in a gas are very weak or negligible.
Implication: Gases fill any available space because of very small intermolecular forces. Also gases in a mixture behave independently.
d) When molecules/atoms collide with one another the collisions are elastic.
Implication: Isolated quantity of a gas does not lose pressure.
e) The average kinetic energy of a gaseous molecule/atom is proportional to temperature.
Implication: Brownian motion, pressure or volume increases with temperature.
subject: Chemistry

question: State the products obtained at the respective electrodes when dilute sodium chloride is electrolysed using inert electrodes and give the amounts that will be formed after passing a charge of 0.600 Faraday.
answer:
Electrolysis of aqueous $\mathrm{NaCl}$ using inert electrodes is equivalent to electrolysis of $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$.
Anode: Oxygen gas is formed; Cathode: Hydrogen gas is formed.
$2 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}+4$ Faraday $\rightarrow 2 \mathrm{H}_{2}+\mathrm{O}_{2}$
$\therefore \mathrm{H}_{2}$ formed after 0.600 Faraday $=\quad(0.600 / 4)^{*} 2=\quad 0.300$ mols
$\mathrm{O}_{2}$ formed after 0.600 Faraday $=\quad(0.600 / 4)^{*} 1=\quad 0.150$ mols
subject: Chemistry

question: State the expected products when molten $\mathrm{KBr}$ is electrolysed using graphite as the electrodes. Give the amounts of the products that will be formed after passing 0.500 Faraday of charge.
answer:
Anode: Bromine gas: Cathode Potassium metal 
$\begin{array}{lll}\mathrm{KBr}+\text { 1Faraday } \rightarrow & \mathrm{K}+\frac{1 / 2 \mathrm{Br}_{2}}{} \\ \text { Amount of } \mathrm{K} \text { formed } & =\quad(0.500 / 1)^{*} 1=0.500 \mathrm{~mol} \\ \text { Amount of } \mathrm{Br}_{2} \text { formed }= & 0.250 \mathrm{~mol}\end{array}$
subject: Chemistry

question: The electrolysis of concentrated solution of $\mathrm{NaCl}$ is an industrial method for manufacturing sodium hydroxide. Give the appropriate equations at the electrodes to show how $\mathrm{NaOH}$ is formed.
answer:
At the anode, $\mathrm{Cl}^{-}$is oxidised
$2 \mathrm{Cl}^{-} \quad-2 \mathrm{e} \quad \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{Cl}_{2(\mathrm{~g})}$
At the cathode, $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$ is reduced
$2 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}+2 \mathrm{e} \rightarrow \mathrm{H}_{2}+2 \mathrm{OH}^{-}$
Adding (1) and (2)

question: Define a base according to the Arrhenius concept of Acids and Bases.

question: Give the main difference or differences between the definition of a base according to Arrhenius on one hand and that of Bronsted-Lowry on the other hand.
answer:
(1) Arrhenius definition restricts bases to substances that contain $\mathrm{OH}^{-}$ ions whereas Bronsted-Lowry definition defines a base including the $\mathrm{OH}^{-}$ ion as any substance that can accept a proton.
(2) Arrhenius restricts the medium to water only but in the Bronsted - Lowry concept the acceptance of the proton could be in any medium.

question: Explain why the acid dissociation constant of H3PO4 molecule is larger than that of H2PO4-.
answer: Acid strength of a molecule depends on its ability to donate a proton to a base. It is easier to remove a proton from a neutral molecule H3PO4 than from a negatively charged ion, H2PO4-.
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain why $\mathrm{HF}$ is an acid but $\mathrm{NH} 3$ is basic.
answer: Acidic strength depends on ability of molecule to donate a proton $\mathrm{H}+$. The $\mathrm{H}-\mathrm{F}$ bond is more polarised than the $\mathrm{N}-\mathrm{H}$ bond because of the higher electronegativity of $\mathrm{F}$ than $\mathrm{N}$. N prefers to use the electron pair on the nitrogen to form a bond with an $\mathrm{H}+$.
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain why the chloride ion can be predicted to be a weaker base than NH3 molecule.
answer: The conjugate acid of the chloride ion is $\mathrm{HCl}$, which is a strong acid. The conjugate acid of $\mathrm{NH} 3$ is $\mathrm{NH} 4+$, a weak acid weaker than $\mathrm{HCl}$.
subject: Chemistry

question: $\mathrm{ClO}^{-}, \mathrm{Cl}^{-}, \mathrm{OH}^{-}/ \mathrm{Pt} \quad 0.900 \mathrm{~V} ; \quad \mathrm{MnO}_{4}^{-}, \mathrm{Mn}^{2+}, \mathrm{H}^{+}/ \mathrm{Pt} \quad 1.49 \mathrm{~V}$
answer:
Oxidation: $\mathrm{Cl}^{-}-2 \mathrm{e}+2 \mathrm{OH}^{-} \quad \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{ClO}^{-}+\mathrm{H}_{2}\mathrm{O} \ldots$ (1)
$-0.900$
Reduction: $\mathrm{MnO_{4}}^{-}+5 \mathrm{e}+8 \mathrm{H}^{+}\quad \rightarrow \mathrm{Mn}^{2+}+$
$4 \mathrm{H}_{2}\mathrm{O}$
$+1.49$
Multiply (1) by 5 and (2) by 2 and add.
Cell reaction: $5 \mathrm{Cl}^{-}+2 \mathrm{MnO_{4}}^{-}+6 \mathrm{H}^{+}\rightarrow 5 \mathrm{ClO}^{-} +2 \mathrm{Mn}^{2+} +$ $3 \mathrm{H}_{2}\mathrm{O}$
Initial emf $=1.49-0.900=0.590 \mathrm{~V}$

answer:
Oxidation: $\mathrm{Al} \quad-\quad 3 \mathrm{e} \quad \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{Al}^{3+}\ldots$ (1) $1.66 \mathrm{~V}$
Reduction: $\mathrm{NO}_{3}^{-}+3 \mathrm{e}+4 \mathrm{H}^{+}\quad \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{NO}+2 \mathrm{H}_{2}\mathrm{O} \ldots$ (2) $0.96 \mathrm{~V}$
Cell reaction: $\mathrm{Al}+ \mathrm{NO_{3}}^{-}+4 \mathrm{H}^{+}\rightarrow  \mathrm{Al}^{3+} + \mathrm{NO} +$ $2 \mathrm{H}_{2}\mathrm{O}$

question: A hydrocarbon contains $85.7 \%$ carbon. Determine its empirical formula and hence its molecular formula if the molar mass is 70.0. $\mathrm{C}=12.0 ; \quad \mathrm{H}=$ 1.00

question: Find the $x$-component of the electric field in a region where the scalar potential is given by $V(x, y, z)=a x^{2}+b y^{2}+c z^{2}$
answer:
$-2 a x$
$$
E_{x}=-\frac{\partial V}{\partial x}=-\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\left(a x^{2}+b y^{2}+c z^{2}\right)=-2 a x
$$
subject: Physics

question: Find the $y$-component of the electric field in a region where the scalar potential is given by $V(x, y, z)=q\left(x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}\right)^{-1 / 2}$
answer:
$q y\left(x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}\right)^{-3 / 2}$
$$
E_{y}=-\frac{\partial V}{\partial y}=-\frac{\partial}{\partial y} q\left(x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}\right)^{-1 / 2}=q y\left(x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}\right)^{-3 / 2}
$$
subject: Physics

question: The scalar potential in a region is given by $V(x, y, z)=U e^{-k y} \cos \cos (\pi x / b) \sin \sin (\pi z / a)$. Find the $z-$ component of the electric field in the region.
answer:
$-\frac{\pi}{a} U e^{-k y} \cos \cos (\pi x / b) \cos \cos (\pi z / a)$
$$
E_{z}=-\frac{\partial V}{\partial z}=-\frac{\partial}{\partial z} U e^{-k y} \cos \cos (\pi x / b) \sin \sin (\pi z / a)=-\frac{\pi}{a} U e^{-k y} \cos \cos (\pi x / b) \cos \cos (\pi z / a)
$$
subject: Physics

question: Apart from the Law of Conservation of Matter there are three other laws that govern Chemical Combinations. Each School is to state one of the laws
answer:
i. The Law of Constant Composition OR
The Law of Constant Proportions OR
The Law of Definite Proportions:
The Law states that the proportions of elements in a compound are always the same no matter how the compound is made.
ii. The Law of Multiple Proportions:
It states that when two elements, $A$ and $B$ combine to form more than one compound the masses of $B$ that combine with the fixed mass of $\mathrm{A}$ are in simple ratio (e.g. $\mathrm{SO}_{2}$ and $\mathrm{SO}_{3}, 32 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{~S}$ to $32 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{O}_{2}$ and $32 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{~S}$ to $48 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{O}$. Then for fixed mass of $\mathrm{S}$ 32; ratio of $\mathrm{O}$ is $32 \mathrm{~g}: 48 \mathrm{~g} ;$ or $2: 3)$
iii. The Law of Equivalent Proportions OR
The Law of Reciprocal Proportions OR
The Law of Permanent Ratios: It states that, if two elements A and B each form a compound with a third element $\mathrm{C}$, then the compound of $\mathrm{A}$ and $\mathrm{B}$ will contain relative proportions in which they react with C (e.g. Assume A is carbon, B is sulphur and C is hydrogen. Consider compounds $\mathrm{CH}_{4}[\mathrm{AC}]$ and $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{~S}[\mathrm{BC}]$, then, carbon and sulphur should combine in the ratio $\left.1: 2, \mathrm{CS}_{2},[\mathrm{AB}]\right)$
subject: Chemistry

question: One of the buffers that maintain the $\mathrm{pH}$ of blood in human body within its accepted limits is trioxocarbonate (IV) acid, also known as carbonic acid and its conjugate base hydrogen trioxocarbonate (IV) ion. If the minimum $\mathrm{pH}$ that a normal blood could attain is 7.36 , what should be the ratio of the acid to the conjugate base concentrations to maintain that $\mathrm{pH}$ ? The pKa of trioxocarbonate (IV) acid is 6.36 .
answer:
Use the Henderson Hasselbalch equation for buffers:
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{pH}=\mathrm{pKa}+\quad \log _{10} \frac{[\text { base }]}{[\text { acid }]} \\
& 7.36=6.36+\quad \log _{10} \frac{[\text { base }]}{[\text { acid }]} \\
& \log _{10} \frac{[\text { base }]}{[\text { acid }]}=\quad 1 ; \quad\left[\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3}\right]:\left[\mathrm{HCO}_{3}{ }^{-}\right]=1: 10
\end{aligned}
$$
subject: Chemistry

question:
The highest $\mathrm{pH}$ allowed for human blood is 7.42. Which of the following four acid-conjugate base pairs would be the best to maintain the $\mathrm{pH}$ at 7.42 ?
$\mathrm{HCO}_{3}{ }^{-} / \mathrm{CO}_{3}{ }^{2-}, \quad \mathrm{H}_{3} \mathrm{PO}_{4} / \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{PO}_{4}{ }^{-}, \quad \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{PO}_{4} / / \mathrm{HPO}_{4}{ }^{2-}, \quad \mathrm{HPO}_{4}{ }^{2-} / \mathrm{PO}_{4}{ }^{3-}$.
The $\mathrm{pKa}$ of $\mathrm{HCO}_{3}{ }^{-}$is 10.3 and the three $\mathrm{pKa}$ 's for $\mathrm{H}_{3} \mathrm{PO}_{4}$ are $2.50,7.20$ and 12.38 .
Determine if the base to acid ratio will be less or greater than 1 at that $\mathrm{pH}$.
answer:
$\quad$ The best pair will be $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{PO}_{4} / \mathrm{HPO}_{4}{ }^{2-}$.
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{pH}=\quad \mathrm{pKa}+\log _{10} \frac{[\text { base }]}{[\text { acid }]} \\
& 7.42=7.20+\log _{10} \frac{[\text { base }]}{[\text { acid }]} \\
& \log _{10} \frac{[\text { base }]}{[\text { acid }]}=0.22
\end{aligned}
$$
Hence base/acid ratio is $>1 ; \quad$ ( or acid/base $<1$ )
subject: Chemistry

question:
You are provided with $500 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of $0.120 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$ ethanoic acid and $10.0 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{NaOH}$. How would you prepare $500 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of a buffer whose $\mathrm{pH}$ is 4.76 ? The $\mathrm{pKa}$ of ethanoic acid is 4.76 .
$$
\mathrm{Na}=23.0 ; \mathrm{O}=16.0 ; \mathrm{H}=1.00
$$
answer:
For a buffer
$$
\mathrm{pH}=\mathrm{pKa}+\log _{10} \frac{[\text { base }]}{[\text { acid }]}
$$
$4.76=4.76+\log _{10}[$ base $]$
So, for this buffer, $\quad$ bbase $] \quad$ [acid $]$
mmols of ethanoic acid present $=500 * 0.120=60.0$
30.0 mmol must be converted into the conjugate base. Formula mass of $\mathrm{NaOH}=$ $40.0 \mathrm{~g}$
$$
\therefore 30.0 \mathrm{mmol} \text { of } \mathrm{NaOH}=30.0^{*} 10^{-3 * 40.0}=1.20 \mathrm{~g}
$$
$1.20 \mathrm{~g}$ of $\mathrm{NaOH}$ must be weighed and dissolved in/added to the 500 solution of ethanoic acid.
OR any method which gives a total volume of $500 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ and contains equal moles of ethanoic acid and sodium ethanoate.

preamble_text: State what happens during the following stages of embryonic development in mammals.
question: Cleavage
answer: The fertilized egg divides without growth occurring, forming a ball of cells.
subject: Biology

preamble_text: State what happens during the following stages of embryonic development in mammals.
question: Gastrulation
answer: Massive movement of cells make the primary axis visible and organize the three embryonic tissues. / There is rearrangement of the cells of the blastula and ultimately forms the three germ layers of the embryo. (Primary layers that will form all of the major body and organ systems of the organism)
subject: Biology

preamble_text: State what happens during the following stages of embryonic development in mammals.
question: Organogenesis
answer: There is the formation of the neural tube which is precursor to the spinal cord and the brain, / The three germ tissue layers of the embryo, which are the ectoderm, endoderm, and mesoderm, develop into the internal organs of the organism.
subject: Biology

question: Why is metaphase the best time to count and study the number and morphology of chromosomes?
answer:
In metaphase, all of the chromosomes become distinctly visible and are aligned at the centre/equatorial plate of the cell in preparation for separating in anaphase.
Since they're all lined up, they are easier to study them and count.
subject: Biology

question: Why is the onion root tip a very good material for the study of mitosis in a laboratory?
answer: In plants mitosis occurs in the meristematic cells of root tip or shoot tip. The cells divide at a faster rate so the root tip shows active cell division and is used in the laboratory to study mitosis.
subject: Biology

question: Explain why in meiosis, the daughter cells differ from parent cell as well as amongst themselves.
answer: In meiosis, the daughter cells differ from parent cell as well as amongst themselves due to segregation, independent assortment and crossing over. These lead to new combinations of genes or characters resulting in variations.
subject: Biology

question: Explain why aging should bring about a decline in vital capacity of the lungs and pulmonary ventilation.
answer: Aging is associated with a gradual loss of elastic tissue in the lungs and a decline in muscle power which affect the rate and extent of chest expansion
subject: Biology

question: Why should ones muscles get weaker with age?
answer: As one gets older, muscle fibres tend to be replaced with connective tissues and collagen that are not as strong as the fibres thereby making the muscles weaker.
subject: Biology

question: Explain why the number of nerve cells (neurons) in the brain of humans decline with age.
answer: Unlike most cells of the body, nerve cells either cannot naturally regenerate themselves by dividing to replace dead cells, or they do so very slowly. As a result the number of nerve cells in the brain declines with age.
subject: Biology
