preamble_text: The position vector of a particle is given as a function of time $t$ by $r=a t^{2} \hat{i}+b t \hat{j}$ where $a=2 m s^{-2}$ and $b=30{m s^{-1}}^{-1}$
question: Determine the velocity of the particle at $t=5 \mathrm{~s}$.
answer:
$(20 \hat{i}+30 \hat{j}) m^{-1}$
$$
v=\frac{d r}{d t}=2 a t \hat{i}+b \hat{j}=\left(2 \times 2 m s^{-2} \times 5 s\right) \hat{i}+\left(30 \mathrm{~ms}^{-1}\right) \hat{j}=(20 \hat{i}+30 \hat{j}) \mathrm{ms}^{-1}
$$
subject: Physics

preamble_text: The position vector of a particle is given as a function of time $t$ by $r=a t^{2} \hat{i}+b t \hat{j}$ where $a=2 m s^{-2}$ and $b=30{m s^{-1}}^{-1}$
question: Determine the average velocity of the particle between $t=0$ and $t=5 \mathrm{~s}$.
answer:
$(10 \hat{i}+30 \hat{j}) \mathrm{ms}^{-1}$
$$
v_{a v g}=\frac{\Delta r}{\Delta t}=\frac{\left[2 m s^{-1} \times(5 s)^{2} \hat{i}+\left(30 m s^{-1} \times 5 s\right) \hat{j}\right]-\left[2 m s^{-1} \times(0 s)^{2} \hat{i}+\left(30 m s^{-1} \times 0 s\right) \hat{j}\right]}{5 s-0 s}=(10 \hat{i}+30 \hat{j}) m^{-1}
$$
subject: Physics

preamble_text: The position vector of a particle is given as a function of time $t$ by $r=a t^{2} \hat{i}+b t \hat{j}$ where $a=2 m s^{-2}$ and $b=30{m s^{-1}}^{-1}$
question: Determine the displacement of the particle between $t=0$ and $t=5 \mathrm{~s}$.
answer:
$(50 \hat{i}+150 \hat{j}) m$
$$
\Delta r=\left[2 m s^{-1} \times(5 s)^{2} \hat{i}+\left(30 m s^{-1} \times 5 s\right) \hat{j}\right]-\left[2 m s^{-1} \times(0 s)^{2} \hat{i}+\left(30 m s^{-1} \times 0 s\right) \hat{j}\right]=(50 \hat{i}+150 \hat{j}) m
$$
subject: Physics

question: For the preparation of a standard solution of $\mathrm{Na}^{+}$ions, $25 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of a stock solution of $0.20$ moldm ${ }^{-3} \mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{SO}_{4}$ is diluted to $1 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ with deionized water. $10 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of the diluted solution is further diluted to $50 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ and labelled $\mathrm{A}$. Calculate the concentration of $\mathrm{Na}^{+}$ions in moldm ${ }^{-3}$ of $\mathrm{A}$.
answer:
Concentration of $\mathrm{Na}^{+}$in stock solution $=0.40 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$
For A. First dilution: $25 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ to $1000 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} \quad 1$ in 40
Second dilution $10 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ to $50 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} \quad 1$ in 5
Total dilution $\quad 1$ in 200
Concentration of $\mathrm{Na}^{+}$in $\mathrm{A}=0.4 / 200=0.002 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$

question: $300 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of $0.20 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$ of $\mathrm{NaOH}$ is partially neutralized with $100 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of $0.10 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$ of $\mathrm{HCl}$. What is the new concentration of the $\mathrm{NaOH}$.
answer:
mmoles of $\mathrm{NaOH}$ initially present $=60$
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \begin{array}{lll}\text { mmoles of } \mathrm{HCl} \text { added } & = & 10\end{array} \\
& \text { mmoles of } \mathrm{NaOH} \text { left } \quad=60-10=50 \\
& \text { New concentration }=\left(\text { mmole/volume) } 50 / 400=0.125 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}\right.
\end{aligned}
$$
subject: Chemistry

question: From a stock solution of $0.50 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$ of $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{SO}_{4}$, a $500 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ solution which should be $0.30$ moldm ${ }^{-3}$ with respect to $\mathrm{Na}^{+}$ions is to be prepared. answer:
$\quad 0.50 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3} \mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{SO}_{4} \quad=\quad 1.0 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3} \mathrm{Na}^{+}$
To obtain a concentration of $0.30$ moldm$^{-3}$, a dilution of 3 in 10 has to be done.

preamble_text:
When ammonia burns in limited amount of oxygen, NO gas and steam are formed. The balanced equation is as follows:
$$
\begin{aligned}
& 4 \mathrm{NH}_{3(\mathrm{~g})} \quad+\quad 5 \mathrm{O}_{2(\mathrm{~g})} \rightarrow \quad 4 \mathrm{NO}_{(\mathrm{g})} \quad+\quad 6 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{(\mathrm{g})} \\
& \mathrm{O}=16.0 ; \mathrm{N}=14.0 ; \mathrm{H}=1.0
\end{aligned}
$$
question: Calculate the moles of oxygen needed to burn $51.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of ammonia. Give your answer to 2 places of decimal
answer:
Molar mass of $\mathrm{NH}_{3}=17.0$;
$$
\text { Moles of } \mathrm{NH}_{3} \text { in } 51 \mathrm{~g}=\quad 51 / 17=3
$$
4 moles required 5 moles of $\mathrm{O}_{2}$
3 moles will require $=(3 / 4) * 5=3.75$ moles
subject: Chemistry

question: Calculate the moles of ammonia that will burn to produce $90.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of steam. Give your answer to two places of decimal
answer:
$\quad$ Molar mass of water $=18$;
Moles of water $\quad=\quad 90 / 18=5$
But 6 moles of water $\equiv \quad 4$ moles of $\mathrm{NH}_{3}$
Hence, 5 moles of water $=(5 / 6) * 4 \quad=\quad 3.33$ moles

Moles of $\mathrm{NH}_{3}$ in $85 \mathrm{~g}=\quad 85 / 17=5$ moles

$=140$

preamble_text: Explain the following
question: Mimicry
answer: A phenomenon characterized by the superficial resemblance of two or more organisms that are not closely related taxonomically which confers an advantage such as protection from predation
subject: Biology

preamble_text: Explain the following
question: Batesian mimicry
answer:
A form of biological resemblance in which a noxious, or dangerous, organism (the model), equipped with a warning system such as 
conspicuous coloration, is mimicked by a harmless organism (the mimic).
subject: Biology

preamble_text: Explain the following
question: Mullerian mimicry
answer:
A form of biological resemblance in which two or more unrelated noxious, or dangerous, organisms exhibit closely similar warning systems, such as the same pattern of bright colors.
(In Mullerian mimicry, the species is both the model and the mimic unlike in Batesian mimicry where it can only either be the mimic or the model)
subject: Biology

question:
Trioxonitrate $(\mathrm{V})$ acid decomposes when exposed to light according to the following equation.
$4 \mathrm{HNO}_{3(\mathrm{aq})} \rightarrow 4 \mathrm{NO}_{2(\mathrm{~g})} \quad+\quad 2 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{(1)}+\mathrm{O}_{2(\mathrm{~g})}$
Determine whether this decomposition is exothermic or endothermic by calculating the enthalpy of reaction. Use the following enthalpies of formation:
$\mathrm{HNO}_{3(\mathrm{~g})} \quad-208.3 \mathrm{kJmol}^{-1} ; \quad \mathrm{NO}_{2(\mathrm{~g})} 33.2 \mathrm{kJmol}^{-1} ; \quad \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{(\mathrm{l})}-286 \mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}$

question: The position vector in meters of a particle is $3 \hat{i}+2 \hat{j}$. What is the position of the particle relative to the point with position vector $3 \hat{j}+2 \hat{k}$ in meters?
answer:
$3 \hat{i}-\hat{j}-2 \hat{k}$ in meters
$$
r_{A B}=r_{A}-r_{B}=3 \hat{i}+2 \hat{j}-(3 \hat{j}+2 \hat{k})=3 \hat{i}-\hat{j}-2 \hat{k} \text { in meters }
$$
subject: Physics

question: The position vector of a particle is $3 \hat{i}+2 \hat{j}$ in meters. Find the displacement of the particle from the point with position vector $2 \hat{i}+3 \hat{j}$ in meters?
answer:
$\hat{i}-\hat{j}$ in meters
$$
r_{A B}=r_{A}-r_{B}=3 \hat{i}+2 \hat{j}-(2 \hat{i}+3 \hat{j})=\hat{i}-\hat{j} \text { in meters }
$$
subject: Physics

question: Find the position relative to $(2 \hat{i}+3 \hat{k}) m$ of a particle whose position vector is $(3 \hat{j}+2 \hat{k}) m$.
answer:
$(-2 \hat{i}+3 \hat{j}-\hat{k}) m$
$$
r_{A B}=r_{A}-r_{B}=(3 \hat{j}+2 \hat{k}) m-(2 \hat{i}+3 \hat{k}) m=(-2 \hat{i}+3 \hat{j}-\hat{k}) m
$$
subject: Physics

preamble_text: Explain the following with respect to the mammalian heart.
question: Pulmonary circuit.

subject: Biology

preamble_text: Explain the following with respect to the mammalian heart.
question: Systemic circuit.
answer: Oxygenated blood is pumped from the left ventricle to the systemic circulation through the aorta, to supply the rest of the body with oxygen. And the return of deoxygenated blood through the venae cavae, and into the right atrium. (Auricle)
subject: Biology

preamble_text: Explain the following with respect to the mammalian heart.
question: The two phases of the cardiac cycle.
answer: The diastole phase, in which the heart ventricles are relaxed and the heart fills with blood and the systole phase, in which the ventricles contract and pumps blood to the arteries
subject: Biology

preamble_text: From the named pair of half-cells, give the cell reaction of a possible voltaic cell that can be set up and the initial emf of the cell.
question: $\mathrm{Mg}^{2+} / \mathrm{Mg},-2.38 \mathrm{~V} ; \quad \mathrm{Al}^{3+} / \mathrm{Al},-1.66 \mathrm{~V}$
answer:
Oxidation: $\mathrm{Mg}-\quad 2 \mathrm{e} \quad \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{Mg}^{2+},+2.38 \mathrm{~V} \ldots \ldots$ (1)
Reduction: $\mathrm{Al}^{3+}+3 \mathrm{e} \rightarrow \mathrm{Al}, \quad-1.66 \mathrm{~V} \ldots \ldots(2)$
Multiply (1) by 3 and (2) by 2 and add
Cell reaction: $3 \mathrm{Mg}+2 \mathrm{Al}^{3+} \rightarrow \quad 3 \mathrm{Mg}^{2+}+\quad 2 \mathrm{Al}$

question:
Calculate the enthalpy change per mole for incomplete combustion of gaseous methanal to $\mathrm{CO}$ and $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$. The balanced equation for the reaction is:
$2 \mathrm{HCHO}_{(\mathrm{g})}+\mathrm{O}_{2(\mathrm{~g})} \rightarrow 2 \mathrm{CO}_{(\mathrm{g})} \quad+\quad 2 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{(\mathrm{l})}$
The enthalpies of formation all in $\mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}$ of $\mathrm{CO}_{(\mathrm{g})}, \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$ (l) and $\mathrm{HCHO}_{(\mathrm{g})}$ are $-110.5,-285.8$ and $108.6$ respectively.
answer:
$2 \mathrm{HCHO}_{(\mathrm{g})}+\mathrm{O}_{2(\mathrm{~g})} \rightarrow 2 \mathrm{CO}_{(\mathrm{g})} \quad+\quad 2 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{(\mathrm{l})}$
$\Delta \mathrm{H}$ reaction $=-(2 * 110.5)-(2 * 285.8)-(-2 * 108.6)$
$$
=-221.0-571.6+217.2=\quad-575.4 \text { or }-5.75 * 10^{2} \mathrm{~kJ}
$$
For one mole $\mathrm{HCHO} \Delta \mathrm{H}$ reaction $=-287.7$ or $-2.88 * 10^{2} \mathrm{~kJ}$
subject: Chemistry

question: A $2 \mathrm{~kg}$ object moving at $5 \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}$ collides with and sticks to a stationary object and the two move together at $2 \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}$. Find the mass of the stationary object.
answer:
$3 \mathrm{~kg}$
$$
m_{2}=m_{1} v_{1} / v-m_{1}=m_{1}\left(v_{1} / v-1\right)=2 \mathrm{~kg} \times\left[\left(5 m \mathrm{~s}^{-1}\right) /\left(2 m \mathrm{~s}^{-1}\right)-1\right]=3 \mathrm{~kg}
$$
subject: Physics

question: Explain why the first ionization energy of beryllium atomic number 4, is higher than the first ionization energy of lithium atomic number 3.
answer:
Beryllium has electronic configuration of $1 \mathrm{~s}^{2} 2 \mathrm{~s}^{2}$ which is more stable than that of lithium which is $1 \mathrm{~s}^{2} 2 \mathrm{~s}^{1}$.
Secondly, the atomic radius of beryllium is smaller than that of lithium.
Removing an electron from beryllium atom will therefore require more energy than in lithium.
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain why the first ionization energy of magnesium, atomic number 12 , is higher than that of aluminum, atomic number 13.
answer:
The electronic configuration of the valence shell for magnesium is more stable.
Removing that lone electron from the $3 p$ subshell in aluminum will require less energy.
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text: A sealed vessel at a pressure of $480 \mathrm{kPa}$ contains 4 moles of nitrogen, 5 moles of oxygen and 7 moles of argon.
question: Calculate the partial pressure of oxygen.
answer:
$\quad$ Partial pressure $=\quad$ mole fraction $*$ total pressure $=5 / 16 * 480$
$$
=\quad 150 \mathrm{kPa}
$$
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text: A sealed vessel at a pressure of $480 \mathrm{kPa}$ contains 4 moles of nitrogen, 5 moles of oxygen and 7 moles of argon.
question: Calculate the moles of helium that must be added to the vessel to increase the total pressure to 720 $\mathrm{kPa}$.
answer:
let the moles of helium be $\mathrm{x}$
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \text { Partial pressure of helium is } 720-480=240 \\
& \text { Partial Pressure }=\quad \text { mole fraction } * \text { total pressure } \\
& \text { Therefore, } 240=(\mathrm{x} / 16+\mathrm{x}) * 720 \\
& 240 *(16+\mathrm{x}) \quad=\quad 720 * \mathrm{x} ; \quad \text { Divide through by } 240 \\
& \text { Therefore } 16+\mathrm{x}=3 \mathrm{x} \\
& 2 \mathrm{x}=16 ; \text { hence, } \mathrm{x}=8
\end{aligned}
$$
subject: Chemistry

answer:
Balanced equation: $\mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CH}_{2} \mathrm{OH}+3 \mathrm{O}_{2} \rightarrow 2 \mathrm{CO}_{2}+$

3 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}

answer:

What is the concentration of the $\mathrm{NaOH}$ in $\mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$ in the final solution?
Give your answer to 4 places of decimal.
answer:
$1^{\text {st }}$ Dilution $20 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} \rightarrow 240 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} ; 1$ in 12
$2^{\text {nd }}$ Dilution $40 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} \rightarrow 120 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} ; 1 \quad$ in 3

$1^{\text {st }}$ dilution $\quad 50 \rightarrow 1000 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} ; 1$ in 20
$2^{\text {nd }}$ dilution $\quad 20 \rightarrow 400 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} ; 1 \quad$ in 20
Total dilution $=1$ in 400
Final concentration $=(0.1 / 400)^{*} 40 \mathrm{gdm}^{-3}=0.01 \mathrm{gdm}^{-3}$
Concentration in ppm $=10 \mathrm{ppm}$

answer:
40 pC
$$
Q=q+n e=32 \times 10^{-12} \mathrm{C}+5.0 \times 10^{7} \text { protons } \times 1.6 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{C} \text { per proton }=40 \times 10^{-12} \mathrm{C}=40 \mathrm{~F}

question:
Consider the following half-cells and their corresponding standard electrode potentials:
$$
\mathrm{Sn}^{2+} / \mathrm{Sn}-0.14 \mathrm{~V} ; \quad \mathrm{Cd}^{2+} / \mathrm{Cd}-0.40 \mathrm{~V} \text {. }
$$
If a primary cell were to be set up using the two half-cells, state which metal will constitute the anode and give your reasons.
answer:
Cd will be the anode.
Oxidation takes place at the anode. For positive emf, $-0.40 \mathrm{~V}$ has to be reversed.
Hence oxidation takes place in the cadmium half-cell, ie $\mathrm{Cd} / \mathrm{Cd}^{2+}$

question: $1 \mathrm{~kg}$ of bauxite after processing yields $306 \mathrm{~g}$ of alumina. What is the percentage aluminum in the bauxite assuming in the processing of the bauxite to alumina, no aluminum is lost? $\mathrm{Al} \quad=$
answer:
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \text { 27.0, } \mathrm{O}=16.0 \text {. } \\
& \text {Alumina }=\mathrm{Al}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3}=54+48=102 \\
& \text { Mass of } \mathrm{Al} \text { in } 306 \text { alumina }=(54 / 102)^{*} 306=162 \mathrm{~g} \text {. } \\
& \% \mathrm{Al} \text { in bauxite }=\quad(162 / 1000) * 100=\quad 16.2
\end{aligned}
$$
subject: Chemistry

question: Chromium may be obtained by reduction of its oxide $\mathrm{Cr}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3}$ with carbon at high temperatures. If $304 \mathrm{~g}$ of impure oxide yielded only $187.2 \mathrm{~g}$ of chromium, what was the percentage purity of the oxide?
answer:
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{Cr}=52, \mathrm{O}=16 \\
&\quad \mathrm{Cr}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3}=104+48=152 \\
& 152 \mathrm{~g} \text { of } \mathrm{Cr}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3} \equiv 104 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{Cr} \\
& \text { Therefore, } 304 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{of}_{2} \mathrm{Cr}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3} \equiv(304 / 152)^{*} 104 \quad=208 \mathrm{~g} \\
& \text { But only } 187.2 \mathrm{~g} \text { of } \mathrm{Cr} \text { obtained } \\
& \text { Therefore, } \% \text { purity }=(187.2 / 208)^{*} 100=90 \%
\end{aligned}
$$
subject: Chemistry

$\quad 2 \mathrm{~F} \equiv 1$ mole $\mathrm{Mg} \quad=\quad 24.0 \mathrm{~g}$

$$
\text { Therefore, efficiency }=20 / 24 * 100=83.3 \%
$$

question:
What mass of magnesium tetraoxosulphate (VI) heptahydrate is needed to prepare a $250 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ solution of $0.12$ moldm$^{-3}$ concentration? Give your answer to two places of decimal.
$$
\mathrm{Mg}=24.0, \mathrm{~S}=32.0, \mathrm{O}=16.0, \mathrm{H}=1.0
$$
answer:
$\mathrm{MgSO}_{4} \cdot 7 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}=24+32+64+7 * 18=120+126=246$
$$
1 \mathrm{dm}^{3} \text { solution of } 0.12 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3} \text { will require } 246 * 0.12=29.52
$$
Therefore, $250 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ solution of $0.12 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$ will require $29.52 / 4=7.38 \mathrm{~g}$
subject: Chemistry

question:
If a solution is $0.10 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$ with respect to $\mathrm{Cu}^{2+}$ ions, what mass of $\mathrm{CuSO}_{4} \cdot 5 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$ must be added to $500 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ to raise the concentration of the $\mathrm{Cu}^{2+}$ ions to $0.16 \mathrm{mldm}$. Give your answer to two places of decimal.
$$
\mathrm{Cu}=64.0, \mathrm{~S}=32.0, \mathrm{O}=16.0, \mathrm{H}=1.0
$$
answer:
$\mathrm{CuSO}_{4} \cdot 5 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}=64+32+64+5 * 18=250$
$1 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ of solution would require additional $0.06$ mol. of salt
Therefore, $500 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ would require $0.03 \mathrm{~mol}=0.03 * 250=7.50 \mathrm{~g}$
subject: Chemistry

question:
One $\mathrm{dm}^{3}$ of $0.20 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$ solution of cadmium (II) trioxonitrate (V) salt is allowed to evaporate to dryness. If in the process the salt forms tetrahydrate crystals, what mass of the hydrated salt will be obtained? Give your answer to 1 place of decimal.
$\mathrm{Cd}=112.0, \mathrm{O}=16.0, \mathrm{~N}=14.0, \mathrm{H}=1.0$
answer:
$\mathrm{Cd}\left(\mathrm{NO}_{3}\right)_{2} 4 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}=112+2 *(14+48)+4 * 18=308$
Hence, $1 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ of $0.20$ moldm$^{-3}$ solution will give $0.2 * 308=61.6 \mathrm{~g}$
subject: Chemistry

question:
Calculate the enthalpy change of the following reaction:
$$
\mathrm{CO}_{(\mathrm{g})}+3 \mathrm{H}_{2(\mathrm{~g})} \rightarrow \mathrm{CH}_{4(\mathrm{~g})}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{(\mathrm{g})}
$$
given that the enthalpies of formation in $\mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}$ of $\mathrm{CO}_{(\mathrm{g})}, \mathrm{CH}_{4(\mathrm{~g})}$ and $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{(\mathrm{g})}$, are $-110$, $75.0$ and $-241$ respectively.
answer:
$\Delta \mathrm{H}_{\mathrm{r}}=\sum \Delta \mathrm{H}$ (of formation of products) $-\sum$ ( $\Delta \mathrm{H}$ of formation of reactants).
$$
\begin{aligned}
&=\quad(-75-241)-\quad(-110-0) \quad=\quad-316+\quad 110 \\
&=\quad-206 \mathrm{kJmol}^{-1} .
\end{aligned}
$$

preamble_text:
When silver (I) oxide is heated alone at temperatures over $100^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$, it decomposes to metallic silver. The balanced equation is as follows:
$$
\begin{aligned}
& 2 \mathrm{Ag}_{2} \mathrm{O} \rightarrow 4 \mathrm{Ag}+\mathrm{O}_{2} \\
& \mathrm{Ag}=108.0, \quad \mathrm{O}=16.0
\end{aligned}
$$
question: Calculate the mass of silver metal that can be obtained from $23.2 \mathrm{~g}$ of the oxide if the conversion is only $90 \%$ efficient. Give your answer to two places of decimal.
answer:
$$
\begin{aligned}
&\mathrm{Ag}_{2} \mathrm{O} \quad \rightarrow \quad 2 \mathrm{Ag}+\frac{1}{2} \mathrm{O}_{2} \\
& (216+16) \quad 216 \\
& \text { Hence, } 23.2 \mathrm{~g} \text { of } \mathrm{Ag}_{2} \mathrm{O} \equiv \quad 21.6 \mathrm{~g} \text { of } \mathrm{Ag} \\
& \text { Mass of silver to be formed }=21.6 * 0.9=19.44
\end{aligned}
$$
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text:

question: Calculate the mass of the silver oxide that needs to be heated in order to obtain $64.8 \mathrm{~g}$ of silver, assuming the process is $100 \%$ efficient. Give your answer to one place of decimal.
answer:
$\mathrm{Ag}_{2} \mathrm{O} \quad \rightarrow \quad 2 \mathrm{Ag} \quad+\quad 1 / 2 \mathrm{O}_{2}$
$216 \mathrm{~g}$ of $\mathrm{Ag} \equiv \quad 232 \mathrm{~g}$ of the oxide
Therefore, $64.8$ of $\mathrm{Ag}=(64.8 / 216)^{*} 232=\quad 69.6 \mathrm{~g}$ of the oxide
subject: Chemistry

Therefore, $142 \mathrm{~g}$ in $10^{6} \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of water
i.e. $142 \mathrm{~g}$ in $10^{3} \mathrm{dm}^{3}$
Therefore, mass of drug dissolved in $1 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ of water $=0.142 \mathrm{~g}$
subject: Chemistry

question: An aqueous solution of a disinfectant is labelled as having a concentration of $37 \% \mathrm{w} / \mathrm{v}$. Explain how $5 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ solution of this disinfectant may have been prepared.
answer:
$37 \mathrm{w} / \mathrm{v}$ means:
$100 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ solution contain $37 \mathrm{~g}$ of pure disinfectant
Therefore, $1 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ solution contain $370 \mathrm{~g}$ of pure disinfectant
Therefore, mass of disinfectant required in $5 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ of solution $=5 * 370=1850 \mathrm{~g}$
Hence, weigh $1850 \mathrm{~g}$ (or $1.85 \mathrm{~kg}$ ) of the disinfectant and add water till volume is up to 5
$\mathrm{dm}^{3}$ (do not accept addition of $5 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ of water because the disinfectant may be a liquid)
subject: Chemistry

question: Convert the concentration of $0.0025 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$ of $\mathrm{NaOH}$ to $\mathrm{ppm} \mathrm{NaOH}$.
answer:
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{Na}=23.0, \mathrm{O}=16.0, \mathrm{H}=1.0 \\
& \quad \text { Molar mass of } \mathrm{NaOH}=40 \mathrm{~g} \\
& \text { Concentration in } \mathrm{gdm}^{-3}=40 * 0.0025=0.1 \mathrm{~g} \\
& \text { Therefore, } 1000 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} \text { contain } 0.1 \mathrm{~g} \\
& \text { Hence, } 10^{6} \mathrm{~cm}^{3} \text { contain } 100 \mathrm{~g} \\
& \text { Therefore, concentration in } \mathrm{ppm}=\quad 100
\end{aligned}
$$
subject: Chemistry

-Ray was deflected by both magnetic and electric field.

-Ray was deflected away from the negative plate and attracted towards the positive plate.

question: Calculate the enthalpy of combustion of $8.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of methane, $$ \mathrm{C}=12, \mathrm{H}=1 $$
answer:
The energy required to break all bonds per mole is $+2716 \mathrm{~kJ}$ and energy given out per mole when all new bonds are formed is $-3434 \mathrm{~kJ}$.
Molar mass of methane $=12+4=16$
$$
\text { Therefore, enthalpy of combustion per mole }=(-3434+2716)
$$
$$
\text { For } 8.0 \mathrm{~g} \text { of } \mathrm{CH}_{4}, \Delta \mathrm{H}=8 / 16(-718)=-359 \mathrm{~kJ} \text { or }-3.59 * 10^{2} \mathrm{k}
$$
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain why nitrogen with atomic number 7 has electron affinity of $-31 \mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}$ but carbon with atomic number 6 has electron affinity of $-123 \mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}$.

question: Explain why electron affinity decreases down a Group of the Periodic Table.

question: The electrode potentials of the half-cells $\mathrm{Cu}^{2+} / \mathrm{Cu}_{\text {and }} \mathrm{Hg}^{2+} / \mathrm{Hg}$ are $0.15 \mathrm{~V}$ and $0.85 \mathrm{~V}$ respectively. Give me the equation for the cell reaction of a primary cell that can be built from these two half cells.
answer:
The cell must have positive emf.
$\begin{array}{lllllllll}\text { Oxidation: } & \mathrm{Cu} & - & 2 \mathrm{e} & \rightarrow & \mathrm{Cu}^{2+} & & -0.15 \mathrm{~V} \\ \text { Reduction: } & \mathrm{Hg}^{2+} & + & 2 \mathrm{e} & \rightarrow & \mathrm{Hg} & & +0.85 \mathrm{~V} \\ \text { Cell reaction: } & \underline{\mathrm{Cu}}+ & \mathrm{Hg}^{2+} & \rightarrow & \mathrm{Cu}^{2+} & + & \mathrm{Hg} & +0.70 \mathrm{~V}\end{array}$
subject: Chemistry

question: The electrode potentials of the half-cells $\mathrm{Al}^{3+} / \mathrm{Al}$ and $\mathrm{Ni}^{2+} / \mathrm{Ni}$ are $-1.66 \mathrm{~V}$ and $-0.23 \mathrm{~V}$ respectively. Give me the cell reaction that occurs when these two half cells are used in constructing a primary cell.
answer:
The cell must have positive emf.
Oxidation: $\mathrm{Al} \quad-\quad 3 \mathrm{e} \quad \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{Al}^{3+} \ldots \ldots(1)$
Reduction: $\mathrm{Ni}^{2+}+2 \mathrm{e} \quad \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{Ni}$
Multiply (1) by 2 and (2) by 3 and add.
$\begin{array}{lllll}\text { Cell reaction: } & 2 \mathrm{Al}+ & 3 \mathrm{Ni}^{2+} & \rightarrow \quad 2 \mathrm{Al}^{3+}+ & 3 \mathrm{Ni} . \\ \mathrm{Emf}= & 1.66-0.23 & = & 1.43 \mathrm{~V}\end{array}$
subject: Chemistry

question: The half-cells $\mathrm{Br}_{2}, \mathrm{Br}^{-} / \mathrm{Pt}$ and $\mathrm{Cr}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{7}^{2-}, \mathrm{Cr}^{3+}, \mathrm{H}^{+} / \mathrm{Pt}$ have electrode potentials $1.07 \mathrm{~V}$ and $1.33 \mathrm{~V}$ respectively. Give me the cell reaction that occurs when a primary cell is created from the two half - cells.
answer:
The cell must have a positive emf.
$\begin{array}{llll}\text { Oxidation: } 2 \mathrm{Br}^{-} & 2 \mathrm{e} \quad \rightarrow & \mathrm{Br}_{2} \ldots \ldots(1) \\ \text { Reduction: } \mathrm{Cr}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{7}^{2-} & +14 \mathrm{H}^{+} & +6 \mathrm{e} \quad \rightarrow \quad 2 \mathrm{Cr}^{3+} \quad+\quad 7 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O} \ldots\end{array}$
Multiply (1) by 3 and add to (2)
$\begin{array}{llll}6 \mathrm{Br}^{-}+ & \mathrm{Cr}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{7}^{2-}+14 \mathrm{H}^{+} & \rightarrow \quad 3 \mathrm{Br}_{2}+2 \mathrm{Cr}^{3+}+7 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O} \\ \mathrm{Emf}= & 1.33-1.07=0.26 \mathrm{~V}\end{array}$
subject: Chemistry

question: Find the potential energy of a $2.0 \mu C$ charged particle in the field of a second $2.0 \mu C$ charged particle at a distance of $5.0 \mathrm{~m}$
answer:
$7.2 \mathrm{~mJ}$
$$
\begin{aligned}
& U=k_{e} q_{1} q_{2} / r=9.0 \times 10^{9} \mathrm{Nm} \mathrm{m}^{2} / C^{2} \times 2.0 \times 10^{-6} C \times 2.0 \times 10^{-6} C \div(5.0 \mathrm{~m})^{\square}=7.2 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~J} \\
&
\end{aligned}
$$
subject: Physics

question: A $100 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of $0.25 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3} \mathrm{HCl}$ solution was added to $400 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of $0.05 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3} \mathrm{NaOH}$. Calculate the expected $\mathrm{pH}$ of the resultant solution.
answer:
$\mathrm{mmol}$ of $\mathrm{HCl}$ present $\quad=100 * 0.25=25$
$\mathrm{mmol}$ of $\mathrm{NaOH}$ present $=400 * 0.05=20$
Excess acid in $500 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ mixture $=\quad 25-20=\quad 5$
Concentration of excess $\mathrm{HCl}$ in moldm $^{-3}=\quad 0.01$
Hence, $\mathrm{pH} \quad=\quad 2$
subject: Chemistry

$\mathrm{pH}=\mathrm{pK}_{\mathrm{a}}+\log _{10}[$ base $] /[$ acid $]$

answer:
mole of ethanoic acid present $=200 * 0.15=30$.
mole of ethanoate $\quad=\quad 300 * 0.1=\quad 30$.
Since the two are in the same solution $\quad$ [Base $]=$ [Acid]
$\mathrm{pH}$ of buffer $=\quad \mathrm{pK}_{\mathrm{a}}$ ethanoic acid $=4.76$
subject: Chemistry

question: $6.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of graphite burns in excess air to give $8.96 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ of carbon (IV) oxide at S.T.P. Calculate the percentage yield of the preparation.
answer:
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{C}=12.0, \mathrm{O}=16.0, \text { Molar volume of a gas at } \mathrm{STP}=22.4 \mathrm{dm}^{3} \\
& \mathrm{C}+\mathrm{O}_{2} \rightarrow \mathrm{CO}_{2} \\
& 12 \mathrm{~g} \\
& 12 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{C}^{2} \quad 22.4 \mathrm{dm}^{3} \mathrm{CO}_{2} \text { at } \mathrm{STP} \\
& 6 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{C} \equiv 11.2 \mathrm{dm}^{3} \mathrm{CO}_{2} \text { at STP } \\
& \text { Therefore } \% \text { yield }=8.96 / 11.2 * 100=80 \%
\end{aligned}
$$

question: Give any two reaction steps that can be considered to be chain termination steps of the chlorination of methane to chloromethane in the presence of UV light.
answer:
Chlorine radical + chlorine radical to give chlorine molecule
$$
\mathrm{Cl}+\mathrm{Cl} \rightarrow \mathrm{Cl}_{2}
$$
Methyl radical + chlorine radical to give methyl chloride.
$\mathrm{CH}_{3}+\mathrm{Cl} \rightarrow \mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{Cl}$
Methyl radical + methyl radical to give ethane.
$\mathrm{CH}_{3}+\mathrm{CH}_{3} \rightarrow \mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CH}_{3}$.
subject: Chemistry

question: Give any two reaction steps that may be considered as chain propagation steps in the chlorination of methane to chloromethane in the presence of UV light.
answer:
Methane molecule + chlorine radical to give methyl radical and $\mathrm{HCl}$
$$
\mathrm{CH}_{4}+\mathrm{Cl} \rightarrow \mathrm{CH}_{3}+\mathrm{HCl}
$$
Methyl radical + chlorine molecule to give chloromethane and chlorine radical.
$$
\mathrm{CH}_{3}+\mathrm{Cl}_{2} \rightarrow \mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{Cl}+\quad \mathrm{Cl}
$$
subject: Chemistry

question: Calculate the enthalpy change for monochlorination of methane by chlorine gas, given the following bond energies in $\mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}: \quad \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{H} \quad 413 ; \quad \mathrm{Cl}-\mathrm{Cl} \quad 243 ; \quad \mathrm{H}-\mathrm{Cl}$ $432 ; \quad \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{Cl} \quad 346$.
answer:
$: \mathrm{CH}_{4}+\mathrm{Cl}_{2} \rightarrow \mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{Cl}+\quad \mathrm{HCl}$
Bonds broken $=\quad \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{H}+\mathrm{Cl}-\mathrm{Cl}=\quad 413+243=\quad+656 \mathrm{~kJ}$
Bonds formed $=\quad \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{Cl}+\mathrm{H}-\mathrm{Cl}=\quad-346+-432=-778 \mathrm{~kJ}$
$\Delta \mathrm{H}$ of reaction $=-778+656=-122 \mathrm{~kJ}$ or $\quad-1.22 * 10^{2} \mathrm{~kJ}$

question: The enthalpies of combustion for a mole each of ethane, propane and butane are $-1560 \mathrm{~kJ},-2220 \mathrm{~kJ}$ and $-2878 \mathrm{~kJ}$ respectively. Show by calculation which of these gases will be most economical per unit carbon as source of heat?
answer:
$\begin{array}{llllll}\text {} & \text { Ethane (2C) } & \text { Heat per carbon }= & 1560 / 2 & 780 \mathrm{~kJ} \\ & \text { Propane (3C) } & \text { Heat per carbon }= & 2220 / 3 & = & 740 \mathrm{~kJ} \\ & \text { Butane (4C) } & \text { Heat per carbon }= & 2878 / 4 & = & 719.5 \mathrm{~kJ}\end{array}$
Hence ethane is the most economical per carbon.
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain why the sulphur atom has lower first ionization energy than oxygen.
answer: Oxygen and sulphur belong to the same group. The valence electrons of sulphur are in a higher energy level where the pull of the nucleus is lower.

question: The fact that oxygen atom has a lower first ionization energy than nitrogen is against the trend of variation of first ionization energies along the period, why?
answer: First ionization energy generally increases from left to right or as atomic number increases. Nitrogen has atomic number 7 while oxygen has atomic number 8 . The electronic configuration of the valence shell of the neutral atom of nitrogen is stable.
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain why aluminum with atomic number 13 has lower first ionization energy than magnesium with atomic number 12.
answer: $\mathrm{Al}$ has $3 \mathrm{~s}^{2} 3 \mathrm{p}^{1}$ valence shell and $\mathrm{Mg} 3 \mathrm{~s}^{2}$. Removing the $3 \mathrm{p}$ electron is easier than, one from the $3 \mathrm{~s}^{2}$ of magnesium, since the $3 \mathrm{~s}^{2}$ is a fully-filled subshell, which is stable.
subject: Chemistry

question: A buried steel pipe may be protected from corrosion by connecting a magnesium rod through a wire to the steel pipe. Explain how this works.
answer:
Since magnesium is more reactive than iron, it readily undergoes oxidation instead of the iron in the moist soil. (A voltaic cell is set up as follows);
Anode: $\quad \mathrm{Mg} \quad-\quad 2 \mathrm{e} \quad \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{Mg}^{2+}$
Cathode: $\mathrm{O}_{2}+2 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}+4 \mathrm{e} \rightarrow 4 \mathrm{OH}^{-}$
Thus the magnesium gets oxidized instead of the iron.
subject: Chemistry

question: When a molecule of an alkanoic acid is refluxed with an alkanol in the presence of a mineral acid, an ester is formed. What role does the mineral acid play? Explain in detail.
answer:
(1) It protonates the oxygen of the carbonyl group of the acid to help polarize the carbonyl thus facilitating the nucleophilic attack by the alkanol on the carbonyl carbon.

question: Why should good drainage and ploughing lead to increased soil fertility?
answer: Ploughing and drainage increase aeration and hence oxygen content of the soil. This stimulates decomposition and nitrification and inhibits denitrification (loss of nitrogen), thereby increasing soil fertility.

question: Explain why animals are dependent on light energy for their source of energy.

question: Which natural areas or situations might favour denitrification?

question: Why do gases deviate from Boyle's law at high pressures and low temperatures?
answer:
At high pressures when densities of gases are high, the space occupied by the molecules is no longer negligible.
At high pressures and low temperatures, attractive and repulsive forces can be felt by the gaseous molecules.

question: How does the Kinetic Theory of Matter account for Charles' law?
answer: Charles' law states that at constant pressure the volume of a given mass of gas varies with absolute temperature. When temperature is increased, the average molecular speed increases and the average rate of collision increases and pressure increases. To keep the pressure as it was before, it is necessary for the volume to increase so that frequency of collision decreases.
subject: Chemistry

$\quad$ Consider the following bond energies in $\mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}: \quad \mathrm{C} \equiv \mathrm{C} \quad 835 ; \quad \mathrm{C}=\mathrm{C} \quad 602$;
$$
\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{C} \quad 346 ; \quad \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{H} \quad 411 ; \quad \mathrm{H}-\mathrm{H} \quad 432 ; \quad \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{O} \quad 358 ; \quad \mathrm{O}-\mathrm{H} \quad 459
$$
question: Calculate the enthalpy change for the hydrogenation of ethyne to ethene.
answer:
$\quad \mathrm{HC} \equiv \mathrm{CH} \quad+\quad \mathrm{H}_{2} \quad \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{CH}_{2}=\mathrm{CH}_{2}$
Bonds broken $=\quad \mathrm{C} \equiv \mathrm{C}+\mathrm{H}-\mathrm{H} \quad=\quad 835+432=1267$
Bond formed $=\mathrm{C}=\mathrm{C}+2 \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{H} \quad=\quad-602+(-2 * 411)$
$=-1424$
Enthalpy change $\quad=\quad-1424+1267=\quad-157$ or $-1.57^{*} 10^{2} \mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}$
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text:
$\quad$ Consider the following bond energies in $\mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}: \quad \mathrm{C} \equiv \mathrm{C} \quad 835 ; \quad \mathrm{C}=\mathrm{C} \quad 602$;
$$
\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{C} \quad 346 ; \quad \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{H} \quad 411 ; \quad \mathrm{H}-\mathrm{H} \quad 432 ; \quad \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{O} \quad 358 ; \quad \mathrm{O}-\mathrm{H} \quad 459
$$
question: Calculate the enthalpy change for the hydrogenation of ethene to ethane.
answer:
$\quad \mathrm{CH}_{2}=\mathrm{CH}_{2}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \quad \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{CH}_{3}-\mathrm{CH}_{3}$
Bonds broken $=\mathrm{C}=\mathrm{C}+\mathrm{H}-\mathrm{H} \quad=\quad 602+432=1034$
Bonds formed $=\quad \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{C}+2 * \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{H} \quad=\quad-346-2 * 411=-1168$
Enthalpy change $=1034-1168=-134$ or $-1.34 * 10^{2} \mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}$
subject: Chemistry

question: Calculate the enthalpy change for the dehydration of ethanol to ethane.
answer:
$\quad \mathrm{CH}_{3}-\mathrm{CH}_{2}-\mathrm{OH} \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{CH}_{2}=\mathrm{CH}_{2}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$
$\begin{array}{llll}\text { Bonds broken: } & & \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{H}+\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{O}+\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{C}= & 411+358+346 \\ & & = & 1115 \\ \text { Bonds formed: } & \mathrm{C}=\mathrm{C}+\mathrm{H}-\mathrm{O} & = & -602-459 \\ & & = & -1061 \\ \text { Enthalpy change } & = & -1061+\quad 115 & =54 \mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}\end{array}$
subject: Chemistry

Consider the equilibrium reaction.

preamble_text:
Compounds $\mathrm{A}, \mathrm{B}$ and $\mathrm{C}$ react to give $\mathrm{D}$ and $\mathrm{E}$ according to the balanced equation as follows; $\mathrm{A}+2 \mathrm{~B}+\mathrm{C} \rightarrow \mathrm{D}+\mathrm{E}$.
In order to determine the order with respect to $\mathrm{A}, \mathrm{B}$ and $\mathrm{C}$, the following experiments were performed: (concentrations are in moldm $^{-3}$ ).
|            |A        |B           |C           |Initial Rate($moldm^-3$)|
|------------|---------|------------|------------|------------------------|
|Experiment 1|0.05     |0.05        |0.05        |$8.0 * 10^{-5}$         |
|Experiment 2|0.05     |0.10        |0.05        |$1.6 * 10^{-4}$         |
|Experiment 3|0.10     |0.05        |0.05        |$3.2 * 10^{-4}$         |
|Experiment 4|0.05     |0.05        |0.10        |$4.0 * 10^{-5}$         |
question: Determine the order of the reaction with respect to $A$.
answer:
Rate $=\quad \mathrm{k}[\mathrm{A}]^{\mathrm{a}}[\mathrm{B}]^{\mathrm{b}}[\mathrm{C}]^{\mathrm{c}}$
Comparing Experiments 1 and 3: when the concentrations of $\mathrm{B}$ and $\mathrm{C}$ remain constant
and that of $\mathrm{A}$ is doubled, the rate increases by a factor of 4 hence $\quad \mathrm{a}=2$.
Order of reaction with respect to $\mathrm{A}=2$.
subject: Chemistry

question: Determine the order of the reaction with respect to $\mathrm{C}$.
answer:
Comparing Experiments 1 and 4. When concentrations of $\mathrm{A}$ and $\mathrm{B}$ remain constant and that of $\mathrm{C}$ is doubled, the rate is halved i.e. $2^{\mathrm{c}}=1 / 2$, hence $\mathrm{c}=-1$.
Order of reaction with respect to $\mathrm{C}=-1$.

preamble_text: A $100 \Omega$ resistor is completely immersed in $0.5 \mathrm{~kg}$ of a thermally insulated liquid with specific heat capacity $800 \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~kg}^{-1} \mathrm{~K}^{-1}$. Find the current required for the given rate of change of temperature of the liquid.

$$

question: Explain why the first ionization energy of helium is much higher than that of hydrogen.

question: Two half-cells, $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}, \mathrm{OH}^{-} / \mathrm{H}_{2} / \mathrm{Pt}$ and $\mathrm{Cr}^{3+} / \mathrm{Cr}$ with electrode potentials -0.83 and $-0.74 \mathrm{~V}$ respectively, are used in constructing a voltaic cell. Give a balanced equation for the cell reaction.
answer:
Oxidation: $\mathrm{H}_{2} \quad+\quad 2 \mathrm{OH}^{-} \quad-\quad 2 \mathrm{e} \rightarrow 2 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O} \ldots(1) \quad+0.83$
$$
\text { Reduction: } \mathrm{Cr}^{3+}+3 \mathrm{e} \quad \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{Cr} \quad \ldots \ldots \ldots(2) \quad-0.74
$$
Multiply (1) by 3 and (2) by 2 and add
$$
\begin{array}{lllllll} 
& 3 \mathrm{H}_{2} & + & 6 \mathrm{OH}^{-} & - & 6 \mathrm{e} & \rightarrow \quad 6 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O} \\
& 2 \mathrm{Cr}^{3+} & + & 6 \mathrm{e} & \rightarrow & 2 \mathrm{Cr} \\
\text { Overall } & 3 \mathrm{H}_{2} & + & 6 \mathrm{OH}^{-} & + & 2 \mathrm{Cr}^{3+} & \rightarrow \\
& & & &
\end{array}
$$
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text: A gun with a muzzle velocity of $300 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}$ fires a $0.1 \mathrm{~kg}$ pellet horizontally $20 \mathrm{~m}$ above ground. Acceleration due to gravity is approximately $10 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}^{2}$.
question: Find the horizontal range of the pellet.
answer:
$600 m$
Fall time $t=\sqrt{2 h / g}=\sqrt{2 \times 20 m \div 10 m / \mathrm{s}^{2}}=2 \mathrm{~s}$ so horizontal distance $x=v t=300 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s} \times 2 \mathrm{~s}=600 \mathrm{~m}$

preamble_text: A gun with a muzzle velocity of $300 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}$ fires a $0.1 \mathrm{~kg}$ pellet horizontally $20 \mathrm{~m}$ above ground. Acceleration due to gravity is approximately $10 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}^{2}$.
question: The same gun fires a pellet that attains a height of $20 \mathrm{~m}$ above the barrel of the gun. Find the sine of the angle of the barrel relative to the horizontal when the pellet is fired.
answer:
$1 / 15=0.07$
Initial vertical component of velocity $u_{v}=\sqrt{2 g h}=20 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}=u \sin \theta$ so
$$
\sin \theta=u_{v} / u=20 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s} \div 300 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}=1 / 15=0.0 \dot{6} .
$$

question: A pesticide sold in a shop is labelled as $0.15 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$ solution. $100 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of the pesticide has to be diluted to $1000 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ before use. If the formula mass is $82 \mathrm{~g}$, what is the concentration of the solution in ppm before it is applied.
answer:
Original concentration in $\mathrm{gdm}^{-3}=\quad 12.3 \mathrm{gdm}^{-3}$
Dilution $\quad 100 \rightarrow 1000$.i.e. 1 in 10
Final concentration $=1.23 \mathrm{gdm}^{-3}=1230 \mathrm{mgdm}^{-3}$
Concentration in ppm $=1230$
subject: Chemistry

question: A bottle of pesticide sold in a shop is labelled as a 0.2 moldm $^{-3}$ solution of the active compound. The molar mass is $45 \mathrm{~g}$ and the solution has to be applied at a concentration of $60 \mathrm{ppm}$. If the volume of the pesticide is $100 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$, calculate the total volume of the diluted solution that can be prepared from one bottle.
answer:
Concentration of pesticide in $\mathrm{gdm}^{-3}=0.2 * 45 \quad=\quad 9.0 \mathrm{gdm}^{-3}$
$\begin{array}{llllc}\text { Final concentration } & = & 60 \mathrm{ppm}= & 0.06 \mathrm{gdm}^{-3} \\ \text { Therefore dilution factor } & = & 9 / 0.06 & = & 150 \\ 100 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} \text { will give } 150 * 100 & = & 15000 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} & \text { or } & 15 \mathrm{dm}^{3}\end{array}$
subject: Chemistry

question: $25.0 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of a stock solution of $\mathrm{HCl}$ were diluted to $250 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ and the diluted solution was titrated against a standardized $\mathrm{NaOH}$ solution. If $25.0 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of $0.10 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3} \mathrm{NaOH}$ solution were neutralized by $15.0 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of the diluted $\mathrm{HCl}$ solution, calculate the concentration of the original $\mathrm{HCl}$ solution in moldm ${ }^{-3}$.
answer:
$\quad \mathrm{HCl}+\mathrm{NaOH} \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{NaCl}+\quad \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$
$15 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}, \mathrm{M} \quad 25,0.1$
$\mathrm{M}^{*} 15 / 25 * 0.1=1 / 1$
$\mathrm{M}=25 * 0.1 / 15=5 / 3=0.167$
Dilution was 1 in 10 , hence concentration of the original $\mathrm{HCl}$ solution $=1.67$ moldm $^{-3}$
subject: Chemistry

question: The electron affinity of beryllium is positive, i.e. $+16 \mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}$ whilst that of the next element boron is $15 \mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}$, what is the significance of the positive and negative values?
answer: Beryllium has a fully filled valence shell of $2 \mathrm{~s}^{2}$ which is stable. Adding an electron will make the valence configuration less stable, hence energy has to be supplied. In the case of boron adding an electron will not destabilize the valence configuration and heat is given out.
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain why generally adding an electron to a neutral atom of an element in the second period gives out more heat than an element in the same group but in the third period.
answer: All things being equal, electron affinity decreases with increase in atomic radius. This is because the effective nuclear charge decreases. An atom of an element in the $3^{\text {rd }}$ Period has a larger radius.
subject: Chemistry

question: Neon, an element that comes after fluorine in the second period, has a positive electron affinity while fluorine has a large and negative electron affinity. Why?
answer: Neon has a fully filled valence shell and therefore adding an electron will require some energy input. Fluorine needs one electron to complete its octet, which is stable and adding an electron will be highly favourable. Heat will be given off.
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text: When ethyne gas is heated in a copper tube and under pressure, three moles combine to give a mole of benzene.
question: What is the percentage yield if $39 \mathrm{~g}$ of ethyne could only produce $31.2 \mathrm{~g}$ of benzene?
answer:
$\begin{array}{lll}\mathrm{C}=\quad & 12.0, \mathrm{H}= & 1.0
\\& 3 \mathrm{CH} \equiv \mathrm{CH} \quad \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{6} \\ & 3 * 26 & 78 \\ & 39 \mathrm{~g} \text { of ethyne } \equiv \quad 39 \mathrm{~g} \text { of benzene } \\ & \text { Therefore, } \% \text { yield } \quad=\quad 31.2 / 39 * 100 \quad=\quad 80 \%\end{array}$
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text: When ethyne gas is heated in a copper tube and under pressure, three moles combine to give a mole of benzene.
question: What is the percentage yield if $67.2 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ of ethyne at STP gave $70.2 \mathrm{~g}$ of benzene. Molar volume of a gas is $22.4 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ at STP.
answer:
$\quad 67.2 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ of ethyne $=\quad 3 * 22.4 \mathrm{dm}^{3}=3$ moles of ethyne.
$$
\begin{array}{lllll}
3 \text { moles of ethyne } & & 1 \text { mole of benzene } & \equiv & 78.0 \mathrm{~g} \\
\text { Therefore, percentage yield } & = & 70.2 / 78 * 100 & = & 90 \%
\end{array}
$$
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text: When ethyne gas is heated in a copper tube and under pressure, three moles combine to give a mole of benzene.
question: An apparatus used in converting ethyne into benzene operates at $80 \%$ yield. If $124.8 \mathrm{~g}$ of benzene was harvested in one such preparation, what mass of ethyne was used? $\quad \mathrm{C}=12.0, \mathrm{H}=1.0$
answer:
$\quad 3 \mathrm{C}_{2} \mathrm{H}_{2} \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{6}$
$$
3 * 26
$$
Since apparatus operates at $80 \%$ yield.
At $80 \%$ yield mass of benzene $=124.8$
Therefore, at 100\% mass of benzene $=124.8 * 100 / 80=156 \mathrm{~g}$
subject: Chemistry

answer:
Solubility at $30^{\circ} \mathrm{C}=0.10 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}=8.6 \mathrm{gdm}^{-3}$
For $250 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ solubility at $30^{\circ} \mathrm{C}=250 / 1000 * 8.6 \quad=\quad 2.15 \mathrm{~g}$
Therefore, mass of $B$ that will be deposited $\quad=\quad 5-2.15$
$$
=2.85 \mathrm{~g} .
$$

question: State one difference each between a grazing food chain and a detritus food chain
answer:
1. Grazing food chain starts from the living green plants i.e. producers occupying the first trophic level, but Detritus starts from the dead organic matter and decomposers called detritivores as the first trophic level.
2. A much less fraction of energy flows through grazing food chain whereas a much larger fraction of energy flows through this detritus food chain.
3. Grazing food chain binds inorganic nutrients but detritivore food chain releases the inorganic nutrients bound in organic matter.
4. Grazing food chain is directly dependent on the inflow of solar radiation. Whereas in detritivore Energy for the food chain comes from the organic wastes, exudates and dead matter termed as detritus.
subject: Biology

question: $10 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of a $0.35 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3} \mathrm{HCl}$ solution is diluted to $250 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ and $50 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of this further diluted to 100 $\mathrm{cm}^{3}$. What is the concentration of the final solution?
answer:
$\quad 1^{\text {st }}$ Dilution; $\quad 10 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} \rightarrow \quad 250 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}, \quad 1$ in 25
$2^{\text {nd }}$ Dilution $\quad 50 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} \rightarrow \quad 100 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}, \quad 1$ in 2
Therefore, total dilution $=\quad 1$ in 50
New concentration $=0.35 / 50=\quad 0.007$ moldm $^{-3}$.
subject: Chemistry

question: $20 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of a solution containing $40 \mathrm{~g}$ per $\mathrm{dm}^{3}$ of a pesticide were diluted to $80 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ and sold in bottles to customers. Customers are expected to dilute each $5 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ to $100 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ before use. Find the final concentration in ppm of the pesticide solution used by the customer.
answer:
$\quad 1^{\text {st }}$ Dilution; $\quad 20 \quad \rightarrow \quad 80 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} ; \quad 1$ in 4
$2^{\text {nd }}$ Dilution; $\quad 5 \quad \rightarrow \quad 100 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} ; \quad 1$ in 20
Total dilution 1 in 80
SFinal concentration $=40 / 80=0.5 \mathrm{gdm}^{-3}=500 \mathrm{ppm}$.
subject: Chemistry

question: $50 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of a stock solution of $\mathrm{KOH}$ were diluted to $1 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ and then $100 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of this further diluted to $250 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$. If by volumetric analysis using a standardized acid, the concentration of the base was found to be 0.012 moldm $^{-3}$, calculate the concentration in moldm $^{-3}$ of the stock solution.
answer:
$\quad 1^{\text {st }}$ Dilution; $\quad 50 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} \quad \rightarrow \quad 1000 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}, \quad 1$ in 20
$2^{\text {nd }}$ Dilution $\quad 100 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} \rightarrow \quad 250 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}, \quad 1$ in 2.5
Total dilution $\quad=\quad 1$ in 50
Initial concentration $=0.012 * 50=0.60 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$.
subject: Chemistry

question: Give one economic importance each of lichens.
answer:
a) Pioneers of vegetation: They secrete acids and disintegrate rocks into soil particles, where moss and higher plants are established.
b) Food: some species of lichen are also used as food.
c) Medicines: some species of lichens are used in treatment of some disease.
d) Perfumes: Several species of lichens are used in preparation of cosmetic perfumes.
e) Bio-indicators of air pollution: Lichens grow in pollution free places. As the level of pollution increase, their number decrease.
f) Dyes: Lichens are used to manufacture high quality dyes of various colors.
g) Litmus is also obtained from lichens.
h) Forest fire: Dry thalli of lichens in forests form the thick mat on tree branches and easily catch fire. So there is high risk of forest fire due to lichens.
i) Damage to buildings: Lichens can grow on the walls of buildings. As they secrete acids, they can damage the plasters and shining beauty of buildings.
j) Shading of leaf: lichens can grow on plant leaves and block the sunlight, so that photosynthesis of plants is badly affected.
subject: Biology

preamble_text: A galvanometer with internal resistance $10 \Omega$ gives full-scale deflection at $50 \mu A$. Find the multiplier required to convert the galvanometer into a voltmeter with the given full scale deflection.

$4 k \Omega$
$$
R=\left(V-V_{\text {full scale }}\right) / I_{\text {full scale }}=\frac{V-10 \Omega \times 50 \times 10^{-6} A}{50 \times 10^{-6} A}=3990 \Omega \cong 4 k \Omega
$$

question: Give one of the changes that are observed in a flower after fertilization.
answer:
a) There is formation of a diploid zygote that develops into an embryo, which forms the future plant.
b) The endosperm cells serve as a source of nutrition for the developing embryo.
c) The ovule becomes the seed.
d) The ovary becomes the fruit.
e) In most of the plants the antipodals and synnergids disintegrate before, during or immediately after fertilization.
f) The outer and inner integuments of the ovule become the testa or the seed coat of the seed.
g) Petals and sepals fall off.
subject: Biology

Dilution: $50 \quad \rightarrow \quad 100 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} \quad$ i.e. 1 in 2
New concentration is $0.10 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$
$$
\mathrm{pH}=-\log _{10}[\mathrm{HCl}]=1.0
$$

question: $50 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of $0.50 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$ solution are diluted to $250 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$. Calculate the change in $\mathrm{pH}$, given that $\log (0.50)=-0.301$
answer:
Dilution: $50 \rightarrow 250 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} \quad$ i.e. 1 in 5
New concentration $=0.10$ moldm $^{-3}$
New $\mathrm{pH} \quad=\quad 1$ Old $\mathrm{pH} \quad=\quad-\log (0.5)=0.3$
Therefore, change in $\mathrm{pH}=0.70$

question: $40 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of $0.30 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3} \mathrm{KOH}$ are diluted to $120 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$. What is the $\mathrm{pH}$ of the new solution?

answer:
Electrolysis of dilute $\mathrm{NaCl}$ with Pt electrodes $\equiv$ electrolysis of $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$.
$\begin{array}{rlrl}4 \mathrm{~F} & =1 \mathrm{~mole} \mathrm{O}_{2} & \\ & =22.4 \mathrm{dm}^{3} \text { at STP } & \\ 1 \mathrm{~F} & =1 / 4 * 22.4 \mathrm{dm}^{3}=5.6 \mathrm{dm}^{3} \\ \text { Efficiency } & =4.48 / 5.6 * 100=80 \% .\end{array}$

question:
Which substance when added to water can remove both temporary hardness and permanent hardness?
Explain your answer.

$\quad \mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3}$
Temporary: $\quad \mathrm{Ca}\left(\mathrm{HCO}_{3}\right)_{2}+\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3} \quad \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{CaCO}_{3}+2 \mathrm{NaHCO}_{3}$
Permanent: $\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}+\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3} \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{CaCO}_{3}+2 \mathrm{Na}^{+}$

question: If the volume, pressure and temperature of a certain amount of an ideal gas are recorded in $\mathrm{dm}^{3}, \mathrm{kPa}$, and degree Kelvin respectively, what should be the units of the gas constant R, for the Ideal Gas Law to hold?
answer:
$\quad \mathrm{V}=\mathrm{dm}^{3}, \quad \mathrm{P}=\mathrm{kPa}, \quad \mathrm{T}=\mathrm{K} ;$ for ideal gas, $\mathrm{PV}=\mathrm{nRT}$
Therefore, $\quad \mathrm{R}=\mathrm{PV} / \mathrm{nT}=\quad \mathrm{kPa} * \mathrm{dm}^{3} / \mathrm{mol}^{*} \mathrm{~K}$
Hence units of $\mathrm{R} \quad=\mathrm{kPadm}^{3} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1} \mathrm{~K}^{-1} \quad \mathrm{OR} \quad \mathrm{JK}^{-1} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$
subject: Chemistry

question: What is the difference between incomplete dominance and co-dominance?
answer:
Incomplete dominance is the phenomenon in which neither of the alleles of gene completely dominates the other and the phenotype of the hybrid is intermediate between the phenotypes of the parents.

question: Explain why grasses are usually at a better advantage than dicotyledons with respect to restoration after grazing by herbivores.
answer: Grasses have meristems at the nodes of their stems and often may form new shoots from buds at or below ground level. question: What type of organic reaction will methyl chloride undergo most readily and why?
answer:
Nucleophilic substitution reactions.
Reason: 
(1) chlorine being an electron withdrawing group would render the carbon it is bonded to an electron deficient centre which can attract a nucleophile.
(2) Elimination is not possible since there is only one carbon so it has to be a substitution reaction.
subject: Chemistry

question: What type of organic reaction would benzene undergo most readily and why?
answer:
(1) Electrophilic substitution reactions
3 Reason: The pi-electron cloud below and above the plane of carbons in benzene will attract electrophiles.
(2) Substitution rather than addition reactions
Reason: So that the stable structure resulting from the resonance / delocalization is maintained.
subject: Chemistry

question: Name the type of reagent methyl amine is and the type of reactions it will undergo.

question: Why do you think the rate of a reaction at a particular time, i.e. instantaneous rate, will be different from the average rate of the reaction?
answer: Instantaneous rate of a reaction is the rate at a particular time $t$, that is a small change in concentration divided by the corresponding change in time. This rate changes as reaction proceeds. Average rate however is overall change divided by the total time the reaction takes place or occurs.
subject: Chemistry

answer:
For calcium
$\mathrm{Ca}\left(\mathrm{HCO}_{3}\right)_{2}+\mathrm{Ca}(\mathrm{OH})_{2} \quad \rightarrow \quad 2 \mathrm{CaCO}_{3(\mathrm{~s})} \quad+\quad 2 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$
For magnesium
$\operatorname{Mg}\left(\mathrm{HCO}_{3}\right)_{2} \quad+2 \mathrm{Ca}(\mathrm{OH})_{2} \quad \rightarrow \quad 2 \mathrm{CaCO}_{3(\mathrm{~s})}+\mathrm{Mg}(\mathrm{OH})_{2}+2 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$
(Note, in the case of magnesium, $\mathrm{Mg}(\mathrm{OH})_{2}$ precipitates because $\mathrm{Mg}(\mathrm{OH})_{2}$ is less soluble than $\left.\mathrm{MgCO}_{3}\right)$
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain how or why soaps can clean fats and vegetable oil stains.
answer: Soaps contain sodium or potassium salts of stearate or palmitate ions. The ions contain long hydrocarbon chains in which the fats are soluble while the charged ends are hydrophilic. The fat/oil is emulsified.
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain why calcium or magnesium ions are not the only metal ions that make water hard.
answer: Any multivalent metal ion whose stearate or palmitate is insoluble in water will make the water hard. For example $\mathrm{Fe}^{2+}$ and $\mathrm{Fe}^{3+}$
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain why kettles in the United Kingdom tend to have white scales in them after they have been used for a while.
answer: The water contains $\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ and $\mathrm{Mg}^{2+}$ ions and $\mathrm{HCO}_{3}{ }^{-}$ions. Heating or boiling of the water causes the decomposition of the $\mathrm{HCO}_{3}{ }^{-}$ions to $\mathrm{CO}_{3}{ }^{2-}, \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$ and $\mathrm{CO}_{2}$. The $\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$ combines with the $\mathrm{CO}_{3}{ }^{2-}$ to give insoluble $\mathrm{CaCO}_{3}--$ the scales.
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain why tertiary amines cannot form amides with carboxylic acid.
answer: Formation of amide results in the elimination of a water molecule from the amine and acid. Tertiary amines have no hydrogen bonded to the Nitrogen to combine with the $-\mathrm{OH}$ on the acid to form the $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$ molecule.
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain why tertiary alkanols cannot be oxidised unless by harsh oxidation that involves breakage of the $\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{C}$
answer: Oxidation of alkanols involves elimination of 2 hydrogen, one from the carbon to which the $-\mathrm{OH}$ is bonded and the $\mathrm{H}$ on the $\mathrm{OH}$. A tertiary alkanol does not have such $\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{H}$.
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain why alkanones do not react with Fehling's reagent.
answer:
Fehling's reagent is a mild oxidising agent. Alkanones cannot be oxidised except in the harsh oxidation involving breaking of $\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{C}$ bond, eg combustion.
Oxidation by Fehling's reagent requires that a hydrogen atom be removed from the carbon of the carbonyl group.
subject: Chemistry

Consider the following equilibrium process in the gaseous phase.
$2 A+B \leftrightarrow 3 C+5 D$
Initially 8 moles of $A$ and 5 moles of B were placed in a $10 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ flask at $300 \mathrm{~K}$ and the mixture allowed to come to equilibrium.
question: If at equilibrium, it was found that 0.45 moles of $C$ were formed, how many moles of $D$ would have been formed?
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text:
Consider the following equilibrium process in the gaseous phase.
$2 A+B \leftrightarrow 3 C+5 D$
Initially 8 moles of $A$ and 5 moles of B were placed in a $10 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ flask at $300 \mathrm{~K}$ and the mixture allowed to come to equilibrium.
question: If under a different equilibrium condition 6.8 moles of $A$ were present, how many moles of $C$ would have been formed?
answer:
moles of $A$ that would have reacted $=8.0-6.8$
$=1.2$
But $\quad \frac{A}{C}=\frac{2}{3}$
$$
\frac{1.2}{C}=\frac{2}{3}
$$
Moles of $\mathrm{C}=1.8$ mols
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text:
Consider the following equilibrium process in the gaseous phase.
$2 A+B \leftrightarrow 3 C+5 D$
Initially 8 moles of $A$ and 5 moles of B were placed in a $10 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ flask at $300 \mathrm{~K}$ and the mixture allowed to come to equilibrium.
question: If under yet another different condition of equilibrium, 4 moles of $B$ are left, how many moles of $A$ and $D$ were present?
answer:
Moles of $B$ that had reacted $=1 \mathrm{~mol}$
$$
\text { Moles of } A \text { that were present }=8-2 \mathrm{~mol}=6 \mathrm{mols}
$$
Moles of $D$ that would have been formed $=5 \mathrm{~mol}$
subject: Chemistry

question: The carbonyl group attracts nucleophiles to its carbon because it has a partially formed positive charge. Explain why this attraction is less in alkanones than alkanasl.

question: What average force can bring a $20 \mathrm{~kg}$ object moving at $5.0 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}$ to rest in $4.0 \mathrm{~s}$ ?
answer:
$25 N$
$$
F=\text { change } in \text { linear momentum } \div \text { time }=(20 \mathrm{~kg} \times 5.0 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}-0) \div 4.0 \mathrm{~s}=25 \mathrm{~N}
$$
subject: Physics

question: How long will it take a $50 \mathrm{~kg}$ object moving at $2.0 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}$ to come to rest if a steady $20 \mathrm{~N}$ decelerating force acts on it?
answer:
$5 s$
$$
t=\text { change } in \text { linear momentum } \div \text { force }=(50 \mathrm{~kg} \times 2.0 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}-0) \div 20 \mathrm{~N}=5.0 \mathrm{~s}
$$
subject: Physics

question: What average force can bring a $50 \mathrm{kgobject}$ moving at $2.0 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}$ to rest in $1.0 \mathrm{~s}$ ?
answer:
$100 \mathrm{~N}$
$$
F=\text { change } in \text { linear momentum } \div \text { time }=(50 \mathrm{~kg} \times 2.0 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}-0) \div 1.0 \mathrm{~s}=100 \mathrm{~N}
$$
subject: Physics

Solubility of $\mathrm{A}$ in $400 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ at $30^{\circ} \mathrm{C}=\quad(400 / 1000)^{*} 16=6.4$

question: State an outline of a scheme you would use to make 1-propene from propane.
answer:
Either
$\mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CH}_{2} \mathrm{CH}_{3}+\mathrm{Cl}_{2}+$ hv/light $\rightarrow \mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CHClCH}_{3}$
$+\mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CH}_{2} \mathrm{CH}_{2} \mathrm{Cl}+$ other compounds
After separation
$\mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CH}_{2} \mathrm{CH}_{2} \mathrm{Cl}+$ ethanolic acid $\mathrm{KOH} / \mathrm{NaOH} /$ heat $\rightarrow \mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CH}=\mathrm{CH}_{2}$
or
$\mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CHClCH}_{3}+$ ethanolic acid $\mathrm{KOH} / \mathrm{NaOH} /$ heat $\rightarrow \mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CH}=\mathrm{CH}_{2}$
OR
$\mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CH}_{2} \mathrm{CH}_{3}+\mathrm{Cl}_{2}+$ hv/light $\rightarrow \mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CHClCH}_{2} \mathrm{Cl}+$ other
compounds
After separation
$\mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CHClCH}_{2} \mathrm{Cl}+\mathrm{Zn} /$ Ether $\rightarrow \mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CH}=\mathrm{CH}_{2}$
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain why the first ionization energy of beryllium is higher than that of boron although beryllium has the lower atomic number.
answer: Be has a valence shell of $2 s^{2}$ while boron has a valence shell of $2 s^{2} 2 p^{1}$. The fully filled $2 s^{2}$ subshell is stable and would not lose an electron readily. The $2 \mathrm{p}^{1}$ electron of the boron may be lost more easily so that boron assumes the more stable configuration of $2 \mathrm{~s}^{2}$.
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain the significance of the positive value the electron affinity of magnesium which is $+67 \mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}$.
answer:
Electron affinity is the energy change for the process $\mathrm{Mg}_{(\mathrm{g})}+\mathrm{e} \rightarrow$
$M g_{(g)}^{-}$. The process is unfavourable as the in-coming electron will make the fairly stable valence configuration of $3 s^{2}$ less stable.
subject: Chemistry

question: Explain why the first electron affinity of oxygen, $\mathrm{O} \rightarrow \mathrm{O}^{-}$is -141 but that for $\mathrm{O}^{-} \rightarrow \mathrm{O}^{2-}$ is $+798$.
answer: Adding an electron to the neutral atom whose valence configuration is $2 s^{2} 2 p^{4}$ makes it more stable. However the second electron faces the strong repulsive field of the first electron which repels it. A lot of energy is needed to overcome this repulsive force.
subject: Chemistry

question: Use the bond energy to calculate the enthalpy change for addition of bromine to 1-butene.
answer:
$\mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CH}_{2} \mathrm{CH}=\mathrm{CH}_{2}+\mathrm{Br}_{2} \rightarrow \mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CH}_{2} \mathrm{CHBrCH}_{2} \mathrm{Br}$
Energy change for bonds broken $\mathrm{C}=\mathrm{C} 838+\mathrm{Br}-\mathrm{Br} 193=1031$
Energy change for bonds formed $=2 \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{Br}+\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{C}$
$=2 * 180+347=-707$
Enthalpy of reaction $=\quad 1031-707=+324 \mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}$.
subject: Chemistry

question: Use the bond energies to calculate enthalpy of hydrogenation of 1-propene
answer:
$\mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CH}=\mathrm{CH}_{2}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \rightarrow \mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CH}_{2} \mathrm{CH}_{3}$
Bonds broken $=\mathrm{C}=\mathrm{C}+\mathrm{H}-\mathrm{H}=838 \quad+436=1274$
Bonds formed $=\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{C}+2 \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{H}=347+2 * 432=1221$
Enthalpy of reaction $=+53 \mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}$
subject: Chemistry

question: Use the bond energies to calculate enthalpy change for addition of chlorine to 2-pentene.
answer:
$\quad \mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CH}_{2} \mathrm{CH}=\mathrm{CHCH}_{3}+\mathrm{Cl}_{2} \rightarrow \mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CH}_{2} \mathrm{CHClCHClCH}_{3}$
Bonds broken $=\mathrm{C}=\mathrm{C}+\mathrm{Cl}_{2}=838+234$
$=1072$
Bonds formed $=\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{C}+2 \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{Cl}=347+2 * 346=1039$
Enthalpy of reaction $=1072-1039=+33 \mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}$
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text: A $5 \Omega$ resistor of negligible heat capacity is inserted into a thermally insulating vessel containing $1 \mathrm{~kg}$ of water at $25^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ and $10 \mathrm{~V}$ is applied to it. The specific heat capacity of water is $4200 \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~kg}^{-1} \mathrm{~K}^{-1}$.
question: What is the temperature of the water after $21 \mathrm{~s}$ ?
answer:
$25.1^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$
$\Delta T=Q / C=P t / m c=V^{2} t / R m C=(10 \mathrm{~V})^{2} \times 21 \mathrm{~s} \div\left(5 \Omega \times 1 \mathrm{~kg} \times 4200 \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~kg}^{-1} \mathrm{~K}^{-1}\right)=0.1 \mathrm{~K}$ so $T=25^{\circ} \mathrm{C}+0.1^{\circ} \mathrm{C}=25.1^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$
subject: Physics

preamble_text: A $5 \Omega$ resistor of negligible heat capacity is inserted into a thermally insulating vessel containing $1 \mathrm{~kg}$ of water at $25^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ and $10 \mathrm{~V}$ is applied to it. The specific heat capacity of water is $4200 \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~kg}^{-1} \mathrm{~K}^{-1}$.
question: How long will it take to increase the temperature of the water by $2 K$ ?
answer:
$420 \mathrm{~s}$
$$
t=R m c \Delta T / V^{2}=\left(5 \Omega \times 1 \mathrm{~kg} \times 4200 \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~kg}^{-1} \mathrm{~K}^{-1} \times 2 K\right) \div(10 \mathrm{~V})^{2}=420 \mathrm{~s}
$$
subject: Physics

preamble_text: A $5 \Omega$ resistor of negligible heat capacity is inserted into a thermally insulating vessel containing $1 \mathrm{~kg}$ of water at $25^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ and $10 \mathrm{~V}$ is applied to it. The specific heat capacity of water is $4200 \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~kg}^{-1} \mathrm{~K}^{-1}$.
question: How much water can be heated to $30^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ in $42 \mathrm{~s}$ ?
answer:
$0.04 \mathrm{~kg}$
$$
m=V^{2} t / R c \Delta T=(10 V)^{2} \times 42 \mathrm{~s} \div\left(5 \Omega \times 4200 \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~kg}^{-1} \mathrm{~K}^{-1} \times 5 K\right)=0.04 \mathrm{~kg}
$$
subject: Physics

preamble_text: You may take the Coulomb law constant as $9 \times 10^{9} \mathrm{~V} \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{C}$.
question: A $20 \mu C$ charge is placed at the origin and a $-50 \mu C$ charge is placed at $x=2 \mathrm{~m}$ on the $x$ axis. What is the electric field strength at $x=1 \mathrm{~m}$ on the $x$ axis?
answer:
$6.3 \times 10^{5} \mathrm{~V} / \mathrm{m}$ in $+x$ direction
$$
E=\sum \frac{q_{i}\left(r-r_{i}\right)}{4 \pi \epsilon_{0}\left|r-r_{i}\right|^{3}}=9 \times 10^{9} \mathrm{Vm} / C \times\left[\frac{20 \mu C \times \hat{i}}{(1 m)^{2}}+\frac{-50 \mu C \times(-\hat{i})}{(1 m)^{2}}\right]=6.3 \times 10^{5} \hat{i} \mathrm{~V} / \mathrm{m}
$$
Accept $N / C$ in place of $V / m$.
subject: Physics

preamble_text: You may take the Coulomb law constant as $9 \times 10^{9} \mathrm{~V} \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{C}$.
question: A $20 \mu C$ charge is placed at the origin and a $50 \mu C$ charge is placed at $x=2 m$ on the $x$ axis. What is the electric field strength at $x=1 m$ on the $x$ axis?
answer:
$2.7 \times 10^{5} \mathrm{~V} / \mathrm{m}$ in $-x$ direction
$$
E=\sum \frac{q_{i}\left(r-r_{i}\right)}{4 \pi \epsilon_{0}\left|r-r_{i}\right|^{3}}=9 \times 10^{9} \mathrm{Vm} / C \times\left[\frac{20 \mu C \times \hat{i}}{(1 \mathrm{~m})^{2}}+\frac{50 \mu C \times(-\hat{i})}{(1 \mathrm{~m})^{2}}\right]=-2.7 \times 10^{5} \hat{i} \mathrm{~V} / \mathrm{m}
$$
subject: Physics

preamble_text: You may take the Coulomb law constant as $9 \times 10^{9} \mathrm{~V} \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{C}$.
question: Two $20 \mu C$ charges are placed $2 m$ apart on the $x$ axis. What is the electric field strength midway between them?
answer:
0
$$
E=\sum \frac{q_{i}\left(r-r_{i}\right)}{4 \pi \epsilon_{0}\left|r-r_{i}\right|^{3}}=9 \times 10^{9} \mathrm{Vm} / C \times\left[\frac{20 \mu C \times \hat{i}}{(1 m)^{2}}+\frac{20 \mu C \times(-\hat{i})}{(1 m)^{2}}\right]=0 \hat{i} V / m
$$
subject: Physics

question: At least two muscles are required to flex and extend at the joint in an animal. Explain why a single muscle cannot act as both flexor and extensor.

answer:

$$

question: A disinfectant is labelled as $36 \mathrm{ppm}$. How was $1 \mathrm{dm} 3$ of this solution prepared starting from the pure disinfectant.

question: Convert a label of a solution of a liquid compound from $240 \mathrm{ppm}$ to \%V/V.

New label is $0.024 \%$ V/V.

question: Give one reason each why the selective removal of some leaves of plants by grazing animals could lead to increase in productivity of some plants.
answer:
a. Nitrogen obtained from the soil by roots no longer needs to be divided among so many leaves. / Reduced competition among parts of the plant for nitrogen
b. The removal of the older dying or even the dead leaves by the grazers decreases shading of younger leaves allowing them to have access to sunlight for photosynthesis. ie Reduction in mutual shading
c. The removal of apical buds by the grazers stimulates lateral buds to become active, thus producing a more heavily branched plant with young and energetic leaves.
d. The transport of sugars and other photosynthetic products from the leaves may be enhanced because the demand for those products in the root is undiminished while the leaves have been decreased
subject: Biology

question: An ideal transformer has a primary-to-secondary turns ratio of $20: 1$. What is the secondary voltage amplitude when the primary voltage amplitude is $220 \mathrm{~V}$ ?
answer: $11 \mathrm{~V} N_{p} / N_{s}=V_{p} / V_{s}$ So $V_{s}=V_{p} \times N_{s} / N_{p}=220 \mathrm{~V} \times 1 / 20=11 \mathrm{~V}$.
subject: Physics

question: An ideal transformer has a primary-to-secondary turns ratio of $40: 1$. What is the current amplitude in the primary coil when the secondary coil delivers alternating current with amplitude 1.6 A?
answer:
$40 m A$
$$
N_{p} / N_{s}=I_{s} / I_{p} \mathrm{so} I_{p}=I_{s} \times N_{s} / N_{p}=1.6 \mathrm{~A} \times 1 / 40=0.04 \mathrm{~A}=40 \mathrm{~mA}
$$
subject: Physics

question: An ideal transformer has a primary-to-secondary turns ratio of $50: 1$. If the secondary supplies $20 \mathrm{~W}$ to a load, what power does the primary consume?
answer: 20 W An ideal transformer has $100 \%$ efficiency so secondary power equals primary power.
subject: Physics

question: Calculate the enthalpy change for hydrogenation of ethyne to ethene from the following bond energies in $\mathrm{kJmol}^{-1} . \mathrm{C} \equiv \mathrm{C} 840 ; \mathrm{C}=\mathrm{C} \quad 610 ; \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{H} \quad 410 ; \mathrm{H}-\mathrm{H} 436$.
answer:
$\mathrm{H}-\mathrm{C} \equiv \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{H} \quad+\quad \mathrm{H}-\mathrm{H} \quad \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{H}_{2}-\mathrm{C} \equiv \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{H}_{2}$
Bonds broken $=\mathrm{C} \equiv \mathrm{C}, \mathrm{H}-\mathrm{H},=840+436=+1276$
Bonds formed $=\mathrm{C}=\mathrm{C}, 2 \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{H}=-610+-2 \mathrm{x} 410=-1430$
Enthalpy change $=1276-1430=-154 \mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}$
subject: Chemistry

question: Calculate the enthalpy change for hydrogenation ethene to ethane from the following bond energies in kJmol-1. $\quad \mathrm{C}=\mathrm{C} \quad 610 ; \quad \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{C} \quad 345 ; \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{H} \quad 410 ; \quad \mathrm{H}-\mathrm{H} 436$.
answer:
$\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{C}=\mathrm{CH}_{2} \quad+\quad \mathrm{H}_{2} \quad \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CH}_{3}$
Bonds broken $=\mathrm{C}=\mathrm{C}, \mathrm{H}-\mathrm{H}=610+436=1046$
Bonds formed $=\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{C}, 2 \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{H}=-345+-2 \times 410=-1165$
Enthalpy change $=1046-1165=-121 \mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}$
subject: Chemistry

question: Calcuate the enthalpy change for hydrogenation propanone to 2-propanol from the following bond energies in kJmol-1. $\mathrm{C}=\mathrm{O}$ 805; $\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{O} 360 ; \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{H} 410 ; \mathrm{O}-\mathrm{H} 464$ $\mathrm{H}-\mathrm{H} 436$.
answer:
$\quad \mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{COCH}_{3}+\mathrm{H}-\mathrm{H} \rightarrow \mathrm{CH}_{3} \mathrm{CHOHCH}_{3}$
Bonds broken $=\mathrm{C}=\mathrm{O}, \mathrm{H}-\mathrm{H}=805+436=1241$
Bonds formed $=\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{O}, \mathrm{C}-\mathrm{H}, \quad \mathrm{O}-\mathrm{H}=-360+-410+-464=-1234$
Enthalpy change $=1241-1234=+7 \mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}$
subject: Chemistry

question: Calculate the mole fraction of argon
answer:
$24 \mathrm{~g}$ of $\mathrm{O}_{2}=24 / 32=0.75 \mathrm{~mol} ; \quad 55 \mathrm{~g}$ of $\mathrm{CO}_{2}=55 / 44=1.25 \mathrm{~mol}$; $56 \mathrm{~g}$ of $\mathrm{N}_{2}=56 / 28=2 \mathrm{~mol}, \quad 40 \mathrm{~g}$ of argon $=40 / 40=1$
mol Total number of moles $=0.75+1.25+3=5$
Hence mol fraction of argon $=1 / 5 \quad=0.2$

question: Calculate the of moles of $\mathrm{NaCl}$ formed
answer:
$HCl + NaOH \rightarrow NaCl + H2O$
Moles of HCl = (300/1000) x 0.15 = 0.045
Moles of NaOH = (200/1000) x 0.20 = 0.040

$R=\rho l / A R=\rho l / A \mathrm{SO}^{R}$ thick $/, R-$ thin. $=A_{\text {thin }} /, A-$ thick. $=d_{\text {thin }}^{2} /, d-$ thick $-\mathbf{2 .}=\mathbf{1 / 4}$
$R_{\text {thick }} /, R-$ thin. $=A_{\text {thin }} /, A-$ thick. $=d_{\text {thin }}^{2} /, d-$ thick $-2 .=1 / 4$
and
$R_{\text {thick }}=R_{\text {thin }} / 4=3 \Omega R_{\text {thick }}=R_{\text {thin }} / 4=3 \Omega$

question: An ammeter has an internal resistance of $5 \Omega$ and full-scale deflection at $10 \mathrm{~mA}$. What shunt resistance is required for full-scale deflection at $\mathbf{1} \mathrm{A}$ ?

question: An ammeter withan internal resistance of $5 \Omega$ and full-scale deflection at $10 \mathrm{~mA}$ is to be used as a voltmeter. What multiplier is required for full-scale deflection at $5 \mathrm{~V}$ ?
answer:
$495 \Omega$
At full scale, the total resistance required for a $5 \mathrm{~V}$ input is $5 \mathrm{~V} / \mathbf{0 . 0 1} \mathrm{A}=500 \Omega$
so the multiplier resistance is $500 \Omega-5 \Omega=495 \Omega$
subject: Physics

question: A voltmeter with internal resistance $1 \mathrm{k} \Omega$ and full-scale deflection of $1 \mathrm{~V}$ is to be used to measure voltages up to $10 \mathrm{~V}$ ? What multiplier is needed?
answer:
$9 \mathrm{k} \Omega$
Current at full scale must be $1 \mathrm{~V} / 1 \mathrm{k} \Omega=0.001 \mathrm{~A}$, so total resistance needed at
$10 \mathrm{~V}$ is $10 \mathrm{~V} / \mathbf{0 . 0 0 1 \mathrm { A }}=10 \mathrm{k} \Omega$, of which $1 \mathrm{k} \Omega$ is internal. The multiplier
resistance is $10 \mathrm{k} \Omega-1 \mathrm{k} \Omega=9 \mathrm{k} \Omega$
subject: Physics

preamble_text: Find the stationary points of the given curve
question: $y=x^{3}-3 x^{2}+6$
answer:
$(0,6)$ and $(2,2)$
$\left[d y / d x=3 x^{2}-6 x=0,3 x(x-2)=0\right.$, hence $x=0, x=2$
For $\mathrm{x}=0, \mathrm{y}=6$ and for $\mathrm{x}=2 \mathrm{y}=8-12+6=2$, points are $(0,6)$ and $(2,2)$ ]
subject: Mathematics

preamble_text: Find the stationary points of the given curve
question: $y=3 x-x^{3}$
answer:
$(1,2)$ and $(-1,-2)$
$\left[d y / d x=3-3 x^{2}=0\right.$, hence $x^{2}=1$, and $x=1, x=-1$
For $\mathrm{x}=1, \mathrm{y}=3-1=2$, and for $\mathrm{x}=-1, \mathrm{y}=-3+1=-2$, points are $(1,2)$ and $(-1,-2)$
subject: Mathematics

preamble_text: Find the stationary points of the given curve
question: $y=x+1 / x$
answer:
$(1,2)$ and $(-1,-2)$
$\left[\mathrm{dy} / \mathrm{dx}=1-1 / \mathrm{x}^{2}=0, \mathrm{x}^{2}=1\right.$ and $\mathrm{x}=1, \mathrm{x}=-1$
For $\mathrm{x}=1, \mathrm{y}=1+1=2$, and for $\mathrm{x}=1, \mathrm{y}=-1+-1=-2$, points are $(1,2)$ and $(-1,-2)]$
subject: Mathematics

40 MJ $40 \mathrm{MJ}$

answer:
$0.1 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}$
Power $=$ burn rate $\times$ heat value $\times$ efficiency $=1 \mathrm{~kW}$ so
burn rate $=1 \mathrm{~kW} \div\left(50 \mathrm{MJ} \mathrm{kg}^{-1} \times 0.2\right)=1 \times 10^{-4} \mathrm{~kg} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}=0.1 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}$

GHS 0.72

question: What is the acceleration of a $5 \mathrm{~kg}$ mass acted on by a horizontal $2 \mathrm{~N}$ force directed to the left and a horizontal $6 \mathrm{~N}$ force directed to the right?
answer:
$0.8 \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~s}^{-2}$ to the right
Net force is $6 \mathrm{~N}-2 \mathrm{~N}=4 \mathrm{~N}$ to the right so acceleration is
$4 \mathrm{~N} / 5 \mathrm{~kg}=0.8 \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~s}^{-2}$.
subject: Physics

question: What is the acceleration of a $2 \mathrm{~kg}$ mass attached by a horizontal inextensible string to a $5 \mathrm{~kg}$ mass which is being pulled to the right by a horizontal $14 \mathrm{~N}$ force?
answer:
$2 \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~s}^{2}$ to the right
The two masses have the same acceleration
$a=F /, m_{\mathbf{1}}+m_{\mathbf{2}}=14 \mathrm{~N} / 7 \mathrm{~kg}=2 \mathrm{~ms}^{-2}$.
subject: Physics

question: A $2 \mathrm{~kg}$ mass is attached by a horizontal inextensible string to a $5 \mathrm{~kg}$ mass which is being pulled to the right by a $14 \mathrm{~N}$ horizontal force. What is the tension in the string?
answer:
$4 \mathrm{~N}$
Acceleration of the $2 \mathrm{~kg}$ mass is $2 \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~s}^{-2}$ and the force on it is
$2 \mathrm{~kg} \times 2 \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~s}^{-2}=4 \mathrm{~N}$, which equals the tension in the string.
subject: Physics

question: The electrode potentials of two half cells $\mathrm{M}^{+} / \mathrm{M}$ and $\mathrm{Q}^{+} / \mathrm{Q}$ (where $\mathrm{M}$ and $\mathrm{Q}$ are metals), are -0.65 and -0.92 volts, respectively. Calculate the initial emf of a cell that can be formed from the half cells. Indicate the anode of the cell.
answer:
$\quad$ Emf $=$ oxidation potential + reduction potential $($ oxd pot $=-$ red pot of same $1 / 2$ cell)
This sum must be positive for a spontaneous reaction
Hence Emf $=+0.92+-0.65=0.27 \mathrm{v}$
Anode (oxidation) hence $\mathrm{Q}$ metal
subject: Chemistry

question: Two half cells, $\mathrm{X}^{+} / \mathrm{X}$ and $\mathrm{Y}^{+} / \mathrm{Y}$ (where $\mathrm{X}$ and $\mathrm{Y}$ are metals) with electrode potentials +0.45 and -0.76 volts respectively are used to construct an electrochemical cell. question: Two half cells, $\mathrm{A}^{+} / \mathrm{A}$ and $\mathrm{B}^{+} / \mathrm{B}$ (where $\mathrm{A}$ and $\mathrm{B}$ are metals) with electrode potentials +0.32 and +0.80 volts respectively are used to construct an electrochemical cell. What will be the initial emf and in which direction will the current flow in the external circuit?
answer:
$\quad \mathrm{Emf}=-0.32++0.80=0.48 \mathrm{v}$
Current flows from oxidation/anode to the reduction/cathode
Hence, current flows from metal A to metal B in the external circuit.
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text: Find the equation of the tangent to the curve $y=f(x)$ at the point on the curve with given $x$-value.
question: $y=x^{3}-3 x^{2}$ at $x=2$
answer: $\mathrm{y}=-4, \quad\left[\mathrm{dy} / \mathrm{dx}=3 \mathrm{x}^{2}-6 \mathrm{x}\right.$, at $\mathrm{x}=2, \mathrm{~m}=12-12=0$, and $\mathrm{y}=8-12=-4$, hence equation of tangent is $(y+4)=0(x-2)$, or $y=-4]$
subject: Mathematics

preamble_text: Find the equation of the tangent to the curve $y=f(x)$ at the point on the curve with given $x$-value.
question: $y=x-1 / x \quad$ at $x=-1$
answer: $\mathrm{y}=2 \mathrm{x}+2\left[\mathrm{dy} / \mathrm{dx}=1+1 / \mathrm{x}^{2}\right.$, at $\mathrm{x}=-1, \mathrm{~m}=1+1=2, \mathrm{y}=-1+1=0$, hence equation of tangent is $y=2(x+1)]$
subject: Mathematics

preamble_text: Find the equation of the tangent to the curve $y=f(x)$ at the point on the curve with given $x$-value.
question: $y=x^{2}-3 x$
answer: $\mathrm{y}=-\mathrm{x}-1 \quad[\mathrm{dy} / \mathrm{dx}=2 \mathrm{x}-3$, at $\mathrm{x}=1, \mathrm{~m}=2-3=-1$, and $\mathrm{y}=1-3=-2$, hence equation of tangent is $(y+2)=-(x-1)$ or $y=-x-1]$
subject: Mathematics

question: The initial rate of decomposition of compound $\mathrm{B}$ was $4.2 \times 10^{-6}$ moldm $^{-3} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}$ when the concentration was $0.0024 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$. When the concentration was increased to 0.0036 moldm ${ }^{-3}$ the initial rate increased to $6.3 \times 10^{-6} \mathrm{moldm}^{-3} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}$. Determine the rate law equation for the reaction.
answer:
$\quad(\text { Rate })_{2} /(\text { Rate })_{1}=\quad\left(\mathrm{k}[\mathrm{B}]_{2} / \mathrm{k}[\mathrm{B}]_{1}\right)^{\mathrm{x}}$ where $\mathrm{x}$ is the order of the reaction
$$
\text { Hence }\left(6.3 \times 10^{-6}\right) /\left(4.2 \times 10^{-6}\right) \quad=\quad(0.0036 / 0.0024)^{\mathrm{x}}
$$
$\begin{array}{llll}9 / 6 & & = & (9 / 6)^{\mathrm{x}} \\ \text { Hence } & x & = & 1\end{array}$
subject: Chemistry

$[v]=\frac{L}{T}=[\rho]^{a}[B]^{b}=\left(\frac{M}{L^{a}}\right)^{a}\left(\frac{M}{L T^{2}}\right)^{b}$ implies $a+b=\mathbf{0},-\mathbf{3} a-b=\mathbf{0}$ and
$-2 b=-1$ so $b=-a=-\frac{1}{2}$
subject: Physics
