Strain $=$ stress $/$ modulus $=10^{7} \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}-2 . \div 0.5 \times 10^{9} \mathrm{~N} / \mathrm{m}-2 .=0.02$ so

0.2\% $0.2 \%$

strain $=$ stress $/$ modulus $=10^{6} \mathrm{~Pa} / 0.5 \times 10^{9} \mathrm{~Pa}=2 \times 10^{-3}=0.2 \%$

question: What is the relative density of a solid that weighs $8 \mathrm{~N}$ in water and $10 \mathrm{~N}$ in air?
answer:
5
Relative density $=$ weight in air $\div$ loss in weight in water $=10 \mathrm{~N} \div(10 \mathrm{~N}-8 \mathrm{~N})=5$.
subject: Physics

question: The relative density of an object is 8 . What is the weight of the object in water if its weight in air is $16 \mathrm{~N}$ ?
answer:
$14 \mathrm{~N}$
Loss in weight in water $=$ weight in air $\div$ relative density $=16 \mathrm{~N} \div 8=2 \mathrm{~N}$ so
weight in water $=16 \mathrm{~N}-2 \mathrm{~N}=14 \mathrm{~N}$.
subject: Physics

question: The relative density of an object is 4 . What is the weight of the object in air if its weight in water is $15 \mathrm{~N}$ ?
answer:
$20 \mathrm{~N}$
Weight in air $=$ Loss in weight in water $\times$ relative density so
weight in air $=[R D \div(R D-1)] \times$ weight in water $=(4 \div 3) \times 15 \mathrm{~N}=20 \mathrm{~N}$
subject: Physics

question: What is the buoyant force on an object of volume $2 \mathrm{~m}^{3}$ and density $8000 \mathrm{kgm}^{-3}$ in a fluid of density $1000 \mathrm{~kg} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}$ where acceleration due to gravity is $10 \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~s}^{-2}$ ?
answer: $20 \mathrm{kN}$ Buoyant force equals weight of fluid displaced, which is $2 \mathrm{~m}^{3} \times 1000 \mathrm{~kg} \mathrm{~m}^{-3} \times 10 \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~s}^{-2}=20000 \mathrm{~N}$.

question: What is the density of an object of volume $2 \mathrm{~m}^{3}$ whose apparent weight is $4000 \mathrm{~N}$ in a fluid of density $1000 \mathrm{~kg} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}$ ? Acceleration due to gravity is $10 \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~s}^{-2}$.
answer: 1200 $\mathrm{kg} \mathrm{m}^{-3}$ Apparent weight is $\left(\rho-\rho_{\text {fluid }}\right) g V$ so density is $1000 \mathrm{~kg} \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}+4000 \mathrm{~N} /, 10 \mathrm{~m} \mathrm{~s}^{-2} \times 2 \mathrm{~m}^{3} .=1200 \mathrm{~kg} \mathrm{~m}^{3}$.

question: $\frac{5 x-1}{x^{2}-1}$
answer:
$\quad \frac{5 x-1}{(x-1)(x+1)}=\frac{A}{x-1}+\frac{B}{x+1}, 5 x-1=A(x+1)+B(x-1)$
$2 /(\mathrm{x}-1)+3(\mathrm{x}+1) \quad \mathrm{x}=1$ gives $4=2 \mathrm{~A}, \mathrm{~A}=2, \quad \mathrm{x}=-1$
$$
\text { gives }-6=-2 B \text { and } B=3 \text { ] }
$$

question: $\frac{2-x}{x^{2}+6 x+8}$
answer:
$\quad \frac{2-x}{x^{2}+6 x+8}=\frac{A}{x+2}+\frac{B}{x+4}, 2-x=A(x+4)+B(x+2)$
$2 /(x+2)-3 /(x+4) \quad x=-2$ gives $4=2 A, A=2, x=-4$
$$
\text { gives } 6=-2 \mathrm{~B}, \mathrm{~B}=-3 \text { ] }
$$

Cell A Anode $\mathrm{O}_{2}$ discharged $2 \mathrm{~F} \equiv \mathrm{O}=1 / 2 \mathrm{O}_{2}$, hence $5 \mathrm{~F} \equiv$ $1 \frac{1}{4} \mathrm{~mol}$ of $\mathrm{O}_{2}$

question: For Cell B the anode is a copper rod weighing $400 \mathrm{~g}$. After what charge in Faradays will the mass of the anode be reduced to $48 \mathrm{~g}$ ?
answer:
Mass of $\mathrm{Cu}$ that had gone into the electrolyte $=400-48=352 \mathrm{~g}$
But $64 \mathrm{~g}$ of $\mathrm{Cu}$ requires $2 \mathrm{~F}$ charge or $32 \mathrm{~g}$ of $\mathrm{Cu}$ requires $1 \mathrm{~F}$
Therefore $160 \mathrm{~g}$ of $\mathrm{Cu}$ will require $(352 / 32)$ x $1 \mathrm{~F}$
$$
=11 \mathrm{~F}
$$

question:
A geometric sequence has second term 24, and fifth term 648. Find the first term and the common ratio. 
$$
\begin{aligned}
& U_{2}=a r=24 \\
& J_{5}=a r^{4}=648
\end{aligned} \quad \therefore \quad r^{3}=\frac{648}{24}=\frac{81}{3}=27 \quad \Rightarrow r=3, a=8
$$
answer: First term a $=8$, common ratio $\mathrm{r}=3\left[U_{5}=a r^{4}=648 \quad \cdots \quad 24 \quad 3 \quad\right.$ ]
subject: Mathematics

question:
A linear sequence (AP) has third term 7 and sixth term 13. Find the first term and the common difference. 
$$
U_{3}=a+2 d
$$
answer: First term $\mathrm{a}=3$, common difference $=2\left[\begin{array}{cll}U_{6}=a+5 d=13 & \therefore 3 d=6 \Rightarrow d=2 \text { and } a=3\end{array}\right]$
subject: Mathematics

It will double (charge remains unchanged; capacitance is halved)
$$
\left[E_{\text {initial }}=\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{Q^{2}}{C}\right) \quad \text { and } E_{\text {initial }}=\frac{1}{2}\left(Q^{\wedge} 2 / C / 2\right)=2 E_{\text {initial }}\right]
$$

preamble_text: A parallel plate capacitor with capacitance $\mathrm{C}$ is charged to a potential difference $\mathrm{V}$ and then isolated.

$$
\left[V_{\text {final }}=\frac{Q}{2 C}=V / 2\right]
$$

question: A rectangular field has a perimeter of 110 metres. The length is 5 metres shorter than thrice the width. Find the dimensions of the field.
answer:
length $=40$ metres width $=15$ metres
$$
\left[\begin{array}{c}
\text { width }=x \\
\text { length }=3 x-5
\end{array} \quad \text { Perimeter }=2 x+2(3 x-5)=110 \quad \therefore 8 x=120 \quad \Rightarrow \quad \begin{array}{c}
x=15 \\
l=45-5=40
\end{array}\right]
$$
subject: Mathematics

question: A rectangular field has a width that is $90 \mathrm{~m}$ less than the length. The perimeter is $1280 \mathrm{~m}$. Find the dimensions of the field.
answer:
length $=365 \mathrm{~m}$, width $=275 \mathrm{~m}$
$$
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
2 L+2(L-90)=1280 & \therefore 4 L=1460 \\
4 L-180=1280 \quad \therefore L=365, W=365-90=275
\end{array}\right]
$$
subject: Mathematics

$(3 x+5 y)(2 x-3 y)$

\begin{aligned}
6 x^{2}+x y-15 y^{2} & =6 x+10 x y-9 x y-15 y^{2} \\
& =2 x(3 x+5 y)-3 y(3 x+5 y) \\
& =(3 x+5 y)(2 x-3 y)
\end{aligned}
$$

question: A balloon contains $16.5 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ of neon at $27.0^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ and $100 \mathrm{kPa}$. If the gas is heated to $72.0^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ while the pressure in the balloon increases to $115 \mathrm{kPa}$, calculate the volume of the balloon under these conditions.
answer:
Using the combined Boyle's and Charles' Laws
$$
\begin{array}{lccc}
\mathrm{P}_{1} \mathrm{~V}_{1} / \mathrm{T}_{1} & =\mathrm{P}_{2} \mathrm{~V}_{2} / \mathrm{T}_{2} ; \quad \mathrm{V}_{2}=\left(\mathrm{P}_{1} / \mathrm{P}_{2}\right) *\left(\mathrm{~T}_{2} / T_{1}\right) * \mathrm{~V}_{1} & \\
\mathrm{P}_{1}= & 100 \mathrm{kPa} ; \mathrm{P}_{2}=115 \mathrm{kPa} ; \\
\mathrm{T}_{1}= & (27.0+273)=300 \mathrm{~K} ; \quad \mathrm{T}_{2}=(72.0+273) \quad=\quad 345 \mathrm{~K} \\
\mathrm{~V}_{2}=(100 / 115) *(345 / 300) * 16.5 \quad= & 16.5 \mathrm{dm}^{3} .
\end{array}
$$
subject: Chemistry

question: Obligatory exchange is a type osmotic exchange that take place between a fish and its environment which is usually in response to physical factors over which the fish has little or no physiological control. Mention one of the four main factors that affect obligatory exchanges
answer:
Gradient between the Extracellular Compartment and the Environment
The greater the ionic difference between the body fluid and external medium, the greater the tendency for net diffusion to low concentrations. Thus, a bony fish in a sea water is affected by the problem of losing water into the hypertonic sea water.
Surface/Volume Ratio
Generally the animal with small body size desiccates (or hydrates) more rapidly than a larger animal of the same shape.
Permeability of the Gills
Fish gills are necessarily permeable to water and solutes as they are the main site of exchange of oxygen and carbon dioxide between the blood and the water. Active transport of salts also takes place in the gills.
Feeding
Fishes take water and solute along with the feeding. A gill takes high quantity of salt than water at the time of feeding on seashore invertebrates, these fishes, therefore, must have some special device to excrete excess of salt. However, a freshwater fish ingests large amount of water than salt and thus needs special means of salt conservation.
subject: Biology

question: Give one disadvantage of transpiration in plants
answer:
Wilting
Wilting reduces photosynthesis and other metabolic activities.
Reduced Growth
Transpiration reduces availability of water inside the plant. Water deficit decreases growth and hence the plant gives a stunted appearance.
Reduced Yield
Decreased availability of water inside the plant checks meristematic activity and hence the formation of flowers, fruits and seeds.
Abscisic Acid
Water stress produces abscisic acid. Abscisic acid prevents several plant processes and promotes abscission of leaves, flowers and fruits.
Wastage of Energy The energy used in absorption and conduction of water goes waste.
Modifications
In order to reduce transpiration during critical periods, the plants produce several types of modifications- thick cuticle, hair, prickles, spines, thorns, sunken stomata, phylloclades, cladodes,
subject: Biology

question: Apart from provision of support, mention one function of a plant cell
answer:
Withstand turgor pressure: Turgor pressure is the force exerted against the cell wall as the contents of the cell push the plasma membrane against the cell wall.
Regulate growth: The cell wall sends signals for the cell to enter the cell cycle in order to divide and grow.
Regulate diffusion: The cell wall is porous allowing some substances, including proteins, to pass into the cell while keeping other substances out.
Communication: Cells communicate with one another via plasmodesmata (pores or channels between plant cell walls that allow molecules and communication signals to pass between individual plant cells).
Protection: The cell wall provides a barrier to protect against plant viruses and other pathogens. It also helps to prevent water loss.
Storage: The cell wall stores carbohydrates for use in plant growth, especially in seeds.
subject: Biology

preamble_text: Use the Kinetic Theory of Gases to explain the following experimental observations:
question: For a given amount of gas at a constant volume, the pressure of the gas increases with temperature.
answer: A postulate of the Theory states that the average kinetic energy of a gas particle depends only on the temperature of the gas; hence the average kinetic energy increases as the gas gets warmer. The higher average kinetic energy means gaseous particles move faster and collide with the wall of its container with greater force, and more frequently, hence increase in pressure.
subject: Chemistry, Physics

preamble_text: Use the Kinetic Theory of Gases to explain the following experimental observations:
question: For a given quantity of a gas, at constant temperature the pressure is inversely proportional to the volume.
answer: As the volume decreases at constant temperature, distances the gaseous molecules have to travel before colliding with the walls of the container decrease hence frequency of collisions increases leading to an increase in pressure.
subject: Chemistry, Physics

question: Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium shows that the gene frequency (the proportion of a particular type of gene in a population) will remain constant if certain conditions occur. Mention one of these conditions
answer:
The size of the population is practically infinite.
Individuals in the population mate at random.
All individuals in the population have the same fitness, regardless of their genes.
There is no gain or loss of genes due to immigration into or emigration out of the population.
There is no new mutation in the population.

question: Give one advantage of cage culture fish when compared to other methods of fish culture
answer:
It requires less investment.
Its installation is easy.
Since it covers only a fraction of the pond, the remaining part can be used in the normal way.
It provides opportunity for controlled culture of choice.
Inspection of fishes and their feeding is much easier.
Treatment of disease is much simple than that of pond culture.
In emergencies it can be removed from one place to another.
Since the cage is meshed, the fishes inside have less chances of being attacked by predators.
Harvesting is very simple.
The number of fish required at a particular time can be harvested and in this way it helps to maintain the non-seasonal supply of the fish.
It is economical as compared to other methods of fish culture except fishculture in running water.
subject: Biology

preamble_text: Find the gradient $d y / d x$ from the implicit equation.
question: $x^{3}-x^{2} y+y^{3}=7 \quad$
answer:
$d y / d x=\left(3 x^{2}-2 x y\right) /\left(x^{2}-3 y^{2}\right)$
$\left[3 x^{2}-2 x y-x^{2} d y / d x+3 y^{2} d y / d x=0,(d y / d x)\left(x^{2}-3 y^{2}\right)=3 x^{2}-2 x y\right.$,
$\left.d y / d x=\left(3 x^{2}-2 x y\right) /\left(x^{2}-3 y^{2}\right)\right]$
subject: Mathematics

preamble_text: Find the gradient $d y / d x$ from the implicit equation.
question: $2 x^{3}+x^{2} y-2 y^{3}=15 \quad$
answer: $d y / d x=\left(6 x^{2}+2 x y\right) /\left(6 y^{2}-x^{2}\right)$ $\left[6 x^{2}+2 x y+x^{2}(d y / d x)-6 y^{2}(d y / d x)=0,(d y / d x)\left(6 y^{2}-x^{2}\right)=\left(6 x^{2}+2 x y\right)\right.$, $\left.d y / d x=\left(6 x^{2}+2 x y\right) /\left(6 y^{2}-x^{2}\right)\right]$

In the commercial preparation of trioxonitrate(V) acid, nitrogen(IV) oxide dissolves in water to give the acid while nitrogen(II) oxide is evolved. The balanced equation for the reaction is as follows:
$3 \mathrm{NO}_{2}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O} \rightarrow 2 \mathrm{HNO}_{3}+\mathrm{NO}$.
$\mathrm{O}=16.0 ; \mathrm{N}=14.0 ; \mathrm{H}=1.00 . \quad$ The molar volume of a gas at STP is $22.4 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$.
question: Calculate the mass of $\mathrm{HNO}_{3}$ that can be produced from $69.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of $\mathrm{NO}_{2}$ gas.
answer:
$3 \mathrm{NO}_{2}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O} \rightarrow 2 \mathrm{HNO}_{3}+\mathrm{NO}$.
$3 \times 46.0$
$138 \mathrm{~g}$ of $\mathrm{NO}_{2} \quad \equiv \quad 126 \mathrm{~g}$ of $\mathrm{HNO}_{3}$
Therefore, mass of $\mathrm{HNO}_{3}$ to be produced from $69.0 \mathrm{~g}$ of NO${ }_{2}=$ $(69.0 / 138)^{*} 126 \mathrm{~g}=63.0 \mathrm{~g}$
subject: Chemistry

preamble_text:
In the commercial preparation of trioxonitrate(V) acid, nitrogen(IV) oxide dissolves in water to give the acid while nitrogen(II) oxide is evolved. The balanced equation for the reaction is as follows:
$3 \mathrm{NO}_{2}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O} \rightarrow 2 \mathrm{HNO}_{3}+\mathrm{NO}$.
$\mathrm{O}=16.0 ; \mathrm{N}=14.0 ; \mathrm{H}=1.00 . \quad$ The molar volume of a gas at STP is $22.4 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$.
question: Find the volume of $\mathrm{NO}_{2}$ at STP that can be used to produce $189 \mathrm{~g}$ of $\mathrm{HNO}_{3}$.
answer:
$3 \mathrm{NO}_{2}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O} \rightarrow 2 \mathrm{HNO}_{3}+\mathrm{NO}$.
Moles of $\mathrm{HNO}_{3}$ in $189 \mathrm{~g}$ of it. $\quad=189 / 63.0=3.00$
Moles of $\mathrm{NO}_{2}$ needed $\quad=(3.00 / 2.00) * 3=4.50$.
Hence volume of $\mathrm{NO}_{2}$ at STP required $=4.50 * 22.4=100.8 \mathrm{dm}^{3}=$
$101 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$
subject: Chemistry

question: If the enthalpies of formation in $\mathrm{kJmol}^{-1}$ of 1-pentyne, 1-pentene and pentane are $+145,-21.0$, and -147 respectively, calculate the enthalpy of hydrogenation of i) 1pentyne to 1-pentene and ii) 1-pentene to pentane. Indicate which reaction is thermodynamically more favourable.
answer:
1-Pentyne $\rightarrow$ 1-pentene
$\Delta r=\Sigma \Delta \mathrm{H}_{\text {products }}-\Sigma \Delta \mathrm{H}_{\text {reactants }}=-21.0-(+145)=-166 \mathrm{~kJ}$
1-Pentene $\rightarrow$ pentane
$\Delta r=\Sigma \Delta \mathrm{H}_{\text {products }}-\Sigma \Delta \mathrm{H}_{\text {reactants }}=-147-(-21.0)=-126 \mathrm{~kJ}$
The reduction from 1-pentyne to 1-pentene is thermodynamically more favourable.
subject: Chemistry

i) cis-2-pentene to pentane and ii) trans-2-pentene to pentane. Indicate which reaction is thermodynamically more favourable and give the reason for that relative order.
answer:
cis-2-Pentene $\rightarrow$ pentane
$\begin{array}{llll}\Delta r \quad-147- & (-28.1) & =-119 \mathrm{~kJ} \\ \text { trans-2-Pentene } \rightarrow & \text { pentane } \\ \Delta r \quad-147-(-31.9) & =-115 \mathrm{~kJ}\end{array}$
Reduction of the cis compound is thermodynamically more favourable.
Reason: The cis compound is less stable/has higher internal energy.

The $\mathrm{IO}_{3}$ ion reacts with the iodide ion in acidic medium according to the following equation:
$1 \mathrm{O}_{3}^{-}+5 \mathrm{I}^{-}+6 \mathrm{H}^{+} \rightarrow 3 \mathrm{I}_{2}+3 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$
The iodine liberated can be titrated against $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{~S}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3}$ solution using starch as indicator. The equation for that reaction is as follows:
$\mathrm{I}_{2}+2 \mathrm{~S}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3}^{2-} \rightarrow 2 \mathrm{I}^{-}+\mathrm{S}_{4} \mathrm{O}_{6}{ }^{2-}$
question: To $20.0 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of $\mathrm{KIO}_{3}$ solution excess $\mathrm{KI}$ solution and dilute $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{SO}_{4}$ are added, and the liberated iodine titrated against $0.400 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$ solution of $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{~S}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3}$. If the titre is $24.0 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$, calculate the concentration in moldm${ }^{-3}$ of the $\mathrm{KIO}_{3}$ solution.
answer:
From equations (1) and (2); $\quad \mathrm{n}\left(\mathrm{IO}_{3}^{-}\right) / \mathrm{n}\left(\mathrm{S}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3}^{2-}\right)=1 / 6$
$(20.0 * M) /(0.400 * 24.0)=\quad 1 / 6 ; \quad M=(0.400 * 24.0) /(6 * 20.0)$
Concentration of $\mathrm{KIO}_{3}$ solution, $\mathrm{M} \quad=\quad 0.0800 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$
subject: Chemistry

question: $\mathrm{H}_{3} \mathrm{PO}_{4}, \mathrm{H}_{3} \mathrm{PO}_{3}, \mathrm{H}^{+} / \mathrm{Pt} \quad-0.276 \mathrm{~V} ; \quad \mathrm{PbO}, \mathrm{OH}^{-} / \mathrm{Pb} \quad-0.576 \mathrm{~V}$.
answer:
Oxid: $\mathrm{Pb}+2 \mathrm{OH}^{-}-2 \mathrm{e} \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{PbO}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O} . \quad+0.576 \mathrm{~V}$
Redu: $\underline{\mathrm{H}}_{3} \underline{\mathrm{PO}}_{4}+2 \mathrm{H}^{+}+2 \mathrm{e} \rightarrow \mathrm{H}_{3} \underline{\mathrm{PO}}_{3}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \underline{\mathrm{O} .} \quad-0.276 \mathrm{~V}$
Cell Rxn: $\underline{\mathrm{H}}_{3} \underline{\mathrm{PO}}_{4}+\mathrm{Pb} \rightarrow \mathrm{H}_{3} \underline{\mathrm{PO}}_{3}+\mathrm{PbO}_{3}$ Initial emf: $\quad 0.576-0.276=\underline{0.300 \mathrm{~V}}$

answer:
Oxid: $\mathrm{NO}_{2}^{-}+2 \mathrm{OH}^{-}-2 \mathrm{e} \rightarrow \mathrm{NO}_{3}^{-}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O} . \quad-0.0100 \mathrm{~V}$
Red: $\mathrm{ClO}_{3}^{-}+\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}+2 \mathrm{e} \rightarrow \mathrm{ClO}_{2}^{-}+2^{-} \quad 2 \mathrm{OH} \cdot{ }^{-} \quad 0.350 \mathrm{~V}$
Cell Rxn: $\quad \mathrm{ClO}_{3}^{-}+\mathrm{NO}_{2}^{-} \rightarrow \mathrm{ClO}_{2}^{-}+\mathrm{NO}_{3}^{-}$.

question:
Methane reacts with chlorine gas in the presence of light to give chloromethane.
Give any one reaction that is either chain initiation step or chain propagation step.
answer:
Chain initiation: chlorine molecule + light to give chlorine radicals.
$$
\mathrm{Cl}_{2}+\text { light } \rightarrow \quad \mathrm{Cl} \cdot
$$
Chain propagation:
i) Chlorine radical + methane molecule to give $\mathrm{HCl}$ molecule and methyl radical.
ii) Methyl radical + Chlorine molecule to give chloromethane and chlorine radical
$$
\mathrm{H}_{3} \mathrm{C} \cdot+\mathrm{Cl}_{2} \rightarrow \mathrm{H}_{3} \mathrm{CCl}+\mathrm{Cl} \cdot
$$
subject: Chemistry

question:
What mass of magnesium tetraoxosulphate(VI) heptahydrate is needed to prepare a $400 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ solution of 0.150 moldm $^{-3}$ concentration?
$\mathrm{Mg}=24.0 ; \mathrm{S}=32.0 ; \mathrm{O}=16.0 ; \mathrm{H}=1.00$
answer:
$\mathrm{MgSO}_{4} \cdot 7 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}=\quad 56.0+64.0+7 * 18.0=120+126=246$
Mass required to prepare $1 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ solution of $0.150 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3} \quad=246^{*} 0.150=36.9 \mathrm{~g}$
Therefore, mass needed for $400 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ solution of $0.150 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}=36.9 * 0.400=14.8 \mathrm{~g}$
subject: Chemistry

question: Calculate the mass of $\mathrm{CuSO}_{4} \cdot 5 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$ needed to prepare a $250 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ solution which is $0.450 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$ with respect to $\mathrm{Cu}^{2+}$ ions. $\mathrm{Cu}=64.0 ; \mathrm{S}=32.0 ; \mathrm{O}=16.0 ; \mathrm{H}=1.00$
answer:
$\quad \mathrm{CuSO}_{4} \cdot 5 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}=96.0+64.0+5 * 18.0=250$
Mass of the compound needed to prepare $1 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ of $0.450 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3} \mathrm{Cu}^{2+}=0.450 * 250$
$=112.5 \mathrm{~g}$
Therefore, mass needed for $250 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}=112.5 / 4=28.1 \mathrm{~g}$
subject: Chemistry

question:
Calculate the mass of sodium trioxocarbonate(IV) decahydrate needed to prepare $500 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ solution which is $0.240 \mathrm{moldm}{ }^{-3}$ with respect to $\mathrm{Na}^{+}$ions.
$\mathrm{Na}=23.0 ; \mathrm{O}=16.0 ; \mathrm{C}=12.0 ; \mathrm{H}=1.00$
answer:
$\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3} \cdot 10 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}=46.0+60.0+180=286$.
$1.00 \mathrm{~mol} \mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3} \cdot 10 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}=2 \mathrm{~mol} \mathrm{Na}+$ ions.
Mass of the compound needed for $1 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ of $0.120 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$ solution $=286 * 0.120=34.32 \mathrm{~g}$
Mass for $500 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$ of $0.240 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$ solution of $\mathrm{Na}^{+}$ions $=34.32 / 2=17.2 \mathrm{~g}$
subject: Chemistry

question:
$2.00 \mathrm{~kg}$ of bauxite after processing yields $714 \mathrm{~g}$ of alumina. What is the percentage aluminum in the bauxite assuming the processing does not lead to any loss of alumina?
$\mathrm{Al}=27.0, \mathrm{O}=16.0$
answer:
Alumina $=\mathrm{Al}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3}=54.0+48.0=102$
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \text { Mass of } \mathrm{Al} \text { in } 714 \mathrm{~g} \text { of alumina }=(54.0 / 102) * 714=378 \mathrm{~g} \text {. } \\
& \% \mathrm{Al} \text { in bauxite }=(378 / 2000) * 100=18.9 \%
\end{aligned}
$$
subject: Chemistry

question: A gold bearing rock is found to contain $3.14^{*} 10^{-2}$ percent of gold. How many grams of gold can be obtained from $15.0 \mathrm{~kg}$ of the rock assuming the processing is $100 \%$ efficient?

question:
Chromium may be obtained by reduction of its oxide $\mathrm{Cr}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3}$ with carbon at high temperatures. If $760 \mathrm{~g}$ of impure oxide yields only $416 \mathrm{~g}$ of chromium, what is the percentage purity of the oxide?
$\mathrm{Cr}=52.0 ; \mathrm{O}=16.0$
answer:
$\mathrm{Cr}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3}=104+48.0=152$;
Hence $\quad 152 \mathrm{~g}$
of $\mathrm{Cr}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3} \equiv 104 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{Cr}$
Therefore, $760 \mathrm{~g}$ of pure $\mathrm{Cr}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{3} \equiv(760 / 152) * 104=520 \mathrm{~g}$
$\mathrm{Cr}$
Therefore, \% purity $=(416 / 520) * 100=80.0 \%$
subject: Chemistry

question: State one of the four common features of enzymes
answer:
Enzymes do not make a reaction occur that would not occur on its own, they just make it happen much faster.
The enzyme molecule is not permanently altered by the reaction. It may be changed transiently, but the enzyme at the end of the reaction is the same molecule it was at the beginning. Therefore, a single enzyme molecule can be used over and over to catalyze the same reaction.
An enzyme can catalyze both the forward and the reverse reaction. One direction may be more favorable than the other, but the unfavorable direction of the reaction can occur.
Enzymes are highly specific for the substrates they bind, meaning they catalyze only one reaction.
subject: Biology

Seeds are transported by the wind, water, or by animals to encourage reproduction and reduce competition with the parent plant.

Also consider the following bond energies all in $\mathrm{kJmol}^{-1} ; \mathrm{N}-\mathrm{H} \quad 386 ; \mathrm{O}-\mathrm{H} \quad 459$;
$$

question: If the energy required to break all the bonds in the combustion is $6,114 \mathrm{~kJ}$, calculate the enthalpy change for the reaction.
answer:
$4 \mathrm{NH}_{3(\mathrm{~g})}+3 \mathrm{O}_{2(\mathrm{~g})} \rightarrow 2 \mathrm{~N}_{2(\mathrm{~g})}+6 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{(\mathrm{g})}$.
Bonds to be formed $=2 \mathrm{~N} \equiv \mathrm{N}+12 \mathrm{O}-\mathrm{H}$.
Energy given out $=-2 * 942+-12 * 459 \quad=\quad-7,392 \mathrm{~kJ}$
Enthalpy of reaction $\quad=\quad-7,392+6,114 \mathrm{~kJ} \quad=\quad-1,278 \mathrm{~kJ}$ or -
$1.28 * 10^{3} \mathrm{~kJ}$
subject: Chemistry

$$

question: In the presence of a platinum catalyst ammonia burns in oxygen to give nitrogen(II) oxide and steam and the balanced equation is as follows: $4 \mathrm{NH}_{3(\mathrm{~g})} \quad+\quad 5 \mathrm{O}_{2(\mathrm{~g})} \rightarrow$ $4 \mathrm{NO}_{(\mathrm{g})}+6 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{(\mathrm{g})}$. If the energy required to break all the necessary bonds is $7,102 \mathrm{~kJ}$ and assuming that the NO molecule contains nitrogen - oxygen double bond, calculate the enthalpy of reaction.
answer:
$4 \mathrm{NH}_{3(\mathrm{~g})}+5 \mathrm{O}_{2(\mathrm{~g})} \rightarrow 4 \mathrm{NO}_{(\mathrm{g})} \quad+\quad 6 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{(\mathrm{g})}$
Bonds to be formed $=4 \mathrm{~N}=\mathrm{O}+12 \mathrm{O}-\mathrm{H}$.
Energy given out $=-4 * 607+-12 * 459=-7,936 \mathrm{~kJ}$
Enthalpy of reaction $=7,102-7,936=-834 \mathrm{~kJ}$

question: Calculate the $\mathrm{pH}$ of 0.100 moldm $^{-3}$ solution of the conjugate base of methanoic acid, if the $\mathrm{pK}_{\mathrm{a}}$ of the acid is 3.76 .
answer:
$\mathrm{pK}_{\mathrm{a}}+\mathrm{pK}_{\mathrm{b}}$ (conjugate base) $=14.0$
$$
\begin{array}{lllll}
\mathrm{pK}_{\mathrm{b}} \text { (Conjugate base) } & =14.0- & 3.76= & 10.2 \\
\mathrm{pOH}=1 / 2 \mathrm{pK}_{\mathrm{b}-} \quad 1 / 2 \log \mathrm{C}_{\mathrm{b}}= & 5.10+0.500 & =5.60 & \\
\text { Hence } \mathrm{pH} \text { of solution of base } & =14.0- & 5.60= & 8.40
\end{array}
$$
subject: Chemistry

question: If the $\mathrm{pH}$ of $0.100 \mathrm{moldm}^{-3}$ solution of a sodium alkanoate, $\mathrm{NaX}$ is 9.20 , calculate the $\mathrm{pK}_{\mathrm{a}}$ of the alkanoic acid $\mathrm{HX}$.
answer:
$\mathrm{pOH}$ of the alkanoate solution $=14.0-9.20=4.80$
But $\mathrm{pOH} \quad=\quad 1 / 2 \mathrm{pK}_{\mathrm{b}}$ (alkanoate) $-\quad 1 / 2 \log \mathrm{C}_{\mathrm{b}}$
Hence $\mathrm{pK}_{\mathrm{b}} \quad=2 * 4.80 \quad-1.00=8.60$
$\mathrm{pK}_{\mathrm{a}}$ of alkanoic acid $=14.0-8.60=5.40$
subject: Chemistry

Lead occurs as sulphide in its ore galena. In the extraction of the metal, the ore is roasted in a stream of oxygen and the balanced equation of the chemical reaction that takes place is as follows:

question: Calculate the mass in $\mathrm{kg}$ of lead(II) oxide to be obtained by the reduction of $23.9 \mathrm{~kg}$ of lead(II) sulphide if the yield is only $90.0 \%$.
answer:
$2 \mathrm{PbS}+3 \mathrm{O}_{2} \rightarrow 2 \mathrm{PbO}+\quad 2 \mathrm{SO}_{2}$
$2 * 239$
Mass in $\mathrm{kg}$ of $\mathrm{PbO}$ expected from $23.9 \mathrm{~kg}$ of $\mathrm{PbS}=22.3 \mathrm{~kg}$
Actual yield $=0.900 * 22.3 \quad=\quad 20.1 \mathrm{~kg}$

question: Give one similarity between reversible and irreversible enzyme inhibition
answer:
Reversible and irreversible enzyme inhibition are two types of enzyme inhibition mechanisms.
They are responsible for reducing the activity of the enzyme.
Usually, they reduce the compatibility of the enzyme to its substrate, inhibiting the formation of the enzyme-substrate complex.
During inhibition, inhibitor molecules bind to the enzyme either temporarily or permanently.
Naturally, enzyme inhibition helps to regulate metabolism. Also, many drug molecules are enzyme inhibitors.

question: Values of the first ionisation energies for the first 20 elements (hydrogen to calcium) show several clear patterns. State any one of them and give reasons for that pattern.
answer:
The first ionisation energy (IE) generally increases appreciably as we go across a Period.
Across a Period, the effective nuclear charge increases, and the atomic radius decreases. Hence it becomes more difficulty to remove an electron from the valence shell.
There is a gradual decrease of the first ionisation energy as we go down a Group.
Down a Group, atomic radius increases hence the attractive force of the nucleus on the outermost electrons decreases. It becomes easier to remove an electron from the valence shell.
There are minor exceptions in a Period. e.g. Be, B or $\mathrm{N}, \mathrm{O}$ or $\mathrm{Mg}, \mathrm{Al}$
Relative Stability of the electron configuration becomes significant in some instances. Removing an electron to give a half- or fully-filled subshell like $B$ or $O$ respectively is more favourable despite higher effective nuclear charge and smaller atomic radius than removing an electron from half- or fully-filled sub-shell like $\mathrm{N}$ or Be.
There is a big drop in the first ionisation (IE) as we go from the end of one period to the beginning of the next period Reason: The end of a Period is occupied by an inert gas. Its atoms have fully filled shells and hence possess very stable electronic configuration and high ionisation potential. The element next after an inert gas is an element that begins a new Period and will have a valence shell of $\mathrm{ns}^{1}$. Losing that electron will be thermodynamically very favourable.
subject: Chemistry

question: Calculate the volume of oxygen gas at STP that would be formed after passing 7.00 Faraday of charge during the electrolysis of dilute $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{SO}_{4}$ using inert electrodes.
answer:
$2 \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}-4 \mathrm{e}=\mathrm{O}_{2}+4 \mathrm{H}^{+} ;$Hence $4.00 \mathrm{~F}=$ $22.4 \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ of $\mathrm{O}_{2}$ at STP
Hence 9.00Faraday $=(7.00 / 4)^{*} 22.4 \mathrm{dm}^{3} \quad=\quad 39.2 . \mathrm{dm}^{3}$ of $\mathrm{O}_{2}$ at STP
subject: Chemistry

question:
Find the mass of hydrogen gas that would be formed after passing 21.0 Faraday charge in the electrolysis of dilute $\mathrm{NaCl}$ solution using inert electrodes.
$$
H=1.00
$$
answer:
At the cathode: $2 \mathrm{H}^{+}+2 \mathrm{e}=\mathrm{H}_{2}$; Hence $2.00 \mathrm{~F}=$ $2.00 \mathrm{~g}$ of $\mathrm{H}_{2}$.
$$
\text { Hence } 21.0 \mathrm{~F}=(21.0 / 2 .) * 2.00 \quad=\quad 21.0 \mathrm{~g} \mathrm{of} \mathrm{H}_{2} \text {. }
$$

question: 1. I am a three digits odd number between 100 and 200. The product of all my digits is a 2 digit odd cube. 2. My digits are distinct. 3. The sum of my digits is 13. 4. My last digit is an exact square. 5. My digits form an increasing exponential sequence. Who am I?
subject: Mathematics

question: 1. I am sensitive to external pressure including atmospheric pressure.  2. I am also sensitive to the presence of a second substance. 3. Although I am usually referred to as a point, I am presented as a range. 4. I am a property of all substances, especially liquids. Who am I?
subject: Physics

question: 1. I am a four digit number. 2. I am an even number with even digits. 3. My first and last digits are identical. 4. My second and third digits are also identical. My first digit is a prime. 5. My second digit is the square of the first digit. Who am I?
subject: Mathematics

question: 1. I am a device for energy conversion. I operate between two temperatures. 2. The efficiency with which I convert energy depends on the temperatures between which I operate. 3. I convert energy of disordered motion to an ordered form of energy. Who am I?
subject: Physics

question: 1. In physics, I am one of the fundamental states of matter. 2. To the biologist, I am the pale-yellow liquid component of blood. Who am I?
subject: Physics

question: 1. I am a field particle. 2. As such I mediate one of the known interactions. 3. Like all field particles, I am a boson. 4. I mediate a long range interaction. 5. I am an uncharged spin 1 particle. 6. I am the particle that accounts for the fact that your seat supports you against gravity. Who am I?
subject: Chemistry

question: 1. I am sometimes described as a rare element but I am more abundant in the Earth crust than sulphur and lead. 2. I am a soft transition metal and named after the first mythical sons of the Earth. 3. I have a high strength to weight ratio and so I am useful in the aircraft industry.  4. I am the second element of the first d-transition series. Who am I?
subject: Chemistry

question: 1. I am a genus of common saprobic fungi. 2. I can be seen with the naked eye as a white fluffy mass. 3. My members are collectively referred to as pin moulds. 4. I grow rapidly on moist decaying bread, fruits and other organic matter. Who am I?
subject: Biology

question: 1. I am a compound statement. 2. I literally add two simple statements together. 3. I am true only if both component simple statements are true. I am partly a junction. 4. I may be mistaken for a con. 5. I am of the form p and q. Who am I?
subject: Mathematics

question: 1. I am a binary operation on a set of subsets. 2. Mind you there are two of us with quite similar properties. I have an identity which is quite an empty boast. 3. I normally combine two sets to create a large set. 4. My name suggests I am a marriage of convenience. Who am I?
subject: Mathematics

question: 1. My name was first coined by Theodor Schwann in the early 19th century. 2. He coined my name from a Greek word meaning digestion. 3. I am one of three principal protein-degrading, or proteolytic, enzymes in the digestive system. I am stored at very low temperatures to prevent autolysis (self digestion). 4. I am secreted in an inactive form known as pepsinogen. Who am I?
subject: Biology

question: 1. I am a common chemical process found in nature, laboratory and industry. I am one of a set of twins. 2. I and my twin love each other so much that we are always together. 3. But in any conversation and action we oppose each other. 4. In terms of acquisition of property, while I am always bringing something home, my twin is rather giving out family property. 5. We are visible when hydrocarbons burn in air or rusting of iron is taking place. Who am I?
subject: Chemistry

question: 1. I am a physical quantity. 2. I am determined by force and area 3. I am measured in Pascals 4. I am given by the product of modulus and strain. Who am I?
subject: Physics

question: 1. I am a polygon. 2. The sum of my interior angles is two straight angles. 3. That makes me a quadrilateral. 4. I am equiangular but not equilateral. 5. My diagonals bisect each other but are not perpendicular. My adjacent sides are perpendicular. Who am I?
subject: Mathematics

question: 1. I am a law with a difference. 2. I manifest with the help of a medium. 3. In a way I mean direct proportionality of two related terms. I am associated with electricity. 4. My unit is characterised by the Omega symbol. Who am I?
subject: Physics

question: 1. I am a red inorganic compound with a melting point of 196^{o}C. 2. I am also an acidic oxide with metal and oxygen as my constituent elements. 3. I am a powerful oxidising agents, especially to organic compounds. 4. Since I am an anhydride, I dissolve in water to give a very strong acid. I dissolve in water to give a very strong acid which is also a powerful oxidising agent. 5. It is not surprising because my metal is in an oxidation state of +6. 6. Steel electroplated with my metal has a bright appear- ance and is more resistant to corrosion. Who am I?
subject: Chemistry

question: 1. I am an elemental metal known to the ancient man and woman. 2. My scientific name from which my symbol is obtained is in Latin. 3. I do not occur in nature in the Free State but as a com- ponent of an ore known as CASSITERITE. Who am I?
subject: Chemistry

question: 1. Apart from a point or a segment, I am the simplest geometrical figure. 2. I am an open figure. 3. I may be acute, obtuse or reflex. 4. I am the union of two rays with a common vertex. I am measured in degrees and radians. 5. I may be a point of view or a way of looking at a problem. Who am I?
subject: Mathematics

question: 1. I am a type of electric circuit. 2. I am named for a hinged device whose function is to close an opening. 3. I am characterized by a set of inputs whose states determine my output. 4. My simplest kind has only one input and one output. 5. I am the electrical realization of the operators in Boolean algebra. 6. Everything about me is logical. Who am I?
subject: Physics

question: 1. I am a physical quantity you may have first encountered in your study of mechanics. 2. I have dimensions of work. 3. But the joule is not my SI unit. 4. I quantify the turning effect of a force. 5. I am to force what angular momentum is to linear momentum. Who am I?
subject: Physics
